<|user|>
I have a model to forecast certain time series using cointegration. My residuals look like this:
[](https://i.stack.imgur.com/ToIxr.png)
Clearly not normal, but somewhat bell-shaped and with some left skewness and extra kurtosis.
How can I include this information of my errors in the model to improve the forecasts?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
There are a couple of ways to utilize this information about your errors to improve your model.  

1. **Nonlinear Transformation**: If your errors are not normally distributed, it might be because the relationship between your inputs and the output variable is not linear. You can consider applying a transformation to your input data or to the output variable itself. Popular transformations include logarithmic, square root, or power transformations. 

2. **Non-Gaussian error distribution**: If your errors still exhibit non-normality even after transformation, you might need to consider models that have more flexibility in terms of the error distribution. For instance, Generalized Linear Models (GLMs) allow you to specify the distribution of the residuals.

3. **Use a different loss function**: If outliers (which often cause skewness and heavy tails) are common in your data, you may want to use a model that is less sensitive to outliers. This might mean using a loss function other than mean squared error, such as mean absolute error. 

4. **GARCH**: If the extra kurtosis is due to volatility clustering (common in financial time series), a GARCH model might be appropriate. This type of model allows for changing variances over time, which can account for this sort of behaviour.

5. **Non-parametric and semi-parametric models**: Non-parametric and semi-parametric models don't make assumptions about the form of the error distribution, which makes them more flexible and robust to non-normality of residuals.

Bear in mind that the best course of action may depend heavily on the specific application and dataset. It can be worthwhile to experiment with different strategies to see what works best for your situation.
  
Just one final note: if the residuals are autocorrelated, you may need to use a model that accounts for this, like autoregressive or moving average errors. Any model assuming independent residuals would be inappropriate in this case.
<|end|>


