<|user|>
Create a SQL query to find all users from the “users” table who have a last name of “Smith” and whose accounts were created within the last 365 days. Additionally, sort the results by their first name in ascending order and paginate the results to show 10 records per page.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Assuming the table has a "created_at" field for the date the account was created and "first_name", "last_name" fields for the users' names.

Here is an example query for retrieving the first page:

```sql
SELECT * 
FROM users 
WHERE last_name = "Smith" 
AND created_at > DATE_SUB(CURRENT_DATE, INTERVAL 1 YEAR) 
ORDER BY first_name ASC 
LIMIT 10;
```

If you need to get subsequent pages, you would need to use the OFFSET keyword to skip the records from the previous pages. Here is an example for getting the second page:

```sql
SELECT * 
FROM users 
WHERE last_name = "Smith" 
AND created_at > DATE_SUB(CURRENT_DATE, INTERVAL 1 YEAR) 
ORDER BY first_name ASC 
LIMIT 10 OFFSET 10;
```

Just increase the OFFSET by 10 for each subsequent page. Note that database indexes would significantly help the performance of these queries if your users table is large and/or if you need to retrieve records from far into the pagination.
<|end|>


