But in NSIS ([http://nsis.sourceforge.net/](http://nsis.sourceforge.net/))
<|end|>
<|asst|>
In NSIS, you may accomplish this task using the RecFind command provided by the NSIS library. Remember to include the FileFunc.nsh and TextFunc.nsh plugins.

Here's a simple script that accomplishes the same thing:

```
!include "FileFunc.nsh"
!include "TextFunc.nsh"

Var fileHandle

Section

; Open a file for writing
FileOpen $fileHandle "C:\files.txt" a

; Call the RecFind function to enumerate all .exe files in C:\ and subdirectories
${RecFind} "C:\" "*.exe" "/r" "callback" "" ""

; Close the opened file
FileClose $fileHandle

SectionEnd

Function callback

; Fetch the long file name (full path)
${GetLongPath} $0 $R9

; Call a custom function to get additional details (if needed)
; Call GetFileDetails

; Write the path to the opened file.
FileWrite $fileHandle "$0$\r$\n"

FunctionEnd
```

This will write the full path of all *.exe files in C:\ and its subdirectories to a file named files.txt. If you wish to get more details about each file, you would need to implement your own GetFileDetails function which is not built-in NSIS and can be quite complex. Note that this will append to the file if it already exists, creating a new one if it doesn't.
<|end|>


