Craft an SQL query that, when executed, will generate a visual representation showcasing the distribution of customers across various cities by enumerating their respective totals.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Though SQL is typically used for data management and manipulation, it doesn't inherently support visualizations such as charts or graphs. However, first you can fetch the data using SQL and then represent this data using any visualization software like Tableau, Power BI, Google Data Studio etc.

Below is the SQL query to get the data:

```sql
SELECT City, COUNT(*) AS Customer_Total
FROM Customers
GROUP BY City
ORDER BY Customer_Total DESC;
```

This code first SELECTs the names of the cities from your "Customers" table. 
COUNT(*) is a function that will tally up the total number of customers in each city.
FROM Customers identifies the table we're working with. 
GROUP BY City will classify the results according to the city names.
ORDER BY Customer_Total DESC, finally, will order the output from the city with the highest number of customers to the lowest.

Once you retrieve this data, you can use a suitable visualization tool to generate a bar chart, pie chart, or any other appropriate visual representation of the data. Be sure to select the relevant options in your visualization tool to use 'City' as the dimension, and 'Customer_Total' as the measure.
