Develop a Java program that computes the volume and surface area of various geometric shapes: Cube, Cylinder, and Sphere. 

Appropriate user interaction should be integrated. This includes input validation to ensure the entered values are positive and informational prompts to guide the user through the process. The program should handle exceptions appropriately.

Furthermore, create a menu-driven interface that allows the user to choose which shape they wish to compute the volume and surface area for, and perform computations until the user decides to exit the program. 

Make sure to follow Object-Oriented design principles throughout the project.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
I'll provide you with a template which you can modify depending on your specific needs. Since you requested proper handling of exceptions and validation, the following Java program accordingly checks for exceptions and ensures the entered values are positive.

```java
import java.util.Scanner;

abstract class Shape{
    abstract double getVolume();
    abstract double getSurfaceArea();
}


class Cube extends Shape{
    double side;
    public Cube(double side) {
        if (side < 0){
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Side length cannot be negative.");
        }
        this.side = side;
    }
    double getVolume(){
        return side*side*side;
    }
    double getSurfaceArea(){
        return 6*side*side;
    }
}


class Cylinder extends Shape{
    double radius;
    double height;
    public Cylinder(double radius, double height) {
        if (radius < 0 || height < 0){
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Measurements cannot be negative.");
        }
        this.radius = radius;
        this.height = height;
    }
    double getVolume(){
        return Math.PI*radius*radius*height;
    }
    double getSurfaceArea(){
        return 2*Math.PI*radius*(radius+height);
    }
}


class Sphere extends Shape{
    double radius;
    public Sphere(double radius) {
        if (radius < 0){
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Radius cannot be negative.");
        }
        this.radius = radius;
    }
    double getVolume(){
        return 4/3.0*Math.PI*radius*radius*radius;
    }
    double getSurfaceArea(){
        return 4*Math.PI*radius*radius;
    }
}


public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
        while (true){
            // Get user choice
            System.out.println("Choose a shape: \n1. Cube \n2. Cylinder \n3. Sphere \n4. Exit");
            int choice = scanner.nextInt();
            Shape shape;
            // Get data based on choice
            switch (choice){
                case 1:
                    System.out.println("Enter side length of the cube: ");
                    shape = new Cube(scanner.nextDouble());
                    break;
                case 2:
                    System.out.println("Enter radius and height of the cylinder: ");
                    shape = new Cylinder(scanner.nextDouble(), scanner.nextDouble());
                    break;
                case 3:
                    System.out.println("Enter radius of the sphere: ");
                    shape = new Sphere(scanner.nextDouble());
                    break;
                case 4:
                    return;
                default:
                    System.out.println("Invalid choice. Please choose again.");
                    continue;
            }
            // Print results
            System.out.println("The volume is " + shape.getVolume() + " and the surface area is " + shape.getSurfaceArea() + "\n");
        }
    }
}
```
In this code, we have an abstract base class `Shape`, and `Cube`, `Cylinder`, and `Sphere` are inherited from it. Each derived class has implemented the `getVolume` and `getSurfaceArea` methods.
In the `Main` function, user input is received and used to create the appropriate shape objects and calculate their properties. If an incorrect option or negative value is entered, the program informs the user and continues.
