<|asst|>
Here is the Java version for the Python script you provided:

```java
public String findClosestVowelSubsequence(String word) {
    String vowels = "aeiouAEIOU";
    String[] pairs = {"ea", "ei", "ie", "ai", "ay", "ae", "ei", "ie", "oy", "au", "eu", "ui", "uo", "oa", "oA", "oi", "oe", "uA", "io", "eo", "ia", "ei"};
    StringBuilder reversedWord = new StringBuilder(word).reverse();
    String result = "";
    for (int i = 1; i < reversedWord.length()-1; i++) {
        // Check for single vowel nestled between two consonants
        if (vowels.indexOf(reversedWord.charAt(i)) != -1 &&
            vowels.indexOf(reversedWord.charAt(i-1)) == -1 && 
            vowels.indexOf(reversedWord.charAt(i+1)) == -1) {
            result = String.valueOf(reversedWord.charAt(i));
            break;
        // Check for vowel pair nestled between two consonants
        } else if (Arrays.asList(pairs).contains((new StringBuilder(reversedWord.substring(i, i+2))).reverse().toString().toLowerCase()) &&
                    vowels.indexOf(reversedWord.charAt(i-1)) == -1 &&
                    vowels.indexOf(reversedWord.charAt(i+2)) == -1) {
            result = (new StringBuilder(reversedWord.substring(i, i+2))).reverse().toString();
            break;
        }
    }
    return result;
}
```

Please note that in Python, 'x in y' means checking if 'x' is a member of 'y'. In Java, you can achieve it with 'y.indexOf(x) != -1'. Also, in Python slicing 'y[x:x+2]' is pretty direct and easy, but in Java we need to write it as 'y.subSequence(x, x+2)'. The other parts are Java format of loops, and conditional statements which are very similar to those in Python.
<|end|>


