Updating the table can be performed by using SQL queries if your data is stored in a relational database like MySQL, PostgreSQL, or Oracle. Here are the steps you can follow:
1. Get a connection to your database.
2. Prepare an update statement.
3. Execute the update.
In Java, you can do something like the following:

```java
import java.sql.Connection;
import java.sql.DriverManager;
import java.sql.PreparedStatement;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        String url = "jdbc:myDriver:myDatabase";
        String username = "username";
        String password = "password";

        try {
            Connection conn = DriverManager.getConnection(url, username, password);

            String sql = "UPDATE myTable SET dateField = ? WHERE accountId = ?";
            PreparedStatement pstmt = conn.prepareStatement(sql);

            // Assuming `newDate` is the new Date you want to set and `accountId` is the id of the account.
            pstmt.setDate(1, newDate);
            pstmt.setInt(2, accountId);

            int rowsUpdated = pstmt.executeUpdate();
            if (rowsUpdated > 0) {
                System.out.println("An existing account was updated successfully!");
            }

        } catch (SQLException e) {
            System.out.println(e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

Please replace `myDriver`, `myDatabase`, `myTable`, `dateField`, and `accountId` with your actual driver name, database name, table name, date field, and account id field. The `newDate` should also be replaced with the new date you want to put in your database.

This is a very basic way of updating a record in a table. Depending on your actual requirements and context, you would need to adjust the query and the logic. 

Also, note that working directly with JDBC can be cumbersome for more complex cases and you might want to consider using a higher-level library or framework, like Spring Data JPA or Hibernate.

Last but not least, always make sure to close your resources (in this case, the PreparedStatement and Connection), preferably in a finally block or by using a try-with-resources statement. For example:
```java
try (Connection conn = DriverManager.getConnection(url, username, password);
     PreparedStatement pstmt = conn.prepareStatement(sql)) {
    ...
} catch (SQLException e) {
    ...
}
```
In this case, the resources will be automatically closed at the end of the statement. This ensures that your resources are always properly closed, even if an exception occurs.
