<|user|>
Write an HTML code to create a form with input fields for name, age, email address, phone number, and an option for gender selection. The form should include client-side validation to check the integrity of the input data. E.g., the name and age fields should not be empty, the email should be correctly formatted, the phone number should only contain numeric values and the gender must be selected. Also, make sure to disable the submit button until all fields are valid.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
HTML doesn't support client-side validation alone. To provide client-side data validation, JavaScript should be used alongside HTML. Here is a sample form with validation,

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Form Validation</title>
</head>
<body>
    <form id="myForm" onsubmit="return validateForm()">
        Name: <input type="text" id="name"><br>
        Age: <input type="text" id="age"><br>
        Email: <input type="text" id="email"><br>
        Phone: <input type="text" id="phone"><br>
        
        Gender:<br>
        <input type="radio" id="male" name="gender" value="male"> Male<br>
        <input type="radio" id="female" name="gender" value="female"> Female<br>
        
        <input id="submitButton" type="submit" value="Submit" disabled>
    </form>

    <script>
        function validateForm() {
            var name = document.getElementById('name').value;
            var age = document.getElementById('age').value;
            var email = document.getElementById('email').value;
            var phone = document.getElementById('phone').value;
            var gender = document.querySelector('input[name="gender"]:checked');
            
            if(!name || !age || !email || !phone || !gender) {
                alert("All fields must be filled out");
                return false;
            }

            var re = /\S+@\S+\.\S+/;
            if(!re.test(email)) {
                alert("Email format is incorrect");
                return false;
            }

            if(isNaN(phone)) {
                alert("Phone number must only contain numbers");
                return false;
            }

            return true;
        }

        document.getElementById('myForm').addEventListener('input', function() {
            var name = document.getElementById('name').value;
            var age = document.getElementById('age').value;
            var email = document.getElementById('email').value;
            var phone = document.getElementById('phone').value;
            var gender = document.querySelector('input[name="gender"]:checked');

            if(name && age && email && phone && gender){
                document.getElementById('submitButton').disabled = false;
            } else{
                document.getElementById('submitButton').disabled = true;
            }
        });
    </script>

</body>
</html>
```
This example form validates an email via a simple regular expression. It simply checks that the email contains something of the form text@text.text. For more comprehensive email validation, a more complex regular expression would be needed.

This code also sets up an event listener that runs on every change in one of the form's inputs and checks if all the inputs are filled out. If they are, the submit button is enabled. If not, the submit button remains disabled. When the form is submitted, the validateForm function checks all the inputs again and gives specific error messages if something is wrong.

Please keep in mind that while client-side validation can create a good user experience, server-side validation is always required too. It's quite easy to submit data to a server bypassing the form, and so client-side validation.
<|end|>


