Write a C# code to extract data from an XML element.
<employees>
  <employee>
    <name>John Doe</name>
    <age>34</age>
  </employee>
  <employee>
    <name>Jane Doe</name>
    <age>27</age>
  </employee>
</employees>
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a simple code snippet on how to extract data from an XML using C# with the help of the `System.Xml.Linq` namespace.

```csharp
using System;
using System.Xml.Linq;

public class Program
{
    public static void Main()
    {
        string xmlData = @"
        <employees>
            <employee>
                <name>John Doe</name>
                <age>34</age>
            </employee>
            <employee>
                <name>Jane Doe</name>
                <age>27</age>
            </employee>
        </employees>";

        XDocument doc = XDocument.Parse(xmlData);

        foreach (var employee in doc.Descendants("employee"))
        {
            string name = employee.Element("name")?.Value;
            string age = employee.Element("age")?.Value;

            Console.WriteLine($"Name: {name}, Age: {age}");
        }
    }
}
```

In this code, we first parse the XML data into an `XDocument` object. We then loop through each `employee` element in the XML and extract the `name` and `age` sub-elements, printing their values to the console.
