The current behavior of your function is that it only checks the first string of the array (arr[0]) and the first letter of each string in the array (in this case, "Hello"). That's why it only returns `true` for "H" or "h". It is now only comparing the first letter of the first string in your array but you probably want to compare all the letters of all strings.

If you want to check if *any* string in `arr` contains `charr`, you can change your function like this:

```javascript
function contains(arr, charr) {
  for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    if (arr[i].toLowerCase().includes(charr.toLowerCase())) {
      return true;
    }
  }
  return false;
}

let arr2 = ["Hello"];
console.log(contains(arr2, "e")) // should return true
```

In this new version, it will correctly return `true` when you call `contains(arr2, "e")`, because it checks the entire string "Hello", and checks every string in the array, if there are more than one. This version uses the `.includes()` method which checks if a string contains another string. 

Please note that the `includes()` function is case sensitive. The `.toLowerCase()` method is used here to make sure the comparison is not case sensitive. If you want it to be case sensitive, you can remove the two `.toLowerCase()` methods.
