I am trying to create some API tests for Azure Functions Apps.
For the API to work properly it needs an azure storage account.
I create a docker-compose file with
- - - 
Everything works pretty smooth, until the API tries to access the storage. Then the storage returns 403 for my check if a file exists.
I created a script on my local system (not inside docker) that does exactly the same thing with exactly the same connection string and the same version of @azure/storage-blob (12.12.0)
"From the outside" my script works, but "from the inside" (docker-networks) it doesn't even though I can see the request being processed by azurite (it logs the incoming request)
I already tried using the name of the container, assigning a domainname (azurite.com) and using the internal and external ip of the system running the docker, but it all fails.
Can anybody offer any advice?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The issue you're facing might be related to how Azure Storage Emulator (Azurite) needs to be set up within a Docker environment. When running Azure Blob Storage on an Azurite Docker instance, you need to ensure your Azure Storage Account connection string is correctly configured.

In Docker, Azurite runs on `localhost` (127.0.0.1) by default. If you are using `localhost` as the Blob Storage endpoint within your Azure Function, it won't work because `localhost` inside the Docker network is isolated from the host machine's network where Azurite is running.

Here are some steps you can take to resolve the issue:

1. Set your Azure Storage Account connection string to point to Azurite's mapped ports on your host machine's IP (not localhost or 127.0.0.1). This would look something like this: `DefaultEndpointsProtocol=http;BlobEndpoint=http://<DOCKER_HOST_IP>:10000/devstoreaccount1;QueueEndpoint=http://<DOCKER_HOST_IP>:10001/devstoreaccount1;TableEndpoint=http://<DOCKER_HOST_IP>:10002/devstoreaccount1;`

2. Use the `--network host` option when running the Docker command for your Azure Functions project. This will ensure that your Azure Functions Docker container uses the same networking as the host machine.

3. If you are using docker-compose, you may need to use the service name as the hostname instead of `localhost` or the docker host IP.

4. If you're still having issues, check that your Azurite container is running correctly and that the ports are correctly exposed. You can do this with a tool like Postman to make a test request to the blob storage API.

Remember that Azurite only supports local emulator account credentials, namely, Account name: `devstoreaccount1`, Account key: `Eby8vdM02xNOcqFlqUwJPLlmEtlCDXJ1OUzFT50uSRZ6IFsuFq2UVErCz4I6tq/K1SZFPTOtr/KBHBeksoGMGw==`.
<|end|>


