<|asst|>
The issue occurs because you are setting the timeout in the wrong place. In puppeteer, the timeout option should be set at the `goto` or `waitUntil` commands, not in the `launch` command. 

Here's an example of how to set the timeout option:

```javascript
const page = await browser.newPage();
await page.goto('http://your-url.com', {timeout: 0});
```

Also, if you are doing page navigation or waiting for elements you need to use the same setting:

```javascript
await page.waitForSelector('.selector',{timeout: 0}) 
```

The `timeout: 0` parameter disables the timeout. This might solve your problem.

>The navigator could be slower depending on the proxies speed. If the speed of the proxy you use is slow this could cause time outs. If you need to use specific proxies, the only possible solution is to disable the timeout as shown above.

Remember to handle errors in your code using try-catch blocks, this way your browser won't close unexpectedly. If you use timeout: 0 your script could hang indefinitely if it gets stuck.

Also, always check if the problem persists without using proxies. A bad proxy can cause various problems when using puppeteer.
<|end|>


