You can add a single dot to your scatterplot by using the `fig.add_trace()` function to add a new scatterplot with a single point. 

First calculate the median of the columns you're interested in and save those into variables.

Then use `go.Scatter` (from `plotly.graph_objects`) to create a single point scatterplot, and finally add this to your figure using `fig.add_trace()`. Here is an example:

```python
import plotly.graph_objects as go

# Make sure you have calculated your median x and y values before this
median_x = df_b['EAD'].median()
median_y = df_b['RAR'].median()

# Create the single-point scatter plot
dot = go.Scatter(x=[median_x], y=[median_y], mode='markers',
                 marker=dict(color='red', size=10), name='Median point')

# Add it to the figure
fig.add_trace(dot)
```

Here, 'markers' specifies that we only want to plot dots,  and 'red' is the color of our dot. 'size' specifies how big our dot is, where 10 is a default size. Finally, 'name' sets the name of our trace, which will show up in the legend of your plot.

Next, `add_trace(dot)` is used to add this scatter plot to your existing figure. Plotly figures can contain multiple traces, so this just adds it on top of your existing scatterplot. The coordinates of your single point will be in the same scale as your original scatterplot, so it'll appear exactly where you want it. The point won't be interactive in the same way as the original scatter plot points, but it will appear in the legend and be hoverable.
<|end|>


