Develop a sophisticated ReactJS module capable of receiving a video file as an input for upload purposes, after which it will intelligently exhibit a brief preview sneak peek of the video data that has been successfully uploaded.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Developing a full ReactJS module for this task is complex, requiring a lot of code and a strong understanding of ReactJS, state management and dealing with file input. Also, a real code implementation always depends on the specific project structure and requirements.

Here's a basic example of how such a module might be structured using React:

```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';

const VideoUploadPreview = () => {
  const [videoSource, setVideoSource] = useState(null);

  const handleVideoUpload = (e) => {
    const file = e.target.files[0];
    if(file) {
      setVideoSource(URL.createObjectURL(file));
    }
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <input type="file" accept="video/*" onChange={handleVideoUpload} />
      
      {videoSource ? (
        <video controls width="500" preload='metadata'>
          <source src={videoSource} type="video/webm" />
        </video>
      ) : null}
    </div>
  );
};

export default VideoUploadPreview;
```

In this component:

1. We define a `useState` hook to keep track of the selected video's source.
2. The `handleVideoUpload` function updates our state when a new file is selected in the input field.
3. We conditionally render a video player with the selected source whenever a video is chosen.

To see a 5 second snippet of the video when it's uploaded, you can manipulate the start and end times of the video. But be aware: not all browsers and video formats will support this, so additional checks should be made.

```jsx
import React, { useRef, useState } from 'react';

const VideoUploadPreview = () => {
  const [videoSource, setVideoSource] = useState(null);
  const videoRef = useRef();

  const handleVideoUpload = (e) => {
    const file = e.target.files[0];
    if(file) {
      setVideoSource(URL.createObjectURL(file));
    }
  };

  const handleLoadedData = () => {
    videoRef.current.currentTime = 5;
    videoRef.current.play();
    setTimeout(() => {
      videoRef.current.pause();
    }, 5000);
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <input type="file" accept="video/*" onChange={handleVideoUpload} />
      
      {videoSource ? (
        <video ref={videoRef} controls width="500" onLoadedData={handleLoadedData}>
          <source src={videoSource} type="video/webm" />
        </video>
      ) : null}
    </div>
  );
};

export default VideoUploadPreview;
```

The code snippets above are simplified examples and might need adjustments according to your specific needs. Remember to handle edge cases, errors and user experience in your final implementation.
