C++ does not natively support PostgreSQL. To work with PostgreSQL in C++, you would need to use a PostgreSQL library, such as libpqxx. Here is an example of how your code might look using libpqxx:

```c++
#include <iostream>
#include <pqxx/pqxx>
#include <string>

using namespace std;
using namespace pqxx;

// Function to connect to PostgreSQL
connection connect_to_postgresql(minconn, maxconn, host, dbname, user, password, port) {
    string connection_string = "dbname = " + dbname + " user = " + user + 
                               " password = " + password + " hostaddr = " + host + 
                               " port = " + port;
    connection conn(connection_string);
    return conn;
}

// Function to execute a query
void execute_query(connection conn, string query) {
    nontransaction N(conn);
    result R(N.exec(query));
    N.commit();
    for (result::const_iterator c = R.begin(); c != R.end(); ++c) {
        for (result::tuple::const_iterator field = c->begin(); field != c->end(); ++field)
            cout << field.c_str() << '\t';
        cout << endl;
    }
}

// Main code
int main(int argc, char* argv[]) {
    connection conn = connect_to_postgresql("1", "10", "hostname", "dbname", "username", "password", "port");
    execute_query(conn, "SELECT * FROM table_name");
    conn.disconnect ();
    return 0;
}
```

This example is quite simplified and may not preserve all the functionality of your original Python script, due to the differing capabilities between psycopg2 and libpqxx. Notably, libpqxx does not support connection pooling and error handling as psycopg2, so minconn and maxconn are not being used in this example and I removed the error handling. 

For a more sophisticated usage of libpqxx, you might want to look at the libpqxx documentation or other resources, which offer more advanced capabilities (like prepared statements, transactions, etc.).
