Analyze and discuss the implications of using string concatenation operation "+=" inside a loop with a large number of iterations in Java. Discuss the performance and memory consequences this choice may bring along and propose a better alternative for this. Compare the two methods in terms of time and space complexity. 

Furthermore, implement a small code example that makes use of the StringBuilder class to perform the same operation more efficiently. Analyze the time and space complexity of your solution and explain why it is more efficient. 

Additionally, discuss thread safety of StringBuilder and StringBuffer classes and its impact on performance.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
When using the string concatenation operation "+=" in a loop with a large number of iterations in Java, the performance implications can be significant due to the immutable nature of String class in Java. Each time the "+=" operation is used, a new String object is created in the memory which includes the previous string. This not only slows down the execution speed but also wastes significant memory.

Ideally, the time complexity of repeated concatenation of n strings in a loop using '+=' operator is O(n^2), which is because string concatenation takes O(n) time, and we are doing it in a loop running n times. The space complexity is also O(n^2) because a new string (holding the old and new data) is created at each iteration.

A better solution is to use the 'StringBuilder' class in Java. This class is designed for efficient string manipulation. It allows us to modify the same object repeatedly, without creating a new one each time. 

Here is a simple code snippet demonstrating StringBuilder:

```java
StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
for(int i=0; i<100000; i++){
  sb.append(" test");
}
```

In terms of time complexity, string concatenation in a loop using StringBuilder's append() method takes O(n), because each append operation takes constant time, and we are doing it in a loop running n times. The space complexity is O(n) because StringBuilder only creates one object that grows as needed.

Regarding thread safety, the StringBuilder class itself is not thread-safe, meaning that it can't be reliably used in a multi-threaded environment without external synchronization. If thread-safety is required, you can use StringBuffer class which is essentially the same as StringBuilder, but all of its methods are synchronized for thread safety. 

However, the added thread safety of StringBuffer comes with a performance cost. In single-threaded environments (where thread safety is not a concern), StringBuilder will generally outperform StringBuffer due to the lack of synchronization overhead. In fact, the general rule of thumb is to use StringBuilder whenever possible, and resort to StringBuffer only when thread safety is needed.
<|end|>


