Here's a basic routing framework in Express.js.

Firstly, you may need to install Express.js using npm. You can follow the command as given below,

```ruby
npm install express --save
```

Setup your configuration file

```javascript
const express = require('express'); 
const app = express();

app.listen(3000, () => console.log("Server running on Port 3000"));
```

Handling the HTTP GET request. 

```javascript
app.get('/sample', (req, res) => {
    res.json({
        status: 200, 
        message: 'GET request successful!',
        data: "This is a sample JSON response."
    });
});
```

Within the '/sample' endpoint, a get request is being registered. Upon calling this endpoint using a GET HTTP method, the server responds with a JSON object.

Addressing the issue of error handling and ensuring the reliability and robustness of the framework.

```javascript
app.use(function (err, req, res, next) {
    console.error(err.stack);
    res.status(500).send({
        status: 500,
        message: 'Internal Server Failed!',
        type: 'InternalError'
    });
});

app.use(function (req, res, next) {
    res.status(404).send({
        status: 404,
        message: 'Not Found!',
        type: 'ResourceError'
    });
});
```

Here two middleware functions registered in the Express.js application handle exceptions. Any errors encountered will result in the error middleware triggering and logging the error stack trace in the console. The client will then receive a 500 Internal Server Error response.

In the case of an undefined route or resource which the server doesn't have any information about it, it returns a 404 not found error response.

Optionally, if you want the Express.js application to function effectively, you can place it after all your app routing registrations.

In addition to this, don’t forget to deploy the express application to a server to get your routing framework working.
