Develop a web scraper with Python BeautifulSoup to scrape data from an online web store.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Firstly, ensure that you have the necessary permissions to scrape data from the website. Not all websites allow for data scraping. Once you've got the necessary permissions, follow these steps.

You will need to install some Python libraries if you haven't already. They are `requests`, `beautifulsoup4` and optional `pandas` for storing data in DataFrames(you can use other ways to store the data as well).

Install them using pip:

```
pip install requests beautifulsoup4 pandas
```

Here is a basic Python script that scrapes data from a sample online store. It scrapes product names and product prices:

```Python
import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import pandas as pd

# Make a request
page = requests.get("https://www.example.com")

# Create a BeautifulSoup object
soup = BeautifulSoup(page.content, 'html.parser')

# Get product names
product_elements = soup.select('.product_name')   #you should replace ".product_name" with the actual class name on the site page source
product_names = [p.get_text() for p in product_elements]

# Get product prices
price_elements = soup.select('.product_price')   #you should replace ".product_price" with the actual class name on the site page source
product_prices = [p.get_text() for p in price_elements]

# Save to DataFrame
df = pd.DataFrame({
    "Product Name": product_names,
    "Product Price": product_prices
})

# Save to CSV
df.to_csv('products.csv', index=False)   
```

Replace `'https://www.example.com'` with the actual URL of the web store. `.product_name` and `.product_price` should be replaced with the actual class names of product names and prices.

Please note that the HTML classes `.product_name` and `.product_price` are hypothetical and you need to inspect the webpage (by right-clicking on the webpage and selecting Inspect Element) to find out the actual class names or tag names.

Also, note that this is a very basic scraper and may not work with websites that heavily rely on Javascript for rendering web pages or have a more complex structure. For more dynamic websites Selenium or Scrapy might be a better option. 

You would also likely need to handle pagination to scrape multiple pages. 

This code saves the scraped data as a CSV file using pandas. 

Remember, when you're scraping a website, always be respectful, don't hit the server too hard and make sure that you conform to the website's robots.txt rules and terms of service.
<|end|>


