Consider a real-world example of a vehicle rental company that has different types of vehicles such as cars, vans, and trucks. Each vehicle has some common properties, for instance, model, year, and mileage, but they also have specific properties. For instance, a car might have a "number of doors," a van might have "cargo capacity," and a truck might have "towing capacity."

Using JavaScript ES6 classes, write an implementation that illustrates the concept of inheritance where a base class 'Vehicle' shares common properties and methods to the derived classes 'Car', 'Van', and 'Truck'. Moreover, add specific properties and methods to the derived classes to make it more realistic. 

Furthermore, add methods in each derived class that override a method from the base class, to illustrate the concept of polymorphism. Also, make sure to include a method in the base class that uses the 'super' keyword. 

Finally, instantiate each derived class, use their methods, and illustrate how each object of the derived classes has access to properties and methods from the base 'Vehicle' class, their own class, and how they react to overridden methods. 

Ensure your code is well-commented to demonstrate understanding and consideration of inheritance principles in JavaScript.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
```javascript
// The base class 'Vehicle'
class Vehicle {
    constructor(model, year, mileage) {
        this.model = model;
        this.year = year;
        this.mileage = mileage;
    }

    // A method common for all vehicles
    vehicleInfo() {
        return `${this.model} ${this.year} has ${this.mileage} miles.`;
    }

    // A method to be overridden by derived classes
    feature() {
        return 'This is a vehicle.';
    }

    // A method that uses 'super'
    display() {
        return `Vehicle Info: ${super.vehicleInfo()}`;
    }
}

// The class 'Car' derived from base class 'Vehicle'
class Car extends Vehicle {
    constructor(model, year, mileage, numDoors) {
        super(model, year, mileage); // accessing the base class constructor using 'super'
        this.numDoors = numDoors;
    }

    // A method specific to 'Car'
    carInfo() {
        return `This car has ${this.numDoors} doors.`;
    }

    // Overriding 'feature' method of base class 
    feature() {
        return 'This is a car, known for comfort and style.';
    }
}

// Similarly, classes 'Van' and 'Truck' can be implemented as follow

class Van extends Vehicle {
    //... write here similar to Car
}

class Truck extends Vehicle {
    //... write here similar to Car
}


// Instantiate the derived classes
const car = new Car('Tesla Model S', 2021, 2000, 4);
const van = new Van('Mercedes Sprinter', 2020, 5000, 1500); // assuming 4th argument is cargo capacity 
const truck = new Truck('Ford F-150', 2020, 5000, 13000); // assuming 4th argument is towing capacity 

console.log(car.vehicleInfo()); // Accessing method from Vehicle class
console.log(car.carInfo()); // Accessing method from Car class
console.log(car.feature()); // Accessing overridden method 

// van and truck can be used similarly

```

In the above JavaScript code, we have a base class `Vehicle` and three derived classes `Car`, `Van`, and `Truck`. Each derived class has properties and methods specific to them. Again, each derived class has access to properties and methods from the base class using the `super` keyword. We also demonstrated method overriding (polymorphism) where the `feature` method from the base class is overridden in each derived class.
<|end|>


