Assuming that hourly/daily funding rates are autocorrelated and revert to a long term mean, then perhaps the following would work:
Use the average of the last N day funding rate as as predictor of the next N day funding rate. Sample a few points and use that to build the curve.
Any other ideas?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
1. Use a more sophisticated time-series model like an ARIMA or GARCH model. These models take into account both the autocorrelation and volatility clustering often seen in financial time series data.

2. Machine Learning Techniques: Use regression-based models (like Support Vector Regression, Random Forest Regression, etc.) or deep learning models (like RNNs). These models can often capture complex, non-linear relationships in the data, which can be beneficial given the complex nature of financial markets.

3. Use additional variables: If you can identify other variables that affect the funding rate (e.g., interest rates, market volatility, economic indicators, etc.), you can use multivariate time series models or include these as additional features in your machine learning models.

4. Ensemble methods: As the saying goes: two (or more) heads are better than one. You could use multiple models and average their predictions or use a more complex ensemble method.

5. Calibration: If you have some kind of physical or economic model that predicts the funding rate, you could use the historical data to calibrate the parameters of your model.

6. Consider seasonality and other trends: If there are certain days of the week, times of the day, or times of the year where the funding rate behaves differently, make sure your model accounts for these. 

7. Use exponential smoothing models: These models are a form of time series forecasting that involves calculating a weighted average of past observations, where the weights decrease exponentially as the observations get older.

8. Sentiment Analysis: Sentiment from news articles or social media can also be used as predictor.

Remember, no model is perfect and all models are based on assumptions that might not hold true. Always test your models on unseen data and keep track of their performance over time.
<|end|>


