I would like to model my problem with a Partially Observable Markov Decision Process (POMDP) but I have as an observation the previous state $o_t = s_{t-1}$.
However, I see in all formal definitions of POMDPs that the observation function can only be a function of the current state, and previous action: $o_t=\mathcal{O}(s_t, a_{t-1})$ and not a function of the previous state.
A imagine a simple way could be to define $\bar{s_t} = (s_t, s_{t-1})$ but I was wondering if there exists some cases where we can have $o_t=\mathcal{O}(s_t, a_{t-1}, s_{t-1})$.
Thank you very much for your help!
<|end|>
<|asst|>
It is possible to modify a POMDP to make the observation dependent on the previous state by effectively rolling the previous state into the current state, as you pointed out with $\bar{s_t} = (s_t, s_{t-1})$. 

This can often be a practical solution, but it also has its downsides:
- It increases the state space, possibly making the problem more computationally expensive.
- The Markov property may not hold anymore, if the system's dynamics are not only a function of the combined state $\bar{s_t}$.
- The assumption being made here is that the system's dynamics can be fully captured by the two most recent states. This may not be the case, especially in complex environments.

As for allowing $o_t=\mathcal{O}(s_t, a_{t-1}, s_{t-1})$ directly, this would indeed depart from the conventional definition of POMDPs. That being said, POMDPs are ultimately just a mathematical framework. If you believe this modification will more accurately represent your specific problem, there is nothing stopping you from using it. Just be aware that standard solution methods for POMDPs might not apply directly to your modified version. 

Ultimately, the "best" approach will depend on the specifics of your problem and the trade-offs you are willing to make.
<|end|>


