I inherited a Windows Forms app written in VB.Net.  Certain parts of the app run dreadfully slow.  What's the easiest way to find which parts of the code are holding things up?  I'm looking for a way to quickly find the slowest subroutines and tackle them first in an attempt to speed up the app.

I know that there are several code profiler products available for purchase which will show how long each subroutine takes, but I was hoping to find a  solution.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
There are a number of ways to profile your VB.Net app without purchasing any third-party tools.

1. Built-in Debugging Tools: Visual Studio, the IDE commonly used for VB.Net development, includes a Performance Profiler for analyzing runtime performance. You can use this tool to figure out which parts of your app are slow. To use this tool, go to 'Debug' -> 'Performance Profiler...' and choose the performance analysis tool you want to use.

2. Console.WriteLine: You can also use simple debug outputs to console or log file. For example, if you suspect a particular function is slow, you could add calls at the start and end of the function to print the current time. By comparing the times, you can see how long the function takes to run.

3. Using Stopwatch Class: The .Net Framework includes a Stopwatch class in System.Diagnostics that you can use to time how long sections of your code take to run. You start the stopwatch before the section of code you want analyze, and stop it afterwards. Then you can check Stopwatch.Elapsed property to know the time taken.

```vb.net
Dim stopwatch As New Stopwatch()
stopwatch.Start()

' Your code here...

stopwatch.Stop()
Console.WriteLine(stopwatch.Elapsed)
```

4. Using Process Class: Similar to Stopwatch, Process class can also help identify CPU and Memory usage of specific tasks.

Note: Keep in mind that profilers and timers can cause some overhead and may slightly alter the performance characteristics of your application while they're running. The changes usually aren't significant enough to generate incorrect results, but they may be noticeable.
<|end|>


