Write a C program to check if a given array is a sorted array or not.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The program will check if an array is sorted in ascending order or not:

```c
#include <stdio.h>

void checkSorted(int array[], int n) {
    int i;
    
    for(i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        if(array[i-1]>array[i])
        {
            printf("The array is not sorted\n");
            return;
        }
    }
    printf("The array is sorted\n");
}

int main() 
{
    int array[] = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6};
    int length = sizeof(array)/sizeof(array[0]);

    checkSorted(array, length);

    return 0;
}
```
In the above C program, an array of integers is defined in the `main()` function. The `sizeof` operator is used to calculate the length of the array. 

The `checkSorted` function is iterating through the array from the second element to the last. 

Within each iteration, it compares the `i-th` element to the `(i-1)th` element (which is its previous element). 

If it finds an element that is lesser than its previous element, it concludes that the array is not sorted in ascending order and then it exits the function.

If the loop completes without finding any such pair, the function concludes that the array is sorted in ascending order.

Remember, this function is checking for ascending order. For descending order, simply switch the comparison in the if statement. If you need to check either ascending or descending, you will need to modify the function or create a separate function.
<|end|>


