Create a program using JavaScript that replicates the results of an Oracle SQL procedure, which specifically pulls out the 'product_id', 'name', and 'manufacturer' fields from an 'inventory' database table.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
In Javascript, you would typically use an SQL querying library or framework that communicates with your Oracle database. Here's an example using 'oracledb' library.

Firstly, make sure to install 'oracledb' library via npm (Node Package Manager). You can install this by running 
```npm install oracledb``` 

Here's how you can execute the required SQL procedure:

```javascript
var oracledb = require('oracledb');

oracledb.getConnection(
  {
    user          : "Database_User",
    password      : "Database_Password",
    connectString : "Database_Connect_String"
  },
  function(err, connection)
  {
    if (err) {
      console.error(err.message);
      return;
    }
    connection.execute(
      `SELECT product_id, name, manufacturer 
       FROM inventory`,
      function(err, result)
      {
        if (err) {
          console.error(err.message);
          doRelease(connection);
          return;
        }
        console.log(result.rows);
        doRelease(connection);
      });
  });

function doRelease(connection)
{
  connection.close(
    function(err) {
      if (err)
        console.error(err.message);
    });
}
```
Change "Database_User", "Database_Password", and "Database_Connect_String" with your actual Oracle database credentials.

This script first establishes a connection to your Oracle database. If there are no connection errors, it runs an SQL query to extract the 'product_id', 'name', and 'manufacturer fields from the 'inventory' table of the database. The results are then logged out to the console.

Make sure your SQL query string is correct and your database user has sufficient privileges. Always remember to release your database connections when you're done with them!

Keep in mind that OracleDB library mainly supports Node.js, so ensure your environment support it.
