I am trying to identify best practices when it comes to Treasury Bill yield calculations.  Without getting too granular, our calculation will use 365 days unless Feb 29 is between settlement date and maturity date, then 366.  Others have said if Feb 29 is within 1 year after issue date, regardless of maturity date, use 366.  Which is correct?  I am struggling with how you calculate to a leap year when the bill matures prior to the leap year.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The yield calculation on a Treasury Bill is based on its discount from face value. That being said, the best practice for counting the days between settlement and maturity dates generally considers the actual number of days in the period, whether it is 365 days or 366. 

Therefore, the 366-day year should only be used when February 29 falls between the settlement date and maturity date. However, please note there isn't a universal agreement on this rule throughout the financial world, although it is broad practice. Some might use the 365-day convention for all T-Bills because of its simplicity. 

In a scenario where a T-Bill matures prior to a leap year, and you're not crossing over February 29, the standard year of 365 days should be used for yield calculations. Jumping to a 366-day count when the T-Bill matures before the leap year doesn't make sense because the extra day (February 29) will not be included in the tenor of the bill.

Ultimately, the critical thing is consistency in how you apply your chosen counting convention. Also, be aware of what convention your counterparts or the market you operate in uses to avoid confusion or discrepancies with calculations.
<|end|>


