I am working on an imbalance dataset with a 98:2 ratio (1M record in the majority class and 20K in the minority class)
I am planning to run my model for 30 folds, 

- I tried with stratified K folds but here again, each fold will have an imbalance problem again

- I don't want to use SMOTE analysis as it creates data loss or Overfitting


which cross-validation techniques or hyperparameters should I use so that all Minority classes are included in each fold?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
To tackle this imbalance problem, try to use a balanced stratified k-fold approach instead. You can opt to balance your data using undersampling or oversampling. Here are some ways:

1. **Undersampling Methods**: Random Under-Sampling, NearMiss, Condensed Nearest Neighbour, One-Sided Selection, Neighbourhood Cleaning Rule, etc.

2. **Oversampling Methods**: Random Over-Sampling, SMOTE, ADASYN and others.

However, in your case where you explicitly mentioned not keen to the use SMOTE method, you may focus on the undersampling techniques. 

You could try balancing each subset individually prior to model training, instead of balancing the entire dataset at once. This will make sure the model gets trained on a balanced subset of data at each iteration. At the same time, it prevents the model from seeing the same oversampled minority class instances or losing some potential valuable majority class instances because of undersampling in every fold.

For hyperparameters, you may want to use something like GridSearchCV (or RandomizedSearchCV if time or computational resources are a concern). If you're using an ensemble method like random forests or gradient boosting, try adjusting the 'class_weight' parameter to account for the imbalance.

Keep in mind that accuracy might not be the best way to evaluate model performance due to the class imbalances. Consider using F1 score, AUC-ROC, Precision, Recall, or Confusion Matrix instead.
<|end|>


