I was just assigned to do a CMS using ASP.net 3.5 and MySQL. I am kind of new to ASP.NET development (quite sufficient with C#) and 

I know already from quick Googling that I lose LINQ (and I was really looking forward to using this to build my model layer!), but I am not sure what other handy features I will lose. Since I've been relying on ASP.net tutorials which assume that you use MS SQL Server, I feel a chunk of my ASP.net knowledge just become invalid.

Thanks!
<|end|>
<|asst|>
You're correct that using MySQL instead of SQL Server will require some adjustment in how you approach ASP.NET development, but luckily there are many resources out there and many developers who have been in your shoes. 

1. Losing LINQ: You may not be able to use LINQ to SQL, which is designed to work with SQL Server specifically, but you can still use LINQ to Entities, which is a part of Entity Framework, works with MySQL and provides similar functionality.

2. Data Providers: ASP.NET uses ADO.NET data providers to interact with databases. SQL Server and MySQL use different data providers, so you'll have to modify your connection strings and code to work with MySQL. For example, you'll use the MySQL .NET Connector instead of the System.Data.SqlClient namespace.

3. Troubleshooting / Debugging: Debugging ASP.NET applications that use MySQL can be trickier because the MySQL .NET Connector doesn't provide as rich information when there’s an error, compared to SQL Server's SqlException class.

4. Stored Procedures: MySQL has a somewhat different syntax for creating stored procedures than SQL Server. If you plan on using stored procedures, you'll need to familiarize yourself with MySQL's syntax.

5. Performance: MySQL can be slower than SQL Server in several scenarios, so keep this in mind. Poor database performance can make your entire application seem slow, even if your ASP.NET code itself is very efficient.

A lot of the basic ASP.NET functionality should still work with MySQL, you'll just need to adjust how you interact with the database.

And don't worry, you have not wasted your time learning ASP.NET with SQL Server. As long as you understand the fundamentals of web development with ASP.NET, including page lifecycles, server controls, state management etc, you can apply that knowledge to any backend database. 

Remember, the more tools you know how to use, and the more situations you can adapt to, the better off you'll be as a developer. You're not losing knowledge, you're gaining flexibility.
<|end|>


