when I was creating the videoCall App Using webrtc, the issue was when a remote streamed
video disconnects due to a network issue, the video was frozen,
How to detect real-time web-streamed video frozen at Webrtc?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
In order to detect if a video is being received or stopped in WebRTC, you can use video statistics provided by the RTCPeerConnection. 

First, get the peer connection video receiver:

```javascript
var receivers = peerConnection.getReceivers();
var videoReceiver = null;
for(var i = 0; i < receivers.length; i++) {
    if(receivers[i].track.kind === 'video') {
        videoReceiver = receivers[i];
        break;
    }
}
```

Then, use `getStats()` method to retrieve the statistics:

```javascript
if(videoReceiver) {
    videoReceiver.getStats().then(stats => {
        stats.forEach(report => {
            if(report.type === 'inbound-rtp' && report.mediaType == 'video') {
                if(report.framesDecoded > 0) {
                    // Video is playing
                } else {
                    // Video is frozen
                }
            }
        });
    });
}
```

'framesDecoded' will give you the total number of frames that have been decoded for playback. If this number isn't changing over time, your stream is likely frozen.

There are other parameters also available like 'packetsLost' that can tell you network issues and 'jitter' that can indicate network delay. 

You can set an interval to check these parameters every second or so to have a real-time check of your video. These statistics are updated in real time by the browser so you can retrieve them as often as you'd like.

Please note this is a subtle and indirect way, different browsers or different versions may have some variation in these 'getStats' details but the idea is similar.

Also, using the standard ICE (Interactive Connectivity Establishment) framework for establishing the network connection, you can monitor the 'iceConnectionState' or 'connectionState' to detect network issues.

```javascript
peerConnection.oniceconnectionstatechange = function() {
    if (peerConnection.iceConnectionState == 'disconnected') {
        // Handle the disconnect event
        console.log("Disconnected due to network issues");
    }
}
```

Proper error handling of `getUserMedia()`, `RTCPeerConnection` and other methods should be in-place to handle user media and network related issues.
<|end|>


