Create a class in C++ that contains three private member variables including one pointer and a public member function that sets each variable. In addition, implement a copy constructor and an overloaded assignment operator to properly manage the memory of the pointer. Also, create an overloaded stream insertion operator to display the object's data in a human-readable format. 

Variables: int age, string name, float* salary.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a simple implementation of a class named Person in C++, that contains three private member variables as specified. 

```cpp
#include<iostream>
#include<string>

using namespace std;

class Person {
private:
    int age;
    string name;
    float* salary;

public:
    // Constructor
    Person(int a, string n, float s) : age(a), name(n) {
        salary = new float;
        *salary = s;
    }

    // Copy Constructor
    Person(const Person &p) : age(p.age), name(p.name) {
        salary = new float;
        *salary = *p.salary;
    }

    // Assignment Operator
    Person& operator= (const Person& p) {
        if (this != &p) {
            delete salary;
            age = p.age;
            name = p.name;
            salary = new float;
            *salary = *p.salary;
        }
        return *this;
    }

    // Destructor
    ~Person() {
        delete salary;
    }

    // Setter
    void SetPerson(int a, string n, float s) {
        age = a;
        name = n;
        *salary = s;
    }

    // Overloaded Stream Insertion Operator
    friend ostream& operator<< (ostream &out, const Person &p);
};

// Implement Stream Insertion Operator
ostream& operator<< (ostream &out, const Person &p) {
    out << "Name: " << p.name << ", Age: " << p.age 
        << ", Salary: " << *p.salary;
    return out;
}

```

The above implementation includes a regular constructor, a copy constructor, an overloaded assignment operator, a destructor, a setter function to modify the object's data, and an overloaded stream insertion operator to display the object's data in a human-readable format.

Money has been dealt dynamically to illustrate the dynamic memory management. Therefore, the copy constructor and the overloaded assignment operator both involve deep copying to avoid the issues that can arise with shallow copying when working with pointers.
<|end|>


