What java GUI layout manager does everyone use?  Lately, I have been using [MigLayout](http://www.miglayout.com/), which has some powerful component controls.  Just wanted to see what other developers are using other than the standard JDK ones.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
There isn't an agreed-upon universal GUI layout manager that all Java developers use. The choice heavily depends on the project and personal preferences. Some popular ones include:

1. GridBagLayout: Provides very fine control over components;
2. BorderLayout: A very basic layout manager;
3. GridLayout: A very simple layout manager that is handy in certain situations;
4. GroupLayout: Good for GUI creation tools like Swing GUI Builder in NetBeans;

Many developers, like you, are using powerful managers like MigLayout or JavaFX's layout managers because they are flexible, easy to use, and produce more visually appealing results.

It's also common to combine multiple layout managers in a program to get the exact look-and-feel desired. For instance, BorderLayout may fit perfectly for the main layout, but for a section of it, GridBagLayout or FlowLayout may be more suitable.

The ultimate takeaway is that there is no one-size-fits-all solution; developers should choose the layout manager that best fits their project's requirements and their working style.
