im trying to get absolute value between base_pos and postiion but clockwise.

position = [9,12,6]

base_pos = 3


position = sorted(position, key=lambda k: abs(k - base_pos))

print (position)


the code above will give the result of this

[6, 9, 12]


my desired result

[6, 12, 9] #or 
[12, 6, 9]


but i want to get [6,12,9] or [12,6,9] because for a clock, 3 is closer to 6 and 9 than 12.
is there any way to accomplish this using abs? if not, is there a good way to do this?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
from a point on a circle, the clockwise distance to another point can be calculated as `(other_point - base_point) % circle_size`. 

For your case, where the circle size is 12 (representing the hours on a clock), base_point is 3 and other_point is any value among [9, 12, 6], we can sort based on the expression `(k - base_pos) % 12`.

Here's how to sort your list:

```python
position = [9,12,6]
base_pos = 3

position = sorted(position, key=lambda k: (k - base_pos) % 12)
print (position)
```

This will give you:

```
[6, 9, 12]
```
Because on a clock, 6 is closer to 3 than 9 or 12, and it is the next one if you look clockwise. Then comes 9 and then 12.

This won't give you your exact requested result [6,12,9] or [12,6,9] because on a clock you can't have these orders starting from 3 going clockwise. But it should clarify the concept and you can adapt it with more specific criteria if need be.

Remember this doesn't measure Angular distance but instead orders the points in clockwise order from the base point.
<|end|>


