I need you to compose a conditional statement in C++ that first checks if a given numerical value is indeed a number, followed by assessing whether this number corresponds to a binary numeral representation in the double-digit length range or fails to match these criteria.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a simple C++ program implementing your requirements. Please note that C++ directly treats any input as a numerical value of the provided type (like int, float) if it expects one. For that reason, checking if the given numerical value is indeed a number is redundant. This following program verifies, however, if a given number fits the binary format and has the length of two digits (10-11, 00-01-10-11 in binary).

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <cmath>

bool isBinary(int n) {    
    while (n != 0) {
        if (n % 10 > 1)
            return false;
        n = n / 10;
    }
    return true;
}

int main() {
    int num;
    std::cout << "Enter a two-digit number: ";
    std::cin >> num;   

    if(!std::cin) {
        std::cout << "Provided input is not a number\n";
        return 0;
    }

    if(num >= 10 && num <= 99) {
        if(isBinary(num)) {
            std::cout << "Given number is a two digit binary number.\n";
        } else {
            std::cout << "Given number is a not binary number.\n";
        }
    } else {
        std::cout << "Given number is not a two digit number.\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

This program first checks if the entered number by the user is a two-digit number or not. If it's a two-digit number, then it checks if it's a binary number.
<|end|>


