<|asst|>
Sure, Let's assume your `Company` table has a unique id `company_id` and your `Employee` table has `employee_id`, `company_id` and `name` columns(just for simplicity). Here is a simple PL/SQL block that would meet your requirements:

```sql
DECLARE
   v_min_limit   CONSTANT PLS_INTEGER := 50;
   v_max_limit   CONSTANT PLS_INTEGER := 250;
   
   v_random_num  PLS_INTEGER;
BEGIN
   FOR c IN (SELECT company_id FROM Company)
   LOOP
      v_random_num := DBMS_RANDOM.VALUE(v_min_limit, v_max_limit);      
      FOR i IN 1 .. v_random_num
      LOOP
         -- Insert into Employee 
         INSERT INTO Employee(employee_id, company_id, name) 
         VALUES (i, c.company_id, 'Employee' || i);         
      END LOOP;
      
      COMMIT; -- commit after each company to avoid any undo space issues
   END LOOP;
END;
/
```

This will insert a number of rows between 50 and 250 for each company in the Employee table. Remember that this assumes you have an Employee table which accepts the values being inserted. You might want to adjust the `INSERT` clause according to your actual `Employee` table structure. 

Please note, it is using DBMS_RANDOM package of Oracle to generate a random number between 50 and 250. It also assumes that the `employee_id` will be unique across the companies which may not be true in actual scenario. You need to modify this part to reflect your actual id generation strategy. 

Always test such scripts with a small data set before running on your actual data to ensure that it’s functioning as expected. 

