As title suggests, I've been wondering about how standardization works when trying to understand how Principal Component Analysis( PCA) works from this tutorial [https://medium.com/analytics-vidhya/understanding-principle-component-analysis-pca-step-by-step-e7a4bb4031d9](https://medium.com/analytics-vidhya/understanding-principle-component-analysis-pca-step-by-step-e7a4bb4031d9)
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Standardization in principal component analysis (PCA) is a crucial pre-processing step which involves scaling the data so that all the features present have a mean of 0 and standard deviation of 1.

Before delving into why we standardize data for PCA, it's essential to understand what PCA is. PCA is a statistical technique that transforms a dataset described by possibly correlated variables into a new set of uncorrelated variables called principal components. These new variables are ordered such that the first few retain most of the variation present in all original variables.

Now coming to standardization, each feature of the data might have a different scale—for example, a dataset containing the information about a lot of people with features like height (cm), weight (kg), and salaried income. Here, the income feature is several magnitudes larger than the height or weight. However, PCA is influenced by the magnitudes of the variables, and this difference in scale would imply potentially putting a higher weight on features with larger values. 

Standardization, or Z-score normalization, is the process of rescaling features so that they'll have the properties of standard normal distribution with $\mu=0$ and $\sigma^2=1$, where $\mu$ is mean and $\sigma^2$ is variance. 

For every feature, the mean is subtracted from the feature's value (which shifts the mean to 0), and then the result is divided by the standard deviation of the feature (which rescales the feature variance).

Formula for standardization:
$z = \frac{x - \mu}{\sigma}$ where, $x$ is feature value.
 
By standardizing the data ahead of running a PCA, you prevent features with large values dominating and bending the principal components' direction towards them.
<|end|>


