I'm in the process of refactoring some code which includes moving folders around, and I would like to regularly merge to keep things current. What is the best way to merge after I've moved folders around in my working copy?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
If you're working with Git, there are a few steps to follow:

1. Before you start to refactor your code, pull all the changes from the main branch upstream. This will ensure you don't miss any updates that others might've pushed. Use the command: 

   ```bash
   git pull origin main_branch_name
   ```
   
2. Once you've refactored your code (moving folders, renaming files, etc.), commit your changes. This includes using `git add` to stage new locations of moved files and `git commit` to officially log the changes.

   ```bash
   git add --all
   git commit -m "Refactored the project structure"
   ```

3. Now if you want to merge changes from main branch to your current working branch, pull from main again:

   ```bash
   git pull origin main_branch_name
   ```  

If there are any conflicts between your changes and the changes others have pushed, Git will prompt you to manually merge those changes. 

Once you've resolved conflict, you can commit your merge.

```bash
git add --all
git commit -m "Merged changes after refactoring"
```

However, if you want to avoid merge conflicts related to project directory structure, it might be better to announce your plans to change the folder structure in advance, or do it during a time when not many people are pushing changes. 

If you're using another version control system like SVN, the exact commands you use may differ, but the process is broadly similar. Make sure all changes are pulled or updated in your working copy before you do any refactoring, and regularly commit and merge to keep everything up to date.
<|end|>


