Craft a Java-based software module encompassing a more intricate mathematical logic, which discerns and validates if the furnished numerical input is indicative of being an Armstrong number, thereby requiring intermediate mathematical computations.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a Java method to check if a number is an Armstrong number. We define an Armstrong number as a number that is the sum of its own digits each raised to the power of the number of digits.

```java
public class ArmstrongNumberChecker {
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		System.out.println(isArmstrongNumber(153)); // true
        System.out.println(isArmstrongNumber(370)); // true
        System.out.println(isArmstrongNumber(371)); // true
        System.out.println(isArmstrongNumber(407)); // true
        System.out.println(isArmstrongNumber(1634)); // true
        System.out.println(isArmstrongNumber(8208)); // true
        System.out.println(isArmstrongNumber(9474)); // true
        System.out.println(isArmstrongNumber(9475)); // false
	}

    public static boolean isArmstrongNumber(int number) {
        int originalNumber, remainder, result = 0, n = 0;

        originalNumber = number;

        // find the number of digits
        while (originalNumber != 0) {
            originalNumber /= 10;
            ++n;
        }

        originalNumber = number;

        // check if it's an Armstrong number
        while (originalNumber != 0) {
            remainder = originalNumber % 10;
            result += Math.pow(remainder, n);
            originalNumber /= 10;
        }

        return result == number;
    }
}
```

In the main method, we test our function with several numbers. In our `isArmstrongNumber` function, we first find the number of digits in the number. Then we check if the given number is an Armstrong number by adding each digit raised to the power of the number of digits and checking if the result is equal to the original number. The function returns `true` if the number is an Armstrong number and `false` otherwise.
<|end|>


