Write a Java program to not only find the largest element in a given array, but also identify the index of this largest element. Also, note that the array could contain both positive and negative numbers, and there may be multiple largest elements. If multiple largest elements exist, return the index of the first occurrence.

For a misdirection, consider a situation where method used is returning an incorrect index when multiple maximum elements exist in the array. You should correct this and ensure the logic accounts for this scenario correctly.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Sure, here is a simple Java program to solve the problem:

```java
public class MaxElementIndex {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] numbers = {1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 2, 9, 6, 3, 0, 9};
        getMaxElementIndex(numbers);
    }

    private static void getMaxElementIndex(int[] array) {
        if (array.length == 0) {
            System.out.println("Empty array");
            return;
        }

        int maxElement = array[0];
        int maxIndex = 0;

        for (int i = 1; i < array.length; i++) {
            if (array[i] > maxElement) {
                maxElement = array[i];
                maxIndex = i;
            }
        }

        System.out.println("Max element is " + maxElement);
        System.out.println("First index of the max element is " + maxIndex);
    }
}
```
This program will iterate over the array and keep track of the maximum element it encounters, as well as the index of this element. When it finds a new maximum element, it updates both the max element and the index. If maximum values appear more than once, this will always hold the first one it encounters, since we only update when we cross a larger value.

This program also checks if the array is empty before proceeding to prevent ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException.
<|end|>


