Create a JavaScript function to check if a string is a valid email address or not.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
In JavaScript, you can use regular expressions to check if a string is a valid email address or not. Here is a function that does this:

```javascript
function validateEmail(email) {
    var re = /^(([^<>()\[\]\\.,;:\s@"]+(\.[^<>()\[\]\\.,;:\s@"]+)*)|(".+"))@((\[[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\])|(([a-zA-Z\-0-9]+\.)+[a-zA-Z]{2,}))$/;
    return re.test(String(email).toLowerCase());
}
```

The code above is a function named `validateEmail` that takes an email address as its input. It defines a regular expression (the pattern within the `//` brackets and the following `^` and `$` marks the start and end of the pattern respectively) that represents the format of a valid email address. 

The `re.test` method tests if the email address matches the described format. It returns `true` if the email is valid and `false` otherwise. We use the `String(email).toLowerCase()` method to convert the email to a string (in case it isn't already) and to lower case (to ensure the email validation is case insensitive).

This regular expression corresponds to the following pattern:

- Start of the string `^`.
- Group that starts with the character that is not any of these characters `<>()[\]\\.,;:\s@` or a sequence of one or more characters that are not any of these characters `.<>()\[\]\\.,;:\s@'` followed by at least one character that is not any of these characters `.<>()\[\]\\.,;:\s@'`.
- Followed by the '@' character.
- Followed by a group that starts with a sequence of digits separated by periods in brackets or a sequence of one or more characters that are not any of these characters `-` followed by at least one letter character.
- End of the string `$`.
<|end|>


