You can apply a glowing or neon effect to SVG using CSS3 filter property. Here is an example of how to do it:

Here I assume the SVG is within a div with the class "mySvgContainer". 

```html
<div class="mySvgContainer">
     <!-- your svg goes here -->
</div>
```

And here is the css, applying glow to the svg within this div:

```css
.mySvgContainer svg {
     filter: drop-shadow( 0 0 5px rgba(0,255,127,1) );
}
```

This applies a green glow around the SVG. You can adjust the color and blur radius to your liking. 

Note: It's important to remember that not all browsers fully support CSS filters. Check the documentation and browser compatibility if you have issues.  
This method also only applies to the whole svg, not to individual pieces of it. It will not be able to target specific elements/path within your SVG using css classes or ids. Your svg paths' need to be separated and given class or id to apply glowing effect individually.
  
If you need a more complex or specific effect, you might want to consider using a SVG or graphics editor like Inkscape or Adobe Illustrator or an online design tool. Then export the result as SVG. This can also be done programmatically using JavaScript libraries like three.js or paper.js, but this approach requires more code and knowledge. 

Remember, SVG handling and rendering can vary across different browsers and versions, while most modern browsers would handle this well, but older versions might not as they have partial to no support for Svg and Css filter.
