using namespace std;

vector<string> split_numbers(string txt) {
    vector<string> result;
    regex r("([0-9]+)");   // regular expression to match numbers

    // Applying the regex
    sregex_iterator it(txt.begin(), txt.end(), r), end;

    // If no number is present in the equation
    if(distance(it, end) == 0) {  
        // tally up the ASCII values of any vowels present
        int sum = 0;
        for(const auto& c : txt) {
            char lc = tolower(c);
            if(lc == 'a' || lc == 'e' || lc == 'i' || lc == 'o' || lc == 'u') {
                sum += c;
            }
        }
        // If no vowels, return vector with solitary '0'
        if(sum == 0) {
            result.push_back("0");
        } else {
            result.push_back(to_string(sum));
        }
    } else {
        // If there are numbers, store those
        for(; it != end; ++it) {
            result.push_back(it->str());
        }
    }
    
    return result;
}
```

You can call the function like:

```cpp
vector<string> nums = split_numbers("2+3*4"); 
for(const auto& num: nums) 
   cout << num << endl;
``` 

This function uses a regular expression to find and extract the numbers in the input string. If no numbers are found, the function then looks for vowel characters and adds up their ASCII values. This sum of ASCII values is then returned as a single element in the output vector. If even no vowels are found, the function returns a vector with a solitary '0'.

Hence the calls to split_numbers return as follows:
  *  split_numbers("2+3*4") returns a vector holding strings ["2","3","4"].
  *  split_numbers("Math=Fun"), where ASCII values for vowels are 97 for 'a' and 117 for 'u', returns a vector holding the string ["214"], which is the sum of ASCII values of 'a' and 'u'.
  *  split_numbers("") returns a vector holding a solitary ['0'].
<|end|>


