In order to classify the given data, we can use several machine learning models. In this example, I will use a Naive Bayes classifier, which is a simple "probabilistic classifiers" based on applying Bayes' theorem with strong (naive) independence assumptions between the features.

Please, note that the provided dataset needs to be significantly larger in the real-world scenario for better accuracy. Here is a simplified implementation:

```python
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer
from sklearn.naive_bayes import MultinomialNB

# Your data
data = {'y1': ['rose', 'lily'], 'y2': ['red', 'white'], 'tag': ['flower', 'flower']}

# Combining data 
combined_data = [' '.join([y1, y2]) for y1, y2 in zip(data['y1'], data['y2'])]

# Vectorizing data
vectorizer = CountVectorizer()
X = vectorizer.fit_transform(combined_data)

# Building a naive bayes model
model = MultinomialNB()
model.fit(X, data['tag'])

# Testing model on a new example
test_data = ['rose red']
test_X = vectorizer.transform(test_data)
predicted = model.predict(test_X)

print(predicted) # -> ['flower']
```

This script first combines the 'y1' and 'y2' fields into a single string. Then, it sets up a vectorizer to convert the combined string into a usable input for the machine learning model, in this case, a Naive Bayes classifier.
After fitting the model with the data, you can use it to predict the class of a new example ('rose red' -> 'flower').

The script will print 'flower'. However, keep in mind that the size of the dataset significantly impacts the accuracy of AI models, and with only two records your model might not perform well.
