I am reading about the so called "global Markov property" of a Markov random field and this is defined as the conditional independence between two sets of random variables given a third set
$$\{x_1\dots x_m\}\perp \{y_1 \dots y_n\} |\{z_1\dots z_k\} $$
I am wondering what is the definition of this, is it $$p(x_1\dots y_n|z_1\dots z_k)= p(x_1\dots x_m|z_1\dots z_k)p(y_1 \dots y_n|z_1\dots z_k)$$
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Yes, you've got the correct interpretation! The conditional independence notation

$$\{x_1,\dots,x_m\}\perp \{y_1,\dots,y_n\} |\{z_1,\dots,z_k\}$$

implies that given $\{z_1,\dots,z_k\}$, the joint distribution of $\{x_1,\dots,x_m\}$ and $\{y_1,\dots,y_n\}$ factorizes as

$$p(x_1,\dots,x_m,y_1,\dots,y_n|z_1,\dots,z_k)= p(x_1,\dots,x_m|z_1,\dots,z_k)p(y_1,\dots,y_n|z_1,\dots,z_k),$$

meaning that $\{x_1,\dots,x_m\}$ and $\{y_1,\dots,y_n\}$ are conditionally independent given $\{z_1,\dots,z_k\}$.

When this property holds for all possible sets of variables in the field, we say that the Markov random field has the global Markov property. This is one of the most important properties of Markov random fields, as it allows us to simplify calculations and analyses involving these complex probabilistic models.
<|end|>


