Refine the upcoming JavaScript code:

/* The function 'longest' receives two parameters - an array of strings and a boolean. If the boolean is true, it yields the string with the most characters. In case of several strings having the same length, it returns the string that occurs last in the array. If the boolean is false, it yields the first string of utmost length that occurs in the array.

If the array is empty, the function returns null. adapt the current code to address the modifications. 

   >>> longest([], true)
   
   >>> longest(['a', 'b', 'c'], false)
   'a'
   >>> longest(['a', 'bb', 'ccc'], true)
   'ccc'
   >>> longest(['a', 'bb', 'ccc'], false)
   'a'
 */
const longest = (strings, order) => {
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is the refined JavaScript code:

```javascript
const longest = (strings, order) => {
    if(strings.length === 0){
        return null;
    }

    else{
        let result = strings[0];

        for(let i =1; i<strings.length;i++){
            if(strings[i].length > result.length){
                result = strings[i];
            }
            else if(strings[i].length === result.length && order){
                result = strings[i];
            }
        }

        return result;
    }
};
```
This solution works by traversing each string value in the string array and comparing its length with the current longest string. If the new string length is longer, it replaces the current longest string. If the lengths are equal, it will decide based on the order boolean whether to replace (when true) or not to replace (when false) the current longest string. If the array string parameter is empty, it simply returns null.
<|end|>


