Combining two or more SVGs involves inserting the content of the second SVG into the first SVG. Below is an example of how to combine this SVG with another one:

The current SVG (SVG 1):
```html
<svg id="svg1" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
    <!-- Element of SVG 1 -->
</svg>
```

Another SVG to be combined with SVG 1 (SVG 2):
```html
<svg id="svg2" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
    <!-- Element of SVG 2 -->
</svg>
```

To combine SVG 2 with SVG 1, remove the top line of SVG 2 (i.e., <svg id="svg2" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">) and the closing tag (</svg>) and then copy the content (The comments "<!-- Element of SVG 2 -->" in SVG 2 represents the SVG code) of SVG 2 to SVG 1. The resulting SVG would look like this:

```html
<svg id="svg1" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
    <!-- Element of SVG 1 -->
    <!-- Element of SVG 2 -->
</svg>
```

However, be aware that if both SVGs use the same IDs for elements, there will be a conflict. Also, if the viewboxes of the SVGs are different, the second SVG might not display properly within the first SVG.
<|end|>


