I have a page with a Google Maps mashup that has pushpins that are color-coded by day (Monday, Tuesday, etc.) The IFrame containing the map is dynamically sized, so it gets resized when the browser window is resized. 

I'd like to put a legend in the corner of the map window that tells the user what each color means. The Google Maps API includes a `GScreenOverlay` class that has the behavior that I want, but it only lets you specify an image to use as an overlay, and I'd prefer to use a DIV with text in it. What's the easiest way to position a DIV over the map window in (for example) the lower left corner that'll automatically stay in the same place relative to the corner when the browser window is resized?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
There are multiple ways to achieve this. But doing it with simple CSS may be the best and easy option. Here is an example:

```
HTML:

<div id="map-container">
  <div id="my-map"></div> <!-- Assume this is where your map lives -->
  <div id="legend">Legend goes here</div>
</div>

CSS:

#map-container {
  position: relative; /* This enables absolute positioning for children */
  /* Your map container sizing goes here */
}

#my-map {
  /* Your map positioning and sizing goes here */
}

#legend {
  position: absolute; /* This will position the legend relative to map-container */
  bottom: 0; /* Positions it at the bottom */
  left: 0;  /* Positions it at the left */
  /* Style your legend however you want from here */
  background: rgba(255,255,255,0.75); /* Example: White semi-transparent background */
  padding: 5px;
  margin: 10px;
}
```

In this example, the 'legend' `div` would appear in the lower left of the 'map-container' `div` and would remain there even if the browser size changes. Adjust the 'bottom' and 'left' properties as necessary to put the legend where you want. If you want it on the right side, replace 'left' with 'right' and adjust accordingly.

This solution assumes that you have access to the HTML and CSS of the page. If you're working in a more restrictive environment, you might need to use JavaScript or jQuery to create and position the `div`. But in general, you should be able to do this with static HTML/CSS.
<|end|>


