i'm looking to rewrite this in php:
def is_happy(s, n):
    if len(s) < n+2:
        return False
    sequences = [s[i:i+n] for i in range(0, len(s)-n+1)]
    for sequence in sequences:
        if sequences.count(sequence) < 2:
            return False
    return True
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is the PHP version of the python script you provided:

```php
function is_happy($s, $n) {
    if (strlen($s) < $n+2) {
        return false;
    }
    $sequences = [];
    for($i = 0; $i <= strlen($s) - $n; $i++) {
        $sequences[] = substr($s, $i, $n);
    }
    foreach ($sequences as $sequence) {
        if (array_count_values($sequences)[$sequence] < 2) {
            return false;
        }
    }
    return true;
}
```
Just keep in mind that the efficiency of this solution is not high, especially with large strings and/or large $n values because of array_count_values returning the counts of all the values in the array in every iteration of the loop.
<|end|>


