I have an XML document with a DTD, and would love to be able to access the XML model, something like this:


title = Thing.Items[0].Title



Is there a way, in Ruby, to generate this kind of object model based on a DTD? Or am I stuck using REXML?

Thanks!
<|end|>
<|asst|>
In Ruby, you don't have out-of-the-box libraries that directly parse DTD. However, you can construct an object model manually by combining REXML for XML parsing and other standard Ruby constructs for object-orientation.

Here is a pseudo code outlining the steps:

```ruby
require 'rexml/document'

xml_string = "" # Your XML string
dtd_string = "" # Your DTD string

class Model
  def initialize
    @items = []
  end

  def add_item(item)
    @items << item
  end

  def items
    @items.dup
  end
end

class Item
  attr_accessor :title

  def initialize(title)
    @title = title
  end
end

model = Model.new
document = REXML::Document.new(xml_string)
document.elements.each('path-to-items') do |element|
  item = Item.new(element.attributes['Title'])
  model.add_item(item)
end

title = model.items[0].title
```

In the code above, we first define our object model with the classes Model and Item. Then we parse the XML document, iterate through each item element and create a new Item object for each, which we add to our Model object.

Remember to replace 'path-to-items' with the actual path to your items in the xml document.

Please note that this does not validate the XML against the DTD, and does not make use of the DTD in any way. It is just a way of building an object model out of an XML file. If you want to use the DTD for validation, you would have to use an external library/tool.

For validation of XML against DTD, you can use the `nokogiri` gem:

```ruby
require 'nokogiri'

schema = Nokogiri::XML::Schema(File.read('my_schema.dtd'))
document   = Nokogiri::XML(File.read('my_document.xml'))

schema.validate(document).each do |error|
  puts error.message
end
```
This will print out each validation error.

But for generating models from DTD - it's not something that Ruby supports out of the box, and I am not aware of any gems that would provide this functionality.
<|end|>


