The provided Python code is a function that checks if two strings are equal or not. Since the given strings "Hello, World!" and "Hello, World!" are exactly the same, the function will return True and the word "No" will be printed in the console. 

In terms of time complexity, this function has a time complexity of O(n) in the worst-case scenario, where n represents the length of the shortest input string. This is because the function uses recursion to compare each character in the strings, which would be performed n times if all characters are equal. In other words, the function needs to go through each character in the string individually, and the maximum number of times this is needed is proportional to the length of the string, hence, the time complexity is linear or O(n).
