Develop a Node.js backend for a simple social media website. The website should accept incoming data from a REST API, update a MongoDB database, and return data in response.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a basic example of how you can structure a Node.js application with Express and MongoDB to act as a REST API for a social media application. Note that this is a very simplified version and much more would be needed for a real-world application.

First install express and mongodb.
```
npm install express mongodb
```
We're also using Mongoose as an ODM (Object Data Mapping) to make working with MongoDB easier.
```
npm install mongoose
```

Now, let's assume that we're building a very simple social media where users can post messages. Below is a very basic example of how your app.js file might look:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const mongoose = require('mongoose');

// Connect to MongoDB database
mongoose.connect('mongodb://localhost/socialmedia', {useNewUrlParser: true, useUnifiedTopology: true});

// Define a new user schema for mongoose
const Post = mongoose.model('Post', new mongoose.Schema({
    username: String,
    message: String
}));

const app = express();

// Enable JSON body for POST requests
app.use(express.json());

// GET all posts
app.get('/post', async (req, res) => {
    const posts = await Post.find();
    res.send(posts);
});

// GET individual post
app.get('/post/:id', async (req, res) => {
    const post = await Post.findById(req.params.id);
    if (!post) return res.status(404).send('No post found');
    res.send(post);
});

// POST new post
app.post('/post', async (req, res) => {
    const post = new Post({
        username: req.body.username,
        message: req.body.message
    });
    await post.save();
    res.send(post);
});

// DELETE post
app.delete('/post/:id', async (req, res) => {
    const post = await Post.findByIdAndDelete(req.params.id);
    if (!post) return res.status(404).send('No post found');
    res.status(204).send();
});

// PATCH update post
app.patch('/post/:id', async (req, res) => {
    const post = await Post.findByIdAndUpdate(req.params.id, req.body, {new: true});
    if (!post) return res.status(404).send('No post found');
    res.send(post);
});

app.listen(3000, () => console.log('Server is running on port 3000...'));
```

By running this script with Node, you will have set up a simple backend for a social media app, which provides five different endpoints:

- `GET /post` to retrieve all posts
- `GET /post/:id` to retrieve a specific post
- `POST /post` to create a new post
- `DELETE /post/:id` to delete a specific post
- `PATCH /post/:id` to update a specific post

These endpoints form the REST API that your frontend can use to interact with the backend server. Each request to these endpoints (except the GET requests) must be made with a JSON body that contains the needed data.
<|end|>


