Identify the HTML element and its attributes used to create a link in the following code snippet. In addition, write a JavaScript function that dynamically changes the href attribute to a URL of your choosing. 
<a target="_blank" href="https://example.com">Example link</a>
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The HTML element used to create a link is the 'a' or anchor element. It has two attributes:

1. target: This specifies where to open the linked document. "_blank" means the link opens in a new window or tab.
2. href: This specifies the URL of the page the link goes to. In this case, it's "https://example.com".

Here is a JavaScript function that changes the href attribute:

```javascript
// JavaScript function to change a href attribute
function changeLinkUrl(id, newUrl) {
    var element = document.getElementById(id);
    
    if (element) {
        element.href = newUrl;
    } else {
        console.log("Element with ID: " + id + ", not found.");
    }
}
```
You can use this function by passing in the ID of your link (which you need to add to your HTML) and the new URL:

```javascript
changeLinkUrl("myLink", "https://newurl.com");
```
To add an ID to your HTML anchor element, you can modify your HTML as follows:

```html
<a id="myLink" target="_blank" href="https://example.com">Example link</a>
```

Note: Ensure that your JavaScript code runs after the HTML has fully loaded. You can either put your JavaScript at the end of your HTML body or use a window load event.
<|end|>


