Craft an advanced expression utilizing the principles of regex, whose purpose would be to meticulously isolate email addresses and classify them based on domain extension from a textual data set embedded in a Python variable. 
You should distinguish between different types of domains such as .com, .net, .edu, etc. Also, ensure the expression can handle case-sensitive and multiple email addresses per domain.
Variable content = "My electronic mail label is john@doe.com while your electronic mail label is jane@doe.com and our professor has the electronic mail label prof@doe.edu"
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here's how to do it using Python's built-in `re` module for regex. I will use the findall method which returns all non-overlapping matches of pattern in string, as a list of strings. After finding all emails, I'll split them by '@' and use a dictionary to separate email addresses based on the domain.

```python
import re

# Variable with the data
content = "My electronic mail label is john@doe.com while your electronic mail label is jane@doe.com and our professor has the electronic mail label prof@doe.edu"

# Here's the regex expression - it captures "word@word.domain"
regex = r'\b[A-Za-z0-9._%+-]+@[A-Za-z0-9.-]+\.[A-Z|a-z]{2,}\b'

# Using the regex findall method
emails = re.findall(regex, content)

# Use dictionary to classify emails based on domain
email_dict = {}
for email in emails:
    username, domain = email.split('@')
    if domain not in email_dict:
        email_dict[domain] = [username]
    else:
        email_dict[domain].append(username)

# print the dictionary
for domain, usernames in email_dict.items():
    print(f"The {domain} domain has the following email addresses:")
    for username in usernames:
        print(f"{username}@{domain}")
```
In this program, `re.findall` function finds all the matches and returns them as a list of strings, with each string representing one match. After we have all emails, we split them by '@' and store usernames corresponding to each domain.
<|end|>


