<|asst|>
In Java, you can use the containsAll() method of the HashSet class to determine if a given set is a subset of another. This method takes a collection as a parameter, returns true if the set contains all of the elements in the specified collection and false otherwise.

Here's the Java equivalent:

```Java
import java.util.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        HashSet<Integer> s1 = new HashSet<>(Arrays.asList(1, 4, 3, 34, 653, 2, 5));
        HashSet<Integer> s2 = new HashSet<>(Arrays.asList(5, 7, 1, 5, 9, 653, 121));
        System.out.println(subsetCheck(s1, s2));  // Output will be False

        HashSet<Integer> s3 = new HashSet<>(Arrays.asList(3, 2));
        HashSet<Integer> s4 = new HashSet<>(Arrays.asList(5, 3, 2, 8));
        System.out.println(subsetCheck(s3, s4));  // Output will be True
    }

    public static boolean subsetCheck(HashSet<Integer> s1, HashSet<Integer> s2) {
        return s2.containsAll(s1);
    }
}
```

This code first creates two sets, s1 and s2, from arrays of integers using the asList() method of the Arrays class and the constructor of HashSet. It then calls the subsetCheck() method to check if s1 is a subset of s2 and print the result. 

The subsetCheck() method simply calls the containsAll() method on s2, passing s1 as the argument. This will return true if all elements of s1 are contained in s2 (i.e., s1 is a subset of s2), and false otherwise.

The same check is repeated for s3 and s4, which are other sets created from arrays of integers.
