Develop a Java-based algorithm to compute the harmonic mean of an array containing particular numeric elements. The algorithm should also handle the cases for arrays with negative numbers and zeros.
For instance, your code should be able to handle an input like:
[4, 7, 11, 15, 18, 21, -7, 0]
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a Java method that can solve the problem:

```java
public static Double harmonicMean(int[] arr) {
    int size = arr.length;
    double sum = 0.0;

    // Zero or negative check
    for (int i : arr) {
        if (i <= 0) {
            System.out.println("Invalid value in array: " + i);
            return null; 
        }
        sum += 1.0/i;
    }

    // Calculating harmonic mean
    if (sum != 0) {
        return size / sum;
    } else {
        return null; // When all elements are zero
    } 
}
```

You would call the function like so:

```java
System.out.println(harmonicMean(new int[]{4, 7, 11, 15, 18, 21, -7, 0}));
```

This code would calculate the harmonic mean for the array. However, the algorithm stops and returns null if it finds a zero or a negative number in the array, because including such numbers in the calculation of a harmonic mean isn't mathematically meaningful. Harmonic mean tends to emphasize the impact of small values and is undefined if any of the inputs are less than or equal to zero.
<|end|>


