Here is a possible solution using a generator function. The "yield" keyword used in this function provides the next elements from the data collection "people" one by one each time when "next()" is called.

```javascript
const people = ["Alice", "Eve", "Carol"];

function* peopleGenerator(arr) {
    for(let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
        yield arr[i];
    }
}

const gen = peopleGenerator(people);

let nextPerson = gen.next();
while(!nextPerson.done) {
    console.log(nextPerson.value);
    nextPerson = gen.next();
}
```

This code creates a generator function `peopleGenerator(arr)` that yields elements from the array one at a time. The `gen.next()` function is used to iterate through each element. The `done` property of the result of `next()` is checked to see if there are more elements to be processed. If there are, `nextPerson.value` is printed and the function continues to the next element.
