i'm converting my project to perl, help me with this code:
sort(numArray.begin(), numArray.end(),[](int a, int b){
        int len_a = (a == 0) ? 1 : ((int)log10(abs(a)) + 1);
        int len_b = (b == 0) ? 1 : ((int)log10(abs(b)) + 1);
    return len_a == len_b ? a < b : len_a < len_b;
    });
    return numArray; 
}
could you also provide some commentary on what the perl code is doing?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Sure, this piece of code sorts an array of numbers such that shorter numbers will come before longer ones. If two numbers have the same length, the smaller number comes first. This might be used for example in phone number lists which are often sorted this way.

Below is an equivalent code in Perl.

```perl
@numArray = sort {
    my $len_a = $a == 0 ? 1 : int(log(abs($a))/log(10))+1;
    my $len_b = $b == 0 ? 1 : int(log(abs($b))/log(10))+1;
  
    if($len_a == $len_b){
        $a <=> $b;
    } else {
        $len_a <=> $len_b;
    }
} @numArray;
```
In the Perl code, `sort` is used just like in the C++ example. We don't have to mention `@numArray`'s start and end; `sort` will handle the entire array. Inside the sort block, we're using Perl's ternary operator (`? :`) and `int()` function like your original C++ code.

In Perl, `<=>` is the equivalent of C++'s return statement. It compares the values and returns -1, 0, or 1 depending on whether the left side is less, equal, or greater than the right side. 

Similar to what your C++ code is doing, this Perl code determines the lengths of the numbers `a` and `b` (being compared during sorting), and feeds this into the comparison for sort. If lengths are equal, the actual integer values are compared to decide their order with `$a <=> $b`.

Note also that `log($a)/log(10)` substitutes for your `log10()` function in C++. This calculates the base-10 logarithm which gives a measure of the "size" of a number.
<|end|>


