Refactor the following JavaScript code, and make necessary modifications so that it can determine whether a user input number is a prime number or not. Additionally, write unit tests to ensure its correctness.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a refactored version JavaScript function that determines whether a number is prime or not. We'll be using a more efficient algorithm to check for primality.

```javascript
// Prime number check function
function isPrime(num) {
  if(num < 2) return false;
  if(num === 2) return true;
  if(num % 2 === 0) return false;

  var sqrtNum = Math.sqrt(num);
  for(let i = 3; i <= sqrtNum; i += 2)
    if(num % i === 0) return false;

  return true;
}
```
This approach improves the efficiency from O(n) to O(sqrt(n)) as we only have to check divisibility up to the square root of the number, not the full number itself.

For the unit testing, we'll be using the Jest testing framework. If Jest is not installed, you can install it using `npm install --save-dev jest`.

Here's how we might create tests to verify the correctness of the `isPrime` function.

```javascript
const isPrime = require('./isPrime'); // Assuming isPrime function is in isPrime.js

test('checks if 2 is prime', () => {
  expect(isPrime(2)).toBeTruthy();
});

test('checks if 3 is prime', () => {
  expect(isPrime(3)).toBeTruthy();
});

test('checks if 4 is not prime', () => {
  expect(isPrime(4)).toBeFalsy();
});

test('checks if 89 is prime', () => {
  expect(isPrime(89)).toBeTruthy();
});

test('checks if 100 is not prime', () => {
  expect(isPrime(100)).toBeFalsy();
});
```

This test suite includes checks for both prime and non-prime numbers, including edge cases like 2 (the smallest prime number) and even numbers. To run the tests, simply run `jest` in the command line. If the `isPrime` function is working correctly, all tests should pass successfully.
