4. The problem states that the program needs to be scalable to handle multiple instances of car pairs, which is not addressed in the code.

Here's the corrected code based on the proper interpretation of the prompt:

```java
import java.util.*;
public class CarSimulation {
    static int car1Speed = 60; // km/h
    static int car2Speed = 80; // km/h

    public static void evaluatePair(int distance, int averageSpeed){
        double timeTakenByCar1 = (double)distance / car1Speed;
        double timeTakenByCar2 = (double)distance / car2Speed;

        if(car1Speed > averageSpeed){
            System.out.println("Car1 in the pair is exceeding the average speed.");
        }

        if(car2Speed > averageSpeed){
            System.out.println("Car2 in the pair is exceeding the average speed.");
        }

        System.out.println("Time taken by Car 1: " + timeTakenByCar1 + " hours");
        System.out.println("Time taken by Car 2: " + timeTakenByCar2 + " hours");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner in = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.println("Enter number of car pairs:");
        int pairs = in.nextInt();

        for(int i = 1; i <= pairs; i++) {
            System.out.println("Enter distance and average speed for pair " + i + ":");
            int distance = in.nextInt();
            int averageSpeed = in.nextInt();
            evaluatePair(distance, averageSpeed);
        }
        in.close();
     }
}
```
This program will ask for the number of car pairs, the distance, and the average speed for each pair. It then evaluates whether each individual car in the given pair is over the average speed and prints the time taken by each car. This solution is scalable to multiple car pairs.
