    const updatedAccount = { ...currentAccount, balance: currentAccount.balance + value }
    const updatedAccounts = accounts.map(acc => acc.id === currentAccount.id ? updatedAccount : acc);
    setAccounts(updatedAccounts);
    setCurrentAccount(updatedAccount);
  };

  const withdrawMoney = (value) => {
    const updatedAccount = { ...currentAccount, balance: currentAccount.balance - value }
    const updatedAccounts = accounts.map(acc => acc.id === currentAccount.id ? updatedAccount : acc);
    setAccounts(updatedAccounts);
    setCurrentAccount(updatedAccount);
  };

  const formatCurrency = (balance) => {
    // ...
  };

  return (
    <div>
      { /* ... */}
      {currentAccount && (
        <div>
          <button onClick={() => addMoney(10)}>Add $10</button>
          <button onClick={() => withdrawMoney(10)}>Withdraw $10</button>
          <div>Balance: {formatCurrency(currentAccount.balance)}</div>
        </div>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}

export default BankingAccount;
```

This is an oversimplified example of managing different accounts and balance. For a real project, you should properly manage and isolate the state and provide better user interactions and error handling. You also have to handle deposit and withdraw from the back end, validating and updating the balance there.

Creating a production-level banking application requires a tremendous understanding of top-notch security, state management, eslint, prop-types, unit-testing, back-end capabilities and many more. Use this guide as your starting point.
