<|asst|>
It seems like the problem occurs because you aren't associating any identifier with the status of the checkbox. Currently, you're setting the status to be true on any checkbox click. This isn't saving the state of the individual todo list note or connecting the status to the specific note.

You should be maintaining an array or object of statuses where the key is the unique identifier (i.e., noteId) of the todo item and value is the status of the checkbox.

Here's how I would handle this:

```jsx
// maintain the status in an object where key is the id of the todo item
const [status, setStatus] = useState({});

// handle change by copying the old status and setting the new todo ID with the checked status
const handleStatus = (event, data) => {
    console.log("Marking todo ... Data : ", data);
    setStatus({...status, [data.id]: event.target.checked});
};
```

For checkbox, give the `checked` prop the value from the status state object and pass the data object to the `onChange` handler:

```jsx
<Checkbox
    style={{ flex: 1 }}
    checked={status[data.id]}    // assuming data is the todo object with an id field
    onChange={(event) => handleStatus(event, data)}
/>
```

Lastly, for persisting the status changes in your database, you should call your API inside the `handleStatus` function after updating the status state. 

Example:

```jsx
const handleStatus = (event, data) => {
    console.log("Marking todo ... Data : ", data);
    const newStatus = {...status, [data.id]: event.target.checked};
    setStatus(newStatus);

    // Call your API to update the status in your database
    // apiSaveStatus(data, newStatus[data.id]);
};
```

Without knowing the exact structure of the `data` object or how you're retrieving/saving it from/to your database, you may need to tweak the above code to match your data structures and API calls.
