<|user|>
I am using WSL2 on my development PC and I need to move to the new PC. What is the recommended approach to migrate all "WSL distributions" to the new PC ?
Do I need to back up each "WSL distributions" separately by command(s) like:
`wsl --export Ubuntu-20.04 C:\WSL-Backup\ubuntu.tar`
Or is there any "magic backup-all" command ?
I do not think that copying whole directory `\\wsl$\` would be the right way to do the trick.
The question can be put simpler: "How to automate WSL backup? In order to make sure that it can be recovered later"
<|end|>
<|asst|>
There is no 'magic backup-all' command for WSL distributions. You will need to issue the `--export` command for each distribution you have installed and want to back up.

However, you can try to automate this process by creating a script or a batch file containing the commands for all distributions. Here's an example of such a script:

```bash
#!/bin/bash
distros=('Ubuntu-20.04' 'Debian' 'Fedora')
for distro in ${distros[@]}; do
  wsl --export $distro C:\WSL-Backup\$distro.tar
done
```

This script assumes that you have three distributions: Ubuntu-20.04, Debian, Fedora. You can replace these with the distributions you have.

You can use this script for a scheduled backup task or run it manually before switching to the new PC.

You'll also need to manually re-import these backed-up distros on your new PC with `wsl --import`.

The entire `\\wsl$\` directory represents a network fileshare to access the Linux filesystems in WSL and it's not suitable for backup purposes. File permissions and system-level details are not preserved when copying files from this location.

Remember that `wsl --export` and `wsl --import` operations do not preserve or restore certain data such as user accounts, sudo privileges and environment variables. Therefore, after importing distributions to a new PC, you might need to manually restore some settings.

It's good practice to also backup your home directory and other important files separately to preserve file permissions, hidden files, and because some software might not be compatible with the `wsl --export`/`--import` operations. Especially important if you've installed a lot of software or made significant modifications to the system. Also, user-created Linux user accounts, sudo privileges won't be maintained. You would have to recreate those manually.
<|end|>


