Formulate an Structured Query Language instruction to extract the comprehensive details of each personnel holding the "Smith" surname along with the list of projects they've worked on in the last five years. Additionally, the resulting output should be organized by their seniority level within the company. For the purpose of this exercise, assume the employee table (employee_details) containing the employee name and other details and the project-contributions table that carries details about the projects an employee has taken part in.

Please remember to handle any potential exceptions in your SQL instruction and provide comments regarding your approach and any specific considerations you've given while crafting your solution.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a possible SQL solution assuming a PostgreSQL type database:

```sql
-- Your SQL goes here

-- Exception Handling
DO $$
BEGIN
   -- Check if the employee_details table exists
   IF NOT EXISTS (
      SELECT 1
      FROM   information_schema.tables 
      WHERE  table_schema = 'public'
      AND    table_name = 'employee_details'
      ) THEN
   RAISE NOTICE 'Table public.employee_details does not exist';
   END IF;

   -- Check if the project_contributions table exists
   IF NOT EXISTS (
      SELECT 1
      FROM   information_schema.tables 
      WHERE  table_schema = 'public'
      AND    table_name = 'project_contributions'
      ) THEN
   RAISE NOTICE 'Table public.project_contributions does not exist';
   END IF;
EXCEPTION WHEN OTHERS THEN
   RAISE NOTICE 'An error has occurred: %', SQLERRM;

END $$
LANGUAGE plpgsql;

-- SQL Query
SELECT e.*, p.project_name 
FROM employee_details e
LEFT JOIN project_contributions p ON e.employee_id = p.employee_id 
WHERE e.last_name='Smith' AND p.year BETWEEN EXTRACT(YEAR FROM current_date)-5 AND EXTRACT(YEAR FROM current_date)
ORDER BY e.seniority_level ASC;
```

In this solution, the entire employee details are being selected (`e.*`) along with the project name (`p.project_name`). The `LEFT JOIN` is used to merge the two tables using the employee_id column. All personnel with the last name 'Smith' are then filtered out, with a time conditional set to select only those projects that the personnel have participated in over the last five years. Finally, the data is ordered according to the seniority level of the employees in ascending order (ASC). The exception handling in PostgreSQL can be handled using DO blocks.

Please modify column names according to your schema design.
