Create a program in JavaScript that produces two arrays, each of 10 unique numbers ranging from 1 to 100. Afterwards, merge these two arrays into one, remove any duplicates, and organize the final array in ascending order.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a simple JavaScript program that fulfills your request:

```javascript
// Function to generate a unique random array
function generateUniqueArray(len, max) {
  const set = new Set();
  
  while(set.size < len) {
    set.add(Math.floor(Math.random() * max) + 1);
  }

  return Array.from(set);
}

let array1 = generateUniqueArray(10, 100),
    array2 = generateUniqueArray(10, 100);

console.log('Array 1: ', array1);
console.log('Array 2: ', array2);

// Merge two arrays and remove duplicates
let merged = Array.from(new Set([...array1, ...array2]));

// Sort the array in ascending order
merged.sort((a, b) => a - b);

console.log('Merged array: ', merged);
```

This program begins by defining a function to generate an array of unique random numbers between 1 and a max number specified by the caller of the function. It then generates two such arrays, each of 10 unique numbers ranging from 1 to 100. It logs these initial arrays to the console, merges the two into one, removes any duplicates from this merged array, sorts the resulting array in ascending order, and logs this final array to the console as well.

Please note that this solution uses Set to ensure uniqueness of numbers while generating and merging arrays which is supported in JavaScript engines ECMAScript 2015 (ES6) and later versions.
