It is said that in next js we don't need to install react-router-dom because the path of our pages depend on the pages folder. Well, it actually works when I create button to move to another pages. But when I create components folder and create navbar component, it doesn't work properly as it was. The next/link keeps reloading when it moves to another pages.

import Link from "next/link";

export default function Navbar() {
  return (
    <nav className="bg-black flex justify-between p-5 text-white">
      <h1 className="font-bold text-sky-400">
        <Link href="/">Furniture App</Link>
      </h1>
      <div>
        <Link href="about">About</Link>
        <Link href="promos">Promos</Link>
      </div>
    </nav>
  );
}


Do I have to create components in pages folder in order to make Next/Link works without reload the browser?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Your links are trying to navigate to relative paths (from the current page) instead of absolute paths. 

To specify an absolute path, add a forward slash (`/`) in front of the path for each Link component. 

Try changing your code to the following:

```jsx
import Link from 'next/link';

export default function Navbar() {
  return (
    <nav className="bg-black flex justify-between p-5 text-white">
      <h1 className="font-bold text-sky-400">
        <Link href="/">Furniture App</Link>
      </h1>
      <div>
        <Link href="/about">About</Link> 
        <Link href="/promos">Promos</Link>
      </div>
    </nav>
  );
}
```

Let me explain the difference. `href="about"` means you want to navigate to the 'about' page that is inside the current page. Let's say you're on the 'furniture' page - i.e., `https://website/furniture` - the link's href (`about`) tells the browser to look for `https://website/furniture/about`, not `https://website/about`. 

With `href="/about"`, you are navigating to the 'about' page that's on the root level of your application, i.e. `https://website/about`

In Next.js, pages are determined by the file path under the `pages` directory. So `/about` would mean there's an `about.js` (or `about/index.js`) file under the `pages` directory. The same applies to `/promos`.

**So no, you don't have to create components in pages folder to make the `next/link` works without reloading the browser**. You just need to correctly specify your routing paths.
<|end|>


