<|asst|>
Here is the equivalent Lua code:

```lua
function sort_third(t)
    -- Table to store elements at multiples of 3 positions
    local multiplesOfThree = {}
    
    -- Lua tables are 1-based
    for i = 1, #t do
        -- Operand is 1-based in lua
        if i % 3 == 0 then
            table.insert(multiplesOfThree, t[i])
        end
    end
    -- Sort the multiples of 3 elements
    table.sort(multiplesOfThree)

    -- Put sorted multiples of 3 back into original positions
    local j = 1
    for i = 1, #t do
        if i % 3 == 0 then
            t[i] = multiplesOfThree[j]
            j = j + 1
        end
    end
    
    return t
end

-- Test the function
local t = {5, 6, 3, 4, 8, 9, 2}
local result = sort_third(t)
for i = 1, #result do
    print(result[i], ' ')
end
```

Please note that Lua uses 1-based indexing, so a few adjustments were made to account for that. Also, print function in Lua doesn't support output using '<<' operator, so it is replaced with the 'print' function.
<|end|>


