Develop a React application that incorporates a dual route system with distinct destinations: Home and About. Each of these routes should correspond to its individual component.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
To create a dual route React application, we're going to use React Router, which is a collection of navigational components that compose declaratively with your application. And it’s simple to drop down to native React primitives at any time if you need more power.

1. First, create a new React project if you haven’t done so, and move into the project directory.
    ```bash
    $ npx create-react-app react-router

    $ cd react-router
    ```
2. Install react-router-dom package as it contains the DOM bindings for React Router.
    ```bash
    $ npm install react-router-dom
    ```
3. Create two folders named ‘components’ and ‘pages’ inside the ‘src’ folder. Inside the ‘pages’ folder create two new JavaScript files ‘Home.js’ and ‘About.js’. Inside the 'components' folder create ‘NavigationBar.js’. Your file structure should look like this now:
    ```
    /src
      /components
        NavigationBar.js
      /pages
        Home.js
        About.js
      App.js
    ```
4. Inside the Home.js file, add the following code:
    ```jsx
    import React from 'react';

    const Home = () => {
        return (
            <div>
                <h1>Home Page</h1>
            </div>
        )
    }

    export default Home;
    ```
5. Inside the About.js file, add the following code:
    ```jsx
    import React from 'react';

    const About = () => {
        return (
            <div>
                <h1>About Page</h1>
            </div>
        )
    }

    export default About;
    ```
6. Now you need to make a NavBar component for routing. Inside the NavigationBar.js, add the following code:
    ```jsx
    import React from 'react';
    import { Link } from 'react-router-dom';

    const NavigationBar = () => {
        return (
            <nav>
                <ul>
                    <li><Link to="/">Home</Link></li>
                    <li><Link to="/about">About</Link></li>
                </ul>
            </nav>
        )
    }

    export default NavigationBar;
    ```
7. In the 'App.js' file, define your routes to each page with `<Route />` component and wrap all routes with `<Switch />` component to display only the first `<Route />` or `<Redirect />` that matches the location. Wrap all the things inside the `<BrowserRouter />` component. 
    ```jsx
    import React from 'react';
    import {BrowserRouter as Router, Route, Switch} from 'react-router-dom';
    import Home from './pages/Home';
    import About from './pages/About';
    import NavigationBar from './components/NavigationBar';

    function App() {
        return (
            <Router>
                <NavigationBar/>
                <Switch>
                    <Route path="/" exact component={Home}/>
                    <Route path="/about" component={About}/>
                </Switch>
            </Router>
        );
    }

    export default App;
    ```
8. Now you can run your app:
    ```bash
    $ npm start
    ```
Now, you can navigate between these two pages by clicking on the links in the navbar. When you click on the 'Home', it takes you to the home page and when you click on the 'About', it takes you to the about page.
<|end|>


