Formulate a JavaScript function that not only validates if the precise character sequence "Hello World" can be identified within another particular string, but also determines the number of occurrences of the sequence within the string. Furthermore, modify the function to allow for case sensitivity or insensitivity according to a defined parameter. Implement error handling to return special messages when an invalid data type is passed in as the input string. Finally, the function should also be able to identify and ignore any leading or trailing whitespaces in the input string. 

For instance, the string input: "Hello World is a universally recognised statement. hello world again, my dear Hello World!", with case insensitive option given, should return a count of 3 occurrences of "Hello World".
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a JavaScript function that accomplishes all of the required tasks:

```javascript
function searchOccurrences(input, caseSensitive = false) {
    if (typeof input === 'string') {
        // trim leading/trailing white spaces
        input = input.trim();
        
        // if not case-sensitive, convert strings to lower case
        if (!caseSensitive) input = input.toLowerCase();

        let counter = 0;
        let position = input.indexOf("hello world");

        while (position !== -1) {  // -1 indicates no further "hello world" found
            counter++;
            position = input.indexOf("hello world", position + 1);  // next position from previous position
        }
        return counter;
    } 
    else {
        return 'Invalid data type. Please input a string.';
    }
}
```

You can call the function like this:

```javascript
console.log(searchOccurrences("Hello World is a universally recognised statement. hello world again, my dear Hello World!"));  // Case-insensitive, 3 occurrences
console.log(searchOccurrences("Hello World is a universally recognised statement. hello world again, my dear Hello World!", true));  // Case-sensitive, 1 occurrences
```

This function checks if the input is a string and if not, returns an error message. It trims the input and, if the `caseSensitive` parameter is false, it converts the input to lower case. It then checks for occurrences of "hello world" in the string and increments a counter each time it finds one. The counter is then returned as the result.
<|end|>


