Sure! Here is a simple CSS style you could use to change the background of an element of a paragraph to a subtle shade of light blue:

```css
p {
  background-color: #f0f8ff; /* this color is also known as AliceBlue */
  /*For a smooth transition, you could include a transition property*/
  transition: background-color 0.5s ease;
}
```

In this CSS style:
- The `"p"` is the selector, here it targets all the paragraph elements in your HTML document.
- The `"background-color: #f0f8ff;"` is the property and value, `#f0f8ff` is a type of light blue also called AliceBlue.
- The `"transition: background-color 0.5s ease;"` is an optional property and value that provides a smooth transition when changing the background.
  
Just add this block of code to your CSS file or inside a `<style>` tag in your HTML. Remember this will apply the style to all `p` elements. If you want to apply it specifically to one paragraph, you can use an id or class. For example:

```html
<p id="bluebg">This is a paragraph</p>
```

Then target the id in your CSS:

```css
#bluebg {
  background-color: #f0f8ff;
  transition: background-color 0.5s ease;
}
```
This will only apply the style to the paragraph with the id "bluebg".
