I am attempting to consolidate user transactions into lists using pandas, but I am struggling to create a list that includes more than one field. For instance, consider the following dataframe:

df = pd.DataFrame({'user':[1,1,2,2,3], 
                   'time':[20,10,11,18, 15], 
                   'amount':[10.99, 4.99, 2.99, 1.99, 10.99]})
which appears as follows:

    amount  time  user
0   10.99    20     1
1    4.99    10     1
2    2.99    11     2
3    1.99    18     2
4   10.99    15     3
When I execute:

print(df.groupby('user')['time'].apply(list))
I receive:

user
1    [20, 10]
2    [11, 18]
3        [15]
However, when I execute:

df.groupby('user')[['time', 'amount']].apply(list)
I receive:

user
1    [time, amount]
2    [time, amount]
3    [time, amount]
Thanks to a previous response, I discovered I can execute:

df.groupby('user').agg(lambda x: x.tolist()))
to receive:

             amount      time
user                         
1     [10.99, 4.99]  [20, 10]
2      [2.99, 1.99]  [11, 18]
3           [10.99]      [15]
However, I need to sort time and amounts in the same order to sequentially process each user's transactions.

I was hoping to generate this dataframe:
                  amount-time-tuple
user                               
1     [[20.0, 10.99], [10.0, 4.99]]
2      [[11.0, 2.99], [18.0, 1.99]]
3                   [[15.0, 10.99]]

Is there a method to sort without "tupling" the two columns?

Solution:
&lt;code&gt;
import pandas as pd

df = pd.DataFrame({'user':[1,1,2,2,3], 'time':[20,10,11,18, 15], 'amount':[10.99, 4.99, 2.99, 1.99, 10.99]})
### Output your answer into variable 'result'
&lt;/code&gt;
result = ... # put solution in this variable
BEGIN SOLUTION
&lt;code&gt;
<|end|>
<|asst|>
df['amount-time-tuple'] = list(zip(df.time, df.amount))
result = df.groupby('user')['amount-time-tuple'].apply(list)
result = result.reset_index()
result&lt;/code&gt;
