<|asst|>
Handling errors in LANSA when using COM objects like Word VBA methods can be complicated, as this would depend on the nature of the error being returned from the COM object. There is no specific method to capture these errors directly within LANSA.

However, you can follow these general approaches to handle errors in LANSA with COM objects:

1. **Use LANSA's Built-in Error Code:** LANSA has a built-in *#com_owner.command_return* function that you can use to check the status after a command was issued. You can use an IF statement to check the value of #com_owner.command_return after the command, and then handle the error based on your requirement.

2. **Use TRY/CATCH in VBA:** As you're using VBA methods, you can use the built-in error handling in VBA. You can surround your code in a Try/Catch block to handle any errors that are thrown when the code is executed. You would need to write the VBA code to handle the error, then return the error to LANSA for further processing.

For example:

```vba
Sub SampleVBAFunction()
    On Error GoTo ErrorHandler
 
    '... Your Code ...
 
ExitHere:   
    Exit Sub

ErrorHandler: 
    'Handle error
    Resume ExitHere   
End Sub
```

3. **Global Error Handling Routine:** Set up a global error handling routine on LANSA level. This task is more involved and depends on your specific LANSA environment. You might want to reach out to LANSA support for more detailed instructions.

Remember that error handling in complex environments like the one you have (LANSA + MS Word COM objects) isn't always straightforward. It is recommended to have a well-thought-out error handling strategy.

Please note that LANSA may not be able to catch or handle every error type from Word VBA or COM objects, this is why using VBA's own error handling mechanisms is highly recommended.
