The above code can be optimized by reducing the number of I/O operations (print here) by merging the data into one string and printing that string only once. The usage of python generators can decrease memory consumption. If data is already a list of numbers, iterating over string formatted numbers can be done with the generator. Here is a suggestion to optimize the code for a large dataset:

```python
def format_data(data):
    return ", ".join((f"{i:.2f}" for i in data))

data = [17.45739184, 19.38927384, 23.23892384, 42.2389238491]
print(format_data(data))
```

In this code, `f"{i:.2f}"` is a string formatting syntax introduced in Python 3.6 that allows us to embed the expression inside string literals in `{}` brackets, `.2f` used to get float number up to 2 decimal places. `join()` is a string method which takes a sequence and converts it into a string. The `join()` method provides a flexible way to create a string from iterable objects. The generator expression `(f"{i:.2f}" for i in data)` makes efficient use of memory when the list of data is large. 

The time complexity of the code is O(n) and the space complexity is also O(n) where n is the length of the input list. The code is efficient and handles the data in an understandable way.
<|end|>


