How do I create a fill color between "the plot and a horizontal line" whenever the "plot" is above the "horizontal line"?
I can only seem to do it for plot and plot or hline and hline, but never both.
Example here I want to make the color filled between the ema 20 and the line, whenever ema is above 220.

//@version=5
indicator("My script")

ema = ta.ema(close, 20)
hline = hline(220)

fill(hline, ema, color=color.red)
<|end|>
<|asst|>
In Pine Script version 5, you can't directly fill between a simple horizontal line and a plotted line if the condition is if one is above the other. However, you can plot a line at a constant level (i.e., horizontal line), with the `plot` function and then use the `fill` function between it and another plotted line.

Based on your request, here is the correct way to do it:

```pinescript
//@version=5
indicator("My script")

ema = ta.ema(close, 20)
value = 220
plot(value, "Value Line", color=color.blue)
plot(ema, "EMA Line", color=color.red)
fill(plot(ema), plot(value), color=color.red, transp=80)
```

The `fill` function works by taking two series' as arguments and shades the area between them. Here the `plot` function is used to create the series', one is for the EMA line and the second is a line at a constant value of 220. The color for filling is also specified as red, and transparency is set to 80. This will fill the area between these two lines with red color when the EMA line is above the constant value line.

Also, you can add a custom condition to only fill when the EMA line crosses above the value line:

```pinescript
//@version=5
indicator("My script")

ema = ta.ema(close, 20)
value = 220
plot(value, "Value Line", color=color.blue)
plot(ema, "EMA Line", color=color.red)
fill(plot(ema), plot(value), color=color.red, transp=80, when = ema > value)
```

This `when` argument in the `fill` function allows you to visually depict when a particular condition is met. In this case, it fills the area with red when the EMA line is greater than the constant value line.
<|end|>


