Delve into the supplied HTML-based webpage, architecting a data structure utilizing an array framework that encapsulates all the 'h2' elements — designated as second-tier headings — nested within the confines of the webpage.
<html>
    <body>
        <h1>This is a Heading</h1>
        <h2>This is a Sub Heading</h2>
        <h2>This is another Sub Heading</h2>
    </body>
</html>
<|end|>
<|asst|>
You can use BeautifulSoup, a Python library, to help parse HTML:

Here is a Python solution:

```python
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

html_doc = """
<html>
    <body>
        <h1>This is a Heading</h1>
        <h2>This is a Sub Heading</h2>
        <h2>This is another Sub Heading</h2>
    </body>
</html>
"""

# Use 'html.parser' to parse the page
soup = BeautifulSoup(html_doc, 'html.parser')

# instantiate an array to hold the headings
h2_titles = []

# Find all of the <h2> tags on the page
for tag in soup.find_all('h2'):
    # add the text of each <h2> tag to the `h2_titles` array
    h2_titles.append(tag.get_text())

# Print h2_titles to verify it contains all titles present in the HTML file
print(h2_titles)
```

When you run this script, it will print: ['This is a Sub Heading', 'This is another Sub Heading'], which is an array of the text inside the `<h2>` elements.
