&lt;p&gt;A &lt;b&gt;Gaussian integer&lt;/b&gt;, also known as an Eisenstein integer, is a complex number $z = a + bi$ where $a$, $b$ are integers and $i^2 = -1$.&lt;br&gt;
These integers are a subset of the complex numbers, and the integers are the subset of Gaussian integers for which $b = 0$.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A Gaussian integer &lt;strong&gt;unit&lt;/strong&gt;, or a Gaussian integer of absolute value 1, is one for which $a^2 + b^2 = 1$, i.e. one of $1, i, -1, -i$.&lt;br&gt;
We will define a &lt;dfn&gt;proper&lt;/dfn&gt; Gaussian integer as one for which $a \gt 0$ and $b \ge 0$.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A Gaussian integer $z_1 = a_1 + b_1 i$ is said to be divisible by $z_2 = a_2 + b_2 i$ if $z_3 = a_3 + b_3 i = z_1 / z_2$ is a Gaussian integer.&lt;br&gt;
$\frac {z_1} {z_2} = \frac {a_1 + b_1 i} {a_2 + b_2 i} = \frac {(a_1 + b_1 i)(a_2 - b_2 i)} {(a_2 + b_2 i)(a_2 - b_2 i)} = \frac {a_1 a_2 + b_1 b_2} {a_2^2 + b_2^2} + \frac  {a_2 b_1 - a_1 b_2}  {a_2^2 + b_2^2}i = a_3 + b_3 i$&lt;br&gt;
Thus, $z_1$ is divisible by $z_2$ if $\frac {a_1 a_2 + b_1 b_2} {a_2^2 + b_2^2}$ and $\frac  {a_2 b_1 - a_1 b_2}  {a_2^2 + b_2^2}$ are integers.&lt;br&gt;
For instance, $2$ is divisible by $1 + i$ because $2/(1 + i) = 1 - i$ is a Gaussian integer.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;Gaussian prime&lt;/strong&gt;, or an irreducible Gaussian integer, is a Gaussian integer that is divisible only by a unit, itself or itself times a unit.&lt;br&gt;
For instance, $1 + 2i$ is a Gaussian prime, because it is only divisible by $1$, $i$, $-1$, $-i$, $1 + 2i$, $i(1 + 2i) = i - 2$, $-(1 + 2i) = -1 - 2i$ and $-i(1 + 2i) = 2 - i$.&lt;br&gt;
$2$ is not a Gaussian prime as it is divisible by $1 + i$.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A Gaussian integer can be uniquely factored as the product of a unit and proper Gaussian primes.&lt;br&gt;
For instance $2 = -i(1 + i)^2$ and $1 + 3i = (1 + i)(2 + i)$.&lt;br&gt;
A Gaussian integer is said to be squarefree if its prime factorization does not contain repeated proper Gaussian primes.&lt;br&gt;
So $2$ is not squarefree over the Gaussian integers, but $1 + 3i$ is.&lt;br&gt;
Units and Gaussian primes are squarefree by definition.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let $f(n)$ be the count of proper squarefree Gaussian integers with $a^2 + b^2 \le n$.&lt;br&gt;
For instance $f(10) = 7$ because $1$, $1 + i$, $1 + 2i$, $1 + 3i = (1 + i)(1 + 2i)$, $2 + i$, $3$ and $3 + i = -i(1 + i)(1 + 2i)$ are squarefree, while $2 = -i(1 + i)^2$ and $2 + 2i = -i(1 + i)^3$ are not.&lt;br&gt;
You are given $f(10^2) = 54$, $f(10^4) = 5218$ and $f(10^8) = 52126906$.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Determine the value of $f(10^{14})$.&lt;/p&gt;
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Given the mathematical complexity and computational intensity of this problem, this is a suitable application for symbolic computation using Python with the help of the SymPy library. 

Firstly, we will define a function to generate all complex numbers $z = a + bi$ with $a^2 + b^2 ≤ n$. By using the SymPy library, we will then define the divisibility conditions of a Gaussian integer $z_1 = a_1 + b_1 i$ by $z_2 = a_2 + b_2 i$, by verifying that $a = a_1 a_2 + b_1 b_2$ and $b = a_2 b_1 - a_1 b_2$ are integers.

Once the list of Gaussian integers are created, we then determine the Gaussian primes by checking the divisibility condition for every combination of these numbers and retain only those which are not divisible by any other. Furthermore, we define the function to check the squarefree numbers by directly looking for repetitions in the factorization of Gaussian integers. 

Finally, the function $f(n)$ is implemented by counting the number of proper squarefree Gaussian integers for a given $n$. The result of $f(10^{14})$ is then computed using this function.

However, this approach could be infeasible due to computational constraints, as the volume of calculations required for such a large $n$ are massive. Therefore, other optimization strategies or mathematical observations may need to be applied.
<|end|>


