My current view is no, prefer Transact SQL stored procedures because they are a lighter weight and (possibly) higher performing option, while CLR procedures allow developers to get up to all sorts of mischief.

However recently I have needed to debug some very poorly written TSQL stored procs.  As usual I found many of the problems due to the original developer developer having no real TSQL experience, they were  ASP.NET / C# focused.

So, using CLR procedures would firstly provide a much more familiar toolset to this type of developer, and secondly, the debugging and testing facilities are more powerful (ie Visual Studio instead of SQL Management Studio).  

I'd be very interested in hearing your experience as it's seems it is not a simple choice.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Both CLR and Transact SQL stored procedures have their advantages and they can be used according to the needs of the programmer and the application.

Advantages of CLR stored procedures:

1. Flexibility and power: CLR can use the full power of .NET languages, take advantage of .NET libraries, and offers features that T-SQL doesn't have.
2. Better programming model: CLR has a more powerful programming model, which can be easier for application developers to pick up and provides more capabilities such as exception handling and static typing.
3. Performance: CLR stored procedures can perform certain complex operations, calculations and complex algorithms much faster than T-SQL.

Advantages of Transact SQL stored procedures:

1. Performance and resource usage: When it comes to basic database operations like the CRUD operations, T-SQL performs better.
2. Simplicity: T-SQL is simpler to use for basic database operations. It is designed specifically for SQL Server and is easy to use for SQL developers.
3. Security: T-SQL stored procedures can limit data exposure through controlled interfaces.
4. Business Logic: T-SQL excels at writing set-based operations and is ideally suited to data access and manipulation tasks that directly translate to SQL.

In terms of debugging, it depends on what you're more comfortable with. If you are familiar with Visual Studio, then debugging CLR stored procedures would be easier. However, if you're not, there are robust tools available for debugging T-SQL stored procedures as well, including SQL Server Profiler and the debugging tools in SQL Server Management Studio.

So, to sum up, both CLR and T-SQL stored procedures have their uses. CLR procedures are powerful and flexible, provide more advanced programming model and better handle complex computations. T-SQL procedures are best for simpler, set-based operations, it’s lightweight and excels in security and primary data manipulation tasks. Choose the right tool for the right job, depending on your familiarity and task requirements.
<|end|>


