Refine the Python code that ascertains the primality of a number using a mapping structure. It should return- correctly- a boolean value of 'true' for prime digits and 'false' for non-prime digits. Moreover, devise an ancillary process that can hash numerals to enhance computational performance. Employ an out of the box strategy to bolster the runtime of compute_primality_hash(n) function: 

def compute_primality_hash(n, ancillary_process):
    """
    Returns true for prime numbers, false for non-prime numbers. Uses a map entity and an 
    unconventional efficiency-improvement technique. Requires an ancillary process to compute the hash of 'n'.
    
    >>> compute_primality_hash(6, ancillary_process)
    False
    >>> compute_primality_hash(101, ancillary_process)
    True
    >>> compute_primality_hash(11, ancillary_process)
    True
    >>> compute_primality_hash(13441, ancillary_process)
    True
    >>> compute_primality_hash(61, ancillary_process)
    True
    >>> compute_primality_hash(4, ancillary_process)
    False
    >>> compute_primality_hash(1, ancillary_process)
    False
    """
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a solution using python, using Sieve of Eratosthenes algorithm to generate a list of prime numbers up to the given number, then checking if it exists in the list of prime numbers or not. Also it involves memoization technique which essentially does stores the expensive function calls and returns the cached result when the same inputs occur again which can be refered as hashing approach here.

Note: Sieve of Eratosthenes algorithm is an algorithm for finding all prime numbers up to any given limit. Here we are going to use it to generate the list of all primes till n and then simply will check if n exists in the list or not, for validating its primality.

```python
def ancillary_process(n):
    primes = [True for i in range(n+1)]
    p = 2
    while (p * p <= n):
        if (primes[p] == True):
            for i in range(p * p, n+1, p):
                primes[i] = False
        p += 1
    primeNumbers = [p for p in range(2, n) if primes[p]]
    return primeNumbers

cache = {}

def compute_primality_hash(n, ancillary_process):
    if n in cache:
        return cache[n]
    else:
        primeNumbers = ancillary_process(1000000) # Generaring list of all primes till 1000000
        check = n in primeNumbers
        cache[n] = check
        return check
```

This is the final prime number checking function and one ancillary_process function where it generates a list of all prime Numbers till 1000000 using Sieve of Eratosthenes algorithm.

The `compute_primality_hash` function also uses caching (memoization technique), so subsequent calls to check a number if it's prime or not, will execute faster if it's already been calculated before.
<|end|>


