?>
```
In the server-side(PHP) code, first, we are receiving the post data, validating using built-in PHP filter_var function. The `FILTER_VALIDATE_EMAIL` filter validates whether the input is a valid email address.

To prevent XSS and SQL-injection attacks, make sure you:

1. Use prepared statements to avoid SQL injection. The exact implementation depends on the database you are using.

2. Use htmlentities() or htmlspecialchars() functions which convert special characters to their HTML entities and this can prevent most XSS attacks. 

(Note: Handling security issues such as XSS and SQL injection via JavaScript validation is not recommended because client-side code can easily be disabled or modified.) 

PS: In a real production environment, you'd also use additional server-side validation and various secure coding practices to prevent both XSS and SQL Injection attacks. Client-side validation is just a first check and the real security check would happen on the server side.

I have also used a very simple method for checking email validity. In a real-world scenario, email validation can get very complex due to the wide variety of valid email address formats and rules. 

Remember, always sanitize and validate on the server side, no matter what you have done on the client side. Never trust user's input.

Also, remember that an actual process of securing a form against these types of attacks is little more complex and requires in-depth knowledge of secure programming practices.
<|end|>


