<|asst|>
Creating an event handler can be a bit tricky because WPF buttons in a style cannot directly trigger an event on your page. This is due to WPF's scoping rules for names within a XAML namescope. But we can use commands to achieve this. 

A command is a way in WPF to bind events from the UI to actions in your code-behind or ViewModel.

Modify your style to use a Button command instead of a click event:


<Style x:Key="UsersTimeOffList"  TargetType="{x:Type ListBoxItem}">
    ...
    <Grid>
      <Button x:Name="btnRemove" Content="Remove" Margin="0,10,40,0" 
             Command="{Binding RelativeSource={RelativeSource AncestorType={x:Type YourPage}}, Path=DataContext.YourCommand}" 
             CommandParameter="{Binding}"/>
    </Grid>
</Style>


Now in your ViewModel (or code-behind if you haven't used MVVM), you create this command.


public ICommand YourCommand => new RelayCommand<UserTimeOffModel>(RemoveUser);

private void RemoveUser(UserTimeOffModel model)
{
    ...//Implement your event here.
}


Make sure to replace "YourCommand" by whatever name you want for your command and UserTimeOffModel by the item your list box must be bound with.

Finally, ensure that DataContext of your page is set to its ViewModel instance in your page constructor or in XAML:

`this.DataContext = new YourViewModel();`

Remember to install MvvmLight or similar pack via Nuget to use RelayCommand or implement your own RelayCommand.

In this approach, each time your button is pressed, the "YourCommand" will be invoked with the ListBoxItem as a parameter.
