What is the considerable approach that can be adopted to instigate superposition of manifold HTML elements while ensuring a particular one is foregrounded in a web page layout?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
This problem of superposition of manifold HTML elements and ensuring a particular one is foregrounded in a web page layout can be solved using CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) in two possible ways:

1. Using Z-Index: The z-index is a CSS property that allows you to position an element in a stack order (z-axis). An element with a higher z-index will be in front of an element with a lower z-index.
   
   For example:

   CSS:

```css
  /* this will put the division with id foreground on top */
  #foreground {
      z-index: 3;
  }

  #midground {
      z-index: 2;
  }

  #background {
      z-index: 1;
  }
```
It's important to note that z-index only works on positioned elements (e.g, position:absolute, position:relative, or position:fixed).

2. Overlapping Elements: Another approach to solve this problem is to overlap the elements using the position property and top, right, bottom, left properties.

  For example:

  CSS:
```css
  /* this will make the HTML elements overlap each other */
  #foreground {
      position:absolute;
      left:0;
  }

  #midground {
      position:absolute;
      left:0;
  }

  #background {
      position:absolute;
      left:0;
  }
```
After this, the content in 'foreground' div will always stay at the top.
<|end|>


