Given a list of sentences, capitalize the first letter of every word in each sentence.
sentences = ["this is a test.", "hello world.", "python is great."]
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a Python solution for your problem using list comprehension and the `title()` string method which capitalizes the first letter of each word in a sentence.

```python
sentences = ["this is a test.", "hello world.", "python is great."]

capitalized_sentences = [sentence.title() for sentence in sentences]
print(capitalized_sentences)
```

When you run this program, it gives the following output:

```shell
['This Is A Test.', 'Hello World.', 'Python Is Great.']
```

Please note that the `title()` method will also capitalize the letters following apostrophes which may not be the desired behavior for certain applications. For example, "don't" would be converted to "Don'T".

If you want to get around this, you could use the `str.capitalize()` function. However, `str.capitalize()` only capitalizes the first letter of the string and makes the other characters lowercase. You would need to split the string into words, then apply `str.capitalize()` to each word, like so:

```python
sentences = ["this is a test.", "hello world.", "python is great."]

capitalized_sentences = [' '.join([word.capitalize() for word in sentence.split()]) for sentence in sentences]
print(capitalized_sentences)
```

This will produce:

```shell
['This Is A Test.', 'Hello World.', 'Python Is Great.']
```
<|end|>


