I've tested a number of fruit samples for weight loss over time (shelf-life assessment).
I want to compare weight loss between the different samples.
My initial idea was to use a linear regression model for each sample and then compare the models' estimates.
Is this the right way to tackle this issue and if so, which tests should I use for this?
P.S I'm using R
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Yes, Linear regression can be used to model this data, but you may want to use a mixed-effects model (also called hierarchical linear models or random effects models) or repeated measures ANOVA if your data have some sort of structure or correlation. 

Mixed-effects models would allow you to account for both fixed effects (the effects you're interested in, such as the type of fruit) and random effects (other sources of variation, such as differences between subjects). 

To implement this in R, you can use the 'lme4' or 'nlme' package. The 'lme4' package has a function called 'lmer' that can be used to fit mixed-effects models. 

If your data doesn't have any structure (i.e., each observation is independent of each other), ANOVA or multiple linear regression could also work. In R, you can use the 'aov' or 'lm' function to do this.

To compare models, you can use the 'anova' function in R.

Keep in mind that choosing the right statistical method also strongly depends on the type and structure of your data and business/hypothesis question, and sometimes more advanced techniques, such as time series analysis, might be required.

Always be careful about assumptions of the model and check whether your data meet those assumptions before running the model, this will largely increase the chance that your results could represent the real-world situation.
<|end|>


