Creating a visually appealing layout for a website's homepage involves defining CSS styles for various elements such as headers, paragraphs, links, images, and sections. Here's a simple example of a CSS style sheet:

```css
/* Define the body style */
body {
    font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    background-color: #f0f0f0;
}

/* Define the header style */
header {
    background-color: #333;
    color: white;
    padding: 10px;
    text-align: center;
}

/* Define the main section style */
main {
    margin: 15px;
    padding: 15px;
    background-color: #fff;
    box-shadow: 0px 0px 10px 0px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);
}

/* Style for h1 elements */
h1 {
    color: #333;
}

/* Style for h2 elements */
h2 {
    color: #666;
}

/* Style for paragraphs */
p {
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: #333;
}

/* Style for links */
a {
    color: #333;
    text-decoration: none;
}

a:hover {
    color: #669;
}

/* Define a style for images */
img {
    max-width: 100%;
    height: auto;
}

/* Footer style */
footer {
    background-color: #333;
    color: white;
    text-align: center;
    padding: 10px;
    position: fixed;
    bottom: 0;
    width: 100%;
}
```

This is a very basic layout and can be made much more sophisticated depending on your needs. You might also consider using a CSS framework like Bootstrap, Foundation, or Bulma to expedite development and improve the professional appearance of your website.

Please note, CSS is all about styling and look-and-feel, and the final choice of colours, fonts, sizes, and other attributes will really depend on the overall design theme and requirement of your website.
