How to interpret the state error variance in the hierarchical random walk plus noise model?
Suppose I want to show how Urbanization percentage changed across time (t = 10) in 25 different countries (g = 25), so it is a hierarchical dynamic model. Suppose the software shows that in the model above the mean of the standard deviation of the state error variance is 0.05 (5%). How would the formal interpretation of it look like?
Please look at the picture below outlining the same question with some mathematical clarifications
[](https://i.stack.imgur.com/fB4QJ.png)
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The state error variance (also known as process variance) in a hierarchical random walk plus noise model quantifies the variability in the underlying, unobservable process. This process represents the "true" urbanization percentage that changes across time.

In this context, a standard deviation of 0.05 (5%) for the state error variance, fundamentally, means that there is a variability or movement in the "true" underlying urbanization process across time. 

Formally, one can interpret this as follows: "The standard deviation of 0.05 in the hierarchical random walk plus noise model indicates that the 'true' unobserved Urbanization percentage for a typical country typically fluctuates from one year to the next by approximately 5%." 

Further, this also may imply that 68.27% of the time (1 standard deviation in a normal distribution), you would expect the underlying urbanization percentage of any given country to vary from one year to the next by no more than 5%. 

So, essentially, this value gives us an idea about the inherent volatility or instability in the urbanization process across time. However, it is also worth noting that this interpretation assumes that the underlying urbanization process follows a Gaussian (normal) distribution. If the distribution of the process is non-normal, the interpretation might change.
<|end|>


