Create a CSS3 animation that moves an element in a sinusoidal path (oscillating up and down) while also moving from left to right. The animation should have customizable duration, amplitude, and frequency.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
It's possible to create an oscillating animation with CSS3, but it's not easy to achieve a sinusoidal motion because CSS3 animations are limited to linear transitions between specific points.

HTML/CSS on its own does not allow for customizable "amplitude" and "frequency" or non-linear motions like a sine wave. This kind of animation requires JavaScript or a complex combination of CSS animations.

Here is a JavaScript solution utilizing CSS Transformations:

HTML:
```html
<div id="animatedElement"></div>
```

CSS:
```css
#animatedElement {
  position: absolute;
  height: 50px;
  width: 50px;
  background-color: red;
}
```

JavaScript:
```javascript
const amplitude = 100;
const frequency = 1;
const duration = 2000;

const animatedElement = document.getElementById('animatedElement');

const animate = time => {
  const t = (time / duration) * 2 * Math.PI * frequency;
  const y = Math.sin(t) * amplitude;

  animatedElement.style.transform = `translate(${time / 10}px, ${y}px)`;

  if (time <= duration) {
    requestAnimationFrame(animate);
  }
};

requestAnimationFrame(animate);
```

This script will animate the element with an id of 'animatedElement'. The animation moves the element in a sinusoidal path by changing the 'transform' property of the element over time. 

The 'amplitude' variable controls the height of the waves, 'frequency' sets the number of oscillations, and 'duration' determines the total time of the animation. All these variables can be customized. The script uses 'requestAnimationFrame' to create the animation, which is a function that tells the browser to perform an animation and requests that the browser call a specified function to update an animation before the next repaint.

Please note that this script needs to run in an environment where it has access to the DOM such as a browser. Make sure to place the JavaScript code in a script tag at the end of the body, or defer/async your script if it's in the head, otherwise the 'document.getElementById' might not be able to find the element.
<|end|>


