Create a JavaScript program to switch between two div components, while keeping track of the number of switches, and without using any external libraries. The program should cease to switch after 1000 switches have taken place.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a solution using Vanilla JavaScript, which follows the requirements and makes use of event handlers:

```javascript
// HTML Elements
let div1 = document.getElementById('div1');
let div2 = document.getElementById('div2');

// Create a switch boolean
let switchState = false;

// Create a counter for number of switches
let switchCount = 0;

function switchDiv() {
  // Check if switch count has reached 1000.
  // If it has, remove the event listener and stop switching
  if (switchCount == 1000) {
    div1.removeEventListener('click', switchDiv);
    div2.removeEventListener('click', switchDiv);
    console.log("Switch count limit reached!");
    return;
  }
  
  // Switch visibility between div elements
  if (switchState) {
    div1.style.display = "none";
    div2.style.display = "block";
  } else {
    div1.style.display = "block";
    div2.style.display = "none";
  }
  
  // Toggle switch state
  switchState = !switchState;
  
  // Increment switch count
  switchCount++;
}

// Add event listeners to div elements
div1.addEventListener('click', switchDiv);
div2.addEventListener('click', switchDiv);
```

Make sure your div1 and div2 have some text or border, otherwise you will not be able to see a div without content when it's displayed.

This program will initially display div1 and hide div2, then switch the visibility each time one of the divs is clicked. This will continue until the divs have been swapped 1000 times, at which point the event listeners will be removed and the divs will no longer be swapped on click. Please replace 'div1' and 'div2' with your actual div ids.
<|end|>


