Refine the Ruby script provided to factor in weekends and public holidays, to exhibit the actual working duration, in days, a staff member has been engaged in a project assignment. Also, identify any periods of inactivity.
start_project_date = "10 June 2021"
<|end|>
<|asst|>
This problem can be solved using the 'business_time' gem in Ruby which will help to include only business days in the calculation. First, a list of public holidays should be added manually for the respective year.

Here is a refined script for your assignment:

```ruby
require 'business_time'
require 'date'

# Start and End Date of Project
start_project_date = Date.parse("10 June 2021")
end_project_date = Date.today

# Public Holidays List in Date Format
public_holidays = ["4th July 2021", "6th September 2021"].map { |holiday| Date.parse(holiday) }

# Update the Business Time Config to include public holidays.
BusinessTime::Config.holidays = public_holidays

# Find the total working days a staff member has spend by excluding weekends and holidays.
total_work_days = BusinessTime::BusinessDays.business_days_between(start_project_date, end_project_date)

# Print Total Working Days
puts "Total working days by staff: #{total_work_days}"

# Discover the inactive periods/days
project_days =(start_project_date..end_project_date).to_a
inactive_days = project_days - BusinessTime::Config.work_week.business_days
inactive_days = inactive_days - public_holidays

# Print inactive days
puts "Inactive days: #{inactive_days}"
```
This script will return the total workdays from the start of the project to the current day, considering only weekdays and non-holiday dates. It will also provide you with a list of inactive days that were either weekends or public holidays.

Please note that you need to enter the end_project_date manually or it's going to be the current date as per the above script. Also, the list of public_holidays should be updated based on the actual holidays for the respective year.
<|end|>


