My data comes from subjects performing the same task under different conditions—in other words, I have data from each subject under both the control condition and the experimental condition. This seems like a good place to use a paired-sample t-test.
However, each subject also performed the task 32 times (16 under one condition, 16 under the other).
Is there a good way to modify the paired-sample t-test to include multiple measurements of each subject, rather than just one? I know I could just take the mean of the measurements and perform the t-test on that, but that would be completely ignoring the variance within each subject.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Yes, the situation you've described suggests a need to account for the repeated measures from each subject. Here, you should probably consider using a repeated-measures analysis of variance (ANOVA) or a mixed-effects model, as both of these techniques are designed to handle data in which multiple measurements have been taken on each subject.

With a repeated-measures ANOVA, you'll be able to test for differences between the control and experimental conditions while accounting for the within-subject variability. However, this approach assumes that the correlations between the repeated measures on each subject are equal (a condition known as sphericity), which might not be true in all cases.

On the other hand, a mixed-effects model, sometimes also called a multi-level model, will also allow you to model both between-subject and within-subject variances. This approach doesn't require the assumption of equal correlations between the repeated measures, so it provides a more flexible way of modelling your data. And with a mixed-effects model, you can include additional variables (both fixed and random effects) to explain additional parts of the variance in your data.
<|end|>


