<|asst|>
Embarking on a journey through so-called quantum strangeness, we delve deep into the genesis and evolution of quantum entanglement, recognizing it as the bedrock of quantum computing. Conceived in 1935 by Albert Einstein, Boris Podolsky, and Nathan Rosen—the trio collectively known as EPR—quantum entanglement was considered a 'spooky action at a distance', influencing particles regardless of their spatial separation. Simultaneously fascinating and paradoxical, the phenomenon started the process of reshaping our understanding of the quantum world.

The embracement of entanglement as the cornerstone for quantum computing owes much to the theoretical principles that allow us to create powerful quantum algorithms, offering significant improvement over classical counterparts for specific problems. Quantum entanglement—the strange connection that allows particles to share their state no matter how far apart they are—profoundly impacts computing performance. However, the supremacy of these inherently quantum phenomena in computing, while intriguing, is not devoid of challenges. 

Unsurprisingly, physicists have led the journey into harnessing quantum entanglement, seeking to rectify theoretical inconsistencies and embrace its supremacy for improved computing performance. Stringent methods have been developed for identifying and addressing these inconsistencies, capitalizing on a wide range of analytical skills and problem-solving capabilities. 

Regrettably, the state of entanglement is susceptible to perturbation by environmental noise, which can readily cause decoherence—an obstacle for quantum computing. Researchers have dedicated themselves to overcoming these and other roadblocks, developing such tools as quantum error correction techniques. Nevertheless, these solutions are in infancy, creating an ever-present demand for further exploration.

Simultaneously, the innate complexity of quantum superposition and entanglement has head-scratching implications on the maintenance and surveillance of quantum systems. Despite these challenges, academics and researchers continue to innovate, forging effective techniques for handling these intricacies and ensuring their smooth integration into quantum systems.

Quantum entanglement's influence extends beyond computing. In the realm of quantum physics, entanglement paves the path for studying phenomena such as quantum teleportation, quantum communication, and entanglement-assisted quantum metrology, to name a few. Its impact on secure data processing similarly cannot be overstated—quantum cryptography counts entanglement as one of its enabling technologies.

As quantum entanglement becomes ever more entwined with our scientific and technological endeavors, ongoing dialogue scrutinizing the risks and inefficiencies involved is a must. The future of quantum computing depends on rigorous evaluation, continual innovation, and widespread acceptance of theoretical principles rooted in quantum entanglement.

Quantum entanglement creates a robust intertwined architecture for complex theoretical systems. Its mastery has the potential to yield powerful quantum computing infrastructures capable of solving problems classical computers can't efficiently shoulder. It is the potential ramifications of this unique quantum element, across the broad landscape of quantum physics, that underline the future—unfolding a path to more powerful quantum computing and heightening the secure processing of information. If we continue to stretch the boundaries of our understanding, our grip on this peculiar feature of the quantum world will only strengthen.
