What is the best (cleanest, most efficient) way to write saturating addition in C?

The function or macro should add two unsigned inputs (need both 16- and 32-bit versions) and return all-bits-one (0xFFFF or 0xFFFFFFFF) if the sum overflows.

Target is x86 and ARM using gcc (4.1.2) and Visual Studio (for simulation only, so a fallback implementation is OK there).
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Since you have noted that you are targeting x86 and ARM using GCC and Visual Studio compilers, you'll need to write the function and macro with respect to both compilers. 

Below are few possible ways to write the saturating addition in C:

GCC Built-in Function:
GCC provides __builtin_add_overflow() as a built-in function specifically for overflow detection. Here's likely one of the simplest and cleanest ways to write the saturating add using GCC.

```c
#include <stdint.h>
#include <limits.h>

uint16_t saturating_add16(uint16_t x, uint16_t y) {
  uint16_t res;
  if (__builtin_add_overflow(x, y, &res))
    return 65535; //All bits set for 16-bit.
  else
    return res;
}

uint32_t saturating_add32(uint32_t x, uint32_t y) {
  uint32_t res;
  if (__builtin_add_overflow(x, y, &res))
    return UINT_MAX; //All bits set for 32-bit.
  else
    return res;
}
```

This benefits from compiler support and is likely to compile to very efficient code.

For the case of Visual Studio:

Since __builtin_add_overflow() is a GCC-specific function, it won't compile on Visual Studio. A replacement could be the following functions:

```c
#include <stdint.h>

uint16_t saturating_add16(uint16_t x, uint16_t y) {
  uint32_t sum = (uint32_t)x + y;
  return (uint16_t)(sum > UINT16_MAX ? UINT16_MAX : sum);
}

uint32_t saturating_add32(uint32_t x, uint32_t y) {
  uint64_t sum = (uint64_t)x + y;
  return (uint32_t)(sum > UINT32_MAX ? UINT32_MAX : sum);
}
```

This is a bit longer and involves casting, but is a good fallback when __builtin_add_overflow() is not available. 

Please note, although the Visual Studio version will work for GCC as well, it might not generate as efficient code as the version using __builtin_add_overflow().
<|end|>


