Problem:
In the context of Python programming, I am seeking an optimized method to ascertain if a SciPy CSR matrix is devoid of any non-zero elements (i.e., it is a zero matrix). I have been utilizing the nonzero() function as follows:
def is_csr_matrix_only_zeroes(my_csr_matrix):
    return(len(my_csr_matrix.nonzero()[0]) == 0)
from scipy.sparse import csr_matrix
print(is_csr_matrix_only_zeroes(csr_matrix([[1,2,0],[0,0,3],[4,0,5]])))
print(is_csr_matrix_only_zeroes(csr_matrix([[0,0,0],[0,0,0],[0,0,0]])))
print(is_csr_matrix_only_zeroes(csr_matrix((2,3))))
print(is_csr_matrix_only_zeroes(csr_matrix([[0,0,0],[0,1,0],[0,0,0]])))
The output is as follows:
False
True
True
False
However, I am curious if there are more straightforward or computationally efficient methods to achieve this, i.e., to directly obtain a Boolean value?
A:
&lt;code&gt;
from scipy import sparse
sa = sparse.random(10, 10, density = 0.01, format = &#39;csr&#39;)
&lt;/code&gt;
result = ... # put solution in this variable
BEGIN SOLUTION
&lt;code&gt;
<|end|>
<|asst|>
result = sa.nnz == 0
&lt;/code&gt;
This command `sa.nnz == 0` will use the `nnz` attribute of the CSR matrix, which gives the count of explicitly-stored values (including zeros), to check if the CSR matrix is empty or not. If `nnz` attribute is zero, it means the CSR matrix does not have any non-zero elements; and if it is not zero, it means there are non-zero elements in the CSR matrix. This is a quicker and more efficient method.
<|end|>


