<|asst|>
You can't directly convert a tree URI to a File path because modern versions of Android restrict direct file system access in the name of security.

When you want to write to a tree URI, you have to use a `DocumentFile`. Below is the correct way to move forward based on your code: 

```java
final ActivityResultLauncher<Uri> mDirRequest = registerForActivityResult(
        new ActivityResultContracts.OpenDocumentTree(), 
        new ActivityResultCallback<Uri>() {
            @Override
            public void onActivityResult(Uri uriTree) {
                // you have to use the uri path here
                DocumentFile pickedDir = DocumentFile.fromTreeUri(context, uriTree);
                // Create a new file and write into it
                DocumentFile newFile = pickedDir.createFile("application/vnd.ms-excel", "goofy.xlsx");
                try {
                    OutputStream out = getContentResolver().openOutputStream(newFile.getUri());
                    workbook.write(out);
                    out.close();
                } catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
                    e.printStackTrace();
                } catch (IOException e) {
                    e.printStackTrace();
                }
            }
        });

mDirRequest.launch(null);
```

This code assumes that `workbook` is a `org.apache.poi.xssf.usermodel.XSSFWorkbook`. 
Remember that in your manifest you need to request `MANAGE_EXTERNAL_STORAGE` permission. Also, you should handle the edge cases where `createFile` returns `null` (i.e., unable to create the file).
<|end|>


