While SVG does not support adding gradient dithering or texture to give a parchment feel directly, you can relatively reproduce the effect combining various SVG filters and gradients.

And as far as adding the magical runes, you could create SVG paths for each rune and arrange them around the circle. Here's an example of how you might do this conceptually:

```xml
<svg width="600" height="600" viewBox="0 0 600 600" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
  <defs>
    <filter id="parchment" x="0" y="0">
      <feTurbulence type="turbulence" baseFrequency="0.2" seed="2" numOctaves="3" result="turbulence"/>
      <feColorMatrix in="turbulence" mode="matrix" values="0.33 0.33 0.33 0 0 0.33 0.33 0.33 0 0 0.33 0.33 0.33 0 0 0 0 0 1 0" result="colormatrix"/>
      <feComposite in="colormatrix" in2="SourceGraphic" operator="in" result="composite"/>
    </filter>
  </defs>
  <path d="M300 50C165.873 50 50 165.873 50 300C50 434.127 165.873 550 300 550C434.127 550 550 434.127 550 300C550 165.873 434.127 50 300 50Z" fill="#212121" filter="url(#parchment)"/>
  <!-- Here's how you might add some runes -->
  <path d="M300 100 ...Rune SVG path..." fill="#fff" />
  <path d="M350 150 ...Rune SVG path..." fill="#fff" />
</svg>
```

In the above snippet, I've provided you a simple way to make it appear like this SVG is inked with quill. It covers the original circle with a filter that is supposedly taking a turbulence effect to simulate the rough surface.

You need to replace `...Rune SVG path...` with the actual SVG paths for the runes.

Please note that this is just a placeholder and would require you to design SVG paths manually or generate with a tool that best suits how you want each of these "magical runes" to look like.
