Write a Java code that implements an efficient algorithm for reversing an ordered array of integers. Your code should be capable of handling larger inputs, i.e., an ordered array consisting of 10^6 integers. Subsequently, your algorithm should also compute the sum of the first half and second half of the reversed array separately. Display these two sums as output. The efficiency of your code will be evaluated based on its time and space complexity.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is the Java code that performs in O(n) time and O(1) space.

This code firstly reverses the array by swapping elements in-place, and then calculate the sum of the first half and second half.

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Assuming an array of size 10^6
        int[] array = new int[1000000];
        
        // Init array in sequential order for demonstration
        for (int i = 0; i < array.length; i++) {
            array[i] = i + 1;
        }
        
        // Reverse array in-place, no extra memory used
        for (int i = 0; i < array.length / 2; i++) {
            int temp = array[i];
            array[i] = array[array.length - i - 1];
            array[array.length - i - 1] = temp;
        }
        
        // Calculation of sum of first half and second half
        long sum_first_half = 0, sum_second_half = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i < array.length / 2; i++) {
            sum_first_half += array[i];
        }
        for(int i = array.length / 2; i < array.length; i++) {
            sum_second_half += array[i];
        }
        
        // Output the results
        System.out.println("Sum of first half: " + sum_first_half);
        System.out.println("Sum of second half: " + sum_second_half);
    }
}
```
Thanks to the array being in-place, the space complexity is O(1) which means it uses constant extra space. The time complexity is O(n) as it runs three loops through the array separately. These complexities should make this solution highly efficient for large inputs.
<|end|>


