Generate a function to encrypt a given text using a rotation cipher.
Text: This is a secret message
Rotation: 3
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Sure, here is a Python code illustrating a rotation cipher (also known as Caesar cipher) function:

```python
def rotation_cipher(text, shift):
    result = ""
    for char in text:
        if char.isalpha():
            ascii_offset = ord('a') if char.islower() else ord('A')
            cipher_char = chr((ord(char) - ascii_offset + shift) % 26 + ascii_offset)
            result += cipher_char
        else:
            result += char
    return result

text = "This is a secret message"
rotation = 3
encrypted_text = rotation_cipher(text, rotation)
print(encrypted_text)
```

The function `rotation_cipher` takes a text string and a shift number as parameters. It iterates over every character in the text. If the character is an alphabetic character, it calculates the ASCII value of the result character by shifting the ASCII value of the original character and applying modulo 26 operator, to make sure it stays within the 26 letters of the alphabet. Then it converts the ASCII value back to a character and adds it to the result string. If the character is not an alphabetic character (like space, punctuation, digits), it leaves it unchanged.

When you run this code with "This is a secret message" as the text and 3 as the rotation, it will output "Wklv lv d vhfuhw phvvdjh".
