I know of an equilateral triangle the center (cx,cy) and the radius (r) of a blue circle which circumscribed it.
If I draw a green circle of any radius (radius), assuming the circle is large enough to have this intersection, can I get the coordinates of the 6 intersection points (P1, P2, P3...)?
![Text](https://r-c.es/equilateral.jpg)
I'm looking for P5JS/processing but any other clue can help me...
Thank you in advance
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Yes, it is possible to calculate the coordinates of the 6 intersection points. Looking at the image you provided tactically, I will assume that the green circle is centered at the same point as the blue circle i.e. (cx, cy). If that is not your case, the following method would need minor adjustments. We will solve this problem based on simple trigonometric considerations. Let's discuss the P1 and P2 points, the others being symmetrical to these.

For both P1 and P2, the x-coordinate is the sum of the x-coordinate of the center and the radius of the blue circle times the cosine of a certain angle. This angle is 60 degrees for P1 and 120 degrees for P2. The y-coordinate is the sum of the y-coordinate of the center and the radius of the blue circle times the sine of the same angle.

To calculate the points of the green circle, replace the radius of the blue circle with the radius of the green circle in the formulas for x and y. The angles remain the same.

Here's code example in P5JS:

```js
let cx = 200; // x-coordinate of the center
let cy = 200; // y-coordinate of the center
let rBlue = 100; // radius of the blue circle
let rGreen = 150; // radius of the green circle

let bluePoints = [];
let greenPoints = [];

function setup() {
  createCanvas(400, 400);
  angleMode(DEGREES); // Use degrees for trigonometric calculations
  
  // Calculate points for blue circle
  for (let angle = 60; angle <= 300; angle += 60) {
    let x = cx + rBlue * cos(angle);
    let y = cy + rBlue * sin(angle);
    bluePoints.push(createVector(x, y));
  }
  
  // Calculate points for green circle
  for (let angle = 60; angle <= 300; angle += 60) {
    let x = cx + rGreen * cos(angle);
    let y = cy + rGreen * sin(angle);
    greenPoints.push(createVector(x, y));
  }
}

function draw() {
  background(220);
  
  // Draw circles
  ellipse(cx, cy, rBlue*2);
  ellipse(cx, cy, rGreen*2);
  
  // Draw points
  for (let point of bluePoints) {
    fill(0);
    ellipse(point.x, point.y, 8);
  }
  for (let point of greenPoints) {
    fill(0, 255, 0);
    ellipse(point.x, point.y, 8);
  }
}
```
The "setup" function calculates the x and y coordinates for each point in both circles (bluePoints and greenPoints). In each loop, the angle decreases by 60 degrees, which corresponds to the angle between each point in an equilateral triangle. The "draw" function then displays the two circles and all points. Each point is represented by a small ellipse.
<|end|>


