Here's an SQL command that you can use to add a new column to your "students" table. The column, in this case, is named "new_column". You can change the name accordingly, use appropriate data type and also set it as NULL or NOT NULL based on the requirements. 

```sql
ALTER TABLE students 
ADD COLUMN new_column data_type NULLorNOTNULL;
```

Let's assume the new column needs to be named "email" of type VARCHAR (something that could store e-mails) and it should allow NULL values:

```sql
ALTER TABLE students 
ADD COLUMN email VARCHAR(255) NULL;
```

Remember, however, you want to maintain data integrity. If this column should not have any repeated data (i.e., it should be unique), you can set it as a UNIQUE key:

```sql
ALTER TABLE students
ADD COLUMN email VARCHAR(255) NULL,
ADD UNIQUE (email);
```

These commands adhere to SQL standards and should work in most modern SQL database systems including MySQL, PostgreSQL and SQL Server. Always be sure to modify them according to your actual needs and specific database system.
