I want alwaysPositive to be assigned a positive number with all possible values for lareValue1 and largeValue2 (these are at least 1).

The following statement causes a buffer overflow:


int alwaysPositive = (largeValue1 + largeValue2) / 2;



I know I can prevent it by substracting and adding:


int alwaysPositive = largeValue1 + ((largeValue2 - largeValue1) / 2);



But in other programming languages I can use an unsigned bitshift to do the trick:


int alwaysPositive3 = (largeValue1 + largeValue2) >>> 1;



How can I do this in C#?


---



The answers below all solve the problem. There are probably lots of ways to do this, but they all (including my solutions) have one thing in common: they all look obfuscated.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
In C#, unsigned right shift operator (>>>) is not directly available. However, the same operation can be performed like below:

```C#
uint alwaysPositive = ((uint)largeValue1 + (uint)largeValue2) >> 1;
```

You need to convert the operands to `uint`(unsigned integer) and then use the right shift (>>) operator. This will effectively divide the sum by 2. Convert back to `int`, if necessary.

If largeValue1 and largeValue2 are so large that they may overflow during conversion to uint (those values greater than int.MaxValue but within the range of int), first convert them into long before the operation.

```C#
long alwaysPositive = ((long)largeValue1 + (long)largeValue2) >> 1;
```

Please be aware of the range of your inputs before choosing the above solutions. If your inputs are larger than int.MaxValue (2^31 - 1) but less than or equal to uint.MaxValue (2^32 - 1), you'd want to go with the uint version. If they are larger than uint.MaxValue but less than or equal to long.MaxValue (2^63 - 1) then go with the long version.
<|end|>


