Develop a C# software application that eliminates all recurring instances of a specific element within a numerical array.
arr = [5, 3, 1, 3, 5, 7]
<|end|>
<|asst|>
You can simply use the built-in `Distinct()` method in C# LINQ to eliminate recurring elements in an array. Here is an example of how this can be applied to your given array in a simple console application:

```CSharp
using System;
using System.Linq;

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        int[] arr = { 5, 3, 1, 3, 5, 7 };

        //Eliminate recurring elements
        int[] distinctArr = arr.Distinct().ToArray();

        Console.WriteLine("Distinct Array: ");

        foreach (int item in distinctArr)
        {
            Console.WriteLine(item);
        }

        Console.ReadKey();
    }
}
```

However, if you are looking for a specific item to be removed, you can use the `List.RemoveAll()` method:

```CSharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        List<int> arr = new List<int>{ 5, 3, 1, 3, 5, 7 };

        //Specific element to be removed
        int specificElement = 5;

        //Remove specific element
        arr.RemoveAll(i => i == specificElement);

        Console.WriteLine("Array after removal: ");
        foreach (int item in arr)
        {
            Console.WriteLine(item);
        }

        Console.ReadKey();
    }
}
```
