Could you guide me through the process of merging two pre-sorted arrays into a singular array in-place, utilizing only one pointer for the procedure, in the context of C++ programming language?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Sure, below is the iterative approach to merge two already sorted arrays into one sorted array in-place using one pointer in C++:

In this process, it's assumed that the first array `arr1` has enough empty spaces at the end to accommodate the second array `arr2`.

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

void mergeSortedArrays(int arr1[], int m, int arr2[], int n) {
    int p = m + n - 1; // pointer to place for next element
    m--;
    n--;
    
    while (m >= 0 && n >= 0) { // iterate over both arrays from the end to the beginning
        if(arr1[m] > arr2[n]) { // compare current elements of arrays
            arr1[p] = arr1[m]; // place bigger to the position 'p'
            m--; 
        }
        else {
            arr1[p] = arr2[n];
            n--; 
        }
        p--;
    }
    
    // if there are still elements in arr2 
    while(n >= 0) {
        arr1[p] = arr2[n];
        p--;
        n--;
    }
}

void printArray(int arr[], int size) {
   for(int i=0; i<size; i++) 
      cout<<arr[i]<<" ";
   cout<<endl;
}

int main() {
   int arr1[8] = {1, 3, 5, 7}; // extra vacant space is for arr2 items
   int arr2[4] = {2, 4, 6, 8}; 
   int m = sizeof(arr1) / sizeof(arr1[0]);
   int n = sizeof(arr2) / sizeof(arr2[0]); 
   mergeSortedArrays(arr1, m - n, arr2, n); // m-n gives the size of first array
   printArray(arr1, m); // print merged array
   
   return 0;
}
```

Assumptions:
- Array `arr1[]` has enough space to accommodate the elements of arr2[]. 
- The resultant merged array is a sorted array.
  
In this code, we start comparing the elements of `arr1` and `arr2` from the end and then place the larger one at the end of `arr1`. We repeat this until we have placed all the elements at the right position. 

If `arr2` has still some elements left, then it means these elements are smaller than the smallest elements already considered in `arr1`, so we are directly placing these in the remaining positions.
<|end|>


