Devise a set of instructions written in Assembly language to execute the multiplication operation between two distinct complex numbers, ensuring the optimal handling of the real and imaginary components throughout the process.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Assembly language programs can vary depending on the type of processor architecture the code is intended to run on. Below is a general example of how you can implement a multiplication of two complex numbers in assembly language.

This example uses the fact that (a + bi) * (c + di) = (ac - bd) + (ad + bc)i. 

```
section .data
    X1 db 3 ;real part of the first complex number
    Y1 db 2 ;imaginary part of the first complex number
    X2 db 1 ;real part of the second complex number
    Y2 db 4 ;imaginary part of the second complex number

section .bss
    real_res resb 1 ;
    imag_res resb 1 ;

section .text
    global _start
    _start:

    mov al, [X1]   ; load real part of the first number into register AL
    imul ax, [X2]  ; AL * X2 -> result is stored in AX
    mov [real_res], ax ; store AX into real_res

    mov al, [Y1]  ; load imaginary part of the first number into register AL
    imul ax, [Y2] ; AL * Y2 -> result is stored in AX
    sub [real_res], ax ; subtract AX from real_res


    mov al, [X1]  ; load real part of the first number into register AL
    imul ax, [Y2] ; AL * Y2 -> result is stored in AX
    mov [imag_res], ax ; store AX into imag_res

    mov al, [X2]  ; load imaginary part of the second number into register AL
    imul ax, [Y1] ; AL * Y1 -> result is stored in AX
    add [imag_res], ax ; add AX to imag_res

    ; Here real_res and imag_res hold the real and imaginary parts
    ; of the result respectively.

    ; halt the program
    mov eax, 1
    int 0x80
```

This program calculates (a + bi) * (c + di) and stores the result into two memory locations: `real_res` and `imag_res`.

Please note this is a simple demonstration on an x86-64 assembly for a Linux system, which may be different if you are using a different assembly language (ARM, MIPS, etc.) or different operating system. It also assumes that the complex numbers we are multiplying fit into a byte. In a real-world scenario, you would probably need to use appropriate data types and handle cases where numbers don't fit into a register. 

Also note, that in a modern environment, assembly is rarely used for high-level operations like complex number multiplication. A high-level language would be more appropriate in such cases.
<|end|>


