Here is a simple JavaScript function to randomly adjust the font size of elements on a page:

```javascript
function adjustFontSize(elementIds, dimensions) {
    if(!Array.isArray(elementIds) || !Array.isArray(dimensions)) {
        console.error("Inputs must be Arrays");
        return;
    }
    if(elementIds.length != dimensions.length) {
        console.error("Both input arrays must be of same length");
        return;
    }
    if(dimensions.some(val => typeof val !=="number")){
        console.error("Dimensions array should only contain number values");
        return;
    }
    try {
        elementIds.forEach((id, index) => {
            var element = document.getElementById(id);
            if(element) {
                var randomDimensionIndex = Math.floor(Math.random() * dimensions.length);
                element.style.fontSize = dimensions[randomDimensionIndex] + 'px';
            } else {
                console.warn('No element found with the id: ', id);
            }
        });
    } catch (error) {
        console.error("An error occurred while adjusting the font size", error);
    }
}
```

The function 'adjustFontSize' takes two parameters: 'elementIds', an array of ids of html elements on the web page. 'dimensions' is an array of font size values.

The function first checks that both arguments are arrays of the same length and that all items in the dimensions array are numbers, then it loops over the 'elementIds'.

For each elementId, it checks if there's an html element with that id. If there is, it generates a random index, fetches the corresponding font size from the 'dimensions' array and assigns it to the html element's font size. If no element with that id is found, a warning is logged.

If an error is thrown anywhere in the function, it's caught and logged.
