We can solve this problem by using a set in python. Set doesn't allow duplicates, so it will remove duplicate characters from our sentence. We can then compare the size of the set to the number of letters in the alphabet. Here is a simple python solution:

```python
def check_sentence(sentence):
    alphabet = set('abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz')
    return not set(sentence.lower()) - alphabet

sentence = "The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog"
print(check_sentence(sentence))
```

This function will return `True` if all the alphabets are present at least once in the provided sentence and `False` otherwise. If there are special characters present, they are ignored as the function only checks for the alphabets a-z.

In the above solution, we convert the sentence to lowercase first using lower() function so that the function is case-insensitive. Then, we get the set of unique characters in the sentence and subtract the set of alphabets from it. If all alphabets are present in the sentence, then the result of the subtraction will be an empty set, and the not operator will give us `True`. If any alphabet is missing, then the result won't be an empty set, and we'll get `False`.
