Design a C++ function that efficiently identifies the count of duplicated elements within a given array while maintaining readability.
array: [1, 3, 2, 5, 2, 3]
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Sure, the following is a basic solution in C++ where we make use of `unordered_map` to keep a track of all elements in the array and their corresponding counts. The function `countDuplicates` will return the total count of duplicate elements in an array.

```cpp
#include<iostream>
#include<unordered_map>
using namespace std;

int countDuplicates(int arr[], int n)
{
   unordered_map<int, int> elementCount;
   for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
   {
      elementCount[arr[i]]++;
   }

   int duplicateCount = 0;
   for (auto i : elementCount)
   {
      if(i.second > 1)
      {
         duplicateCount += i.second - 1;
      }
   }
   return duplicateCount;
}

int main()
{
   int arr[] = {1, 3, 2, 5, 2, 3};
   int n = sizeof(arr) / sizeof(arr[0]);
   cout << "Count of duplicated elements: " << countDuplicates(arr, n) << endl;
   return 0;
}
```

In this program, we have used an unordered_map (Hashmap in C++) that stores the frequency of all elements present in the array. Then, we iterate the map and for every element whose count is more than 1, we add the frequency count minus 1 to `duplicateCount`.

Note: This does not return the distinct count of duplicated elements, but the total count of duplicates. If multiple instances of the same element are each counted as a duplicate, then this method would be appropriate.
<|end|>


