<|end|>
<|asst|>
Sure, I can increase the complexity of this code by using a priority queue and handling the uniqueness of the values.

Below is the solution in Javascript:

```javascript
function topKUnique(arr, k) {
    // Create a priority queue with maxHeap
    let pq = [], 
        seen = new Set(), 
        res = [];
            
    for(let num of arr) {
        // Check the number has been met before
        if(!seen.has(num)) {
            pq.push(num);
            seen.add(num);
        }
    }

    // Sort the priority queue
    pq.sort((a, b) => b - a);
    
    // Get top-k unique numbers
    while(k-- > 0 && pq.length) {
        res.push(pq.shift());
    }
    
    return res;
}
```

Here's what we're doing:

- We're using a priority queue (implemented as a simple array) to keep track of the greatest numbers we've seen.
- We're also using a Set 'seen' to keep track of the numbers we've seen so far. Since sets automatically remove duplicates, this ensures we're only considering each number once.
- When we see a number, we add it to the priority queue and the Set.
- We then sort the array and add it to the result array.
- We continue this process until we've found the k greatest unique numbers.

This is a valid solution and implementation increases the code complexity which able to return only unique numbers while maintaining performance as best as possible using the given parameters.
