Given a partly incorrect JavaScript code snippet, identify the errors and correct them in order to create a working JavaScript program that extracts and retrieves the shown URL of a specific web page as well as its path and query parameters.

Reference Code:

```javascript
function getUrl() {
    return null.document.URL 
}

console.log(getUrl());
```

Please use this erroneous code as a reference. Beyond fixing the shown errors, add functionalities so your code can:

1. Retrieve and print to the console the Hostname of the specific URL.
2. Retrieve and print to the console the pathname (directory and file path).
3. Retrieve and print to the console any query parameters available in the URL. 
4. If the URL does not contain any query parameters, your code should print "No query parameters found" to the console.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
To complete this task, the JavaScript 'url' library can be utilized. This library contains methods for URL resolution and parsing. This is a Node.js built-in library, so there's no need to install it specifically.

Let's consider a URL e.g. 'https://www.example.com/path/to/page?param1=value1&param2=value2' for illustration.

Here's the corrected and enhanced code according to your requirements:

```javascript
var url = require('url');

function getUrlData() {
    // Suppose this is the current URL of the webpage
    var currentUrl = 'https://www.example.com/path/to/page?param1=value1&param2=value2';

    // Parse the URL
    var parsedUrl = url.parse(currentUrl, true);

    // Retrieve and display the hostname
    console.log('Hostname: ' + parsedUrl.hostname);

    // Retrieve and display the path
    console.log('Pathname: ' + parsedUrl.pathname);

    // Retrieve and display the query parameters
    if (Object.keys(parsedUrl.query).length === 0){
        console.log('No query parameters found.');
    } else {
        console.log('Query parameters: ', parsedUrl.query);
    }
}

getUrlData();
```

When you run this code in node, it will output:
Hostname: www.example.com
Pathname: /path/to/page
Query parameters: { param1: 'value1', param2: 'value2' }

Please note that this solution assumes a server-side JavaScript environment using Node.js. If your code is running in a browser, there are different ways to get the current URL due to different security considerations. Here's an alternative for browser-based JavaScript:

```javascript
function getUrlData() {
    // In browsers, we can get the current URL with window.location.href
    const currentUrl = new URL(window.location.href);

    console.log('Hostname: ' + currentUrl.hostname);
    console.log('Pathname: ' + currentUrl.pathname);

    let queryParams = new URLSearchParams(currentUrl.search);
    if (queryParams.toString()) {
        console.log('Query parameters: ', queryParams.toString());
    } else {
        console.log('No query parameters found');
