I know how to test an object to see if it is of a type, using the IS keyword e.g.


if (foo is bar)
{
  //do something here
}



but how do you test for it not being "bar"?, I can't seem to find a keyword that works with IS to test for a negative result. 

BTW  - I have a horrible feeling this is soooo obvious, so apologies in advance...
<|end|>
<|asst|>
You just need to put a "!" before the expression. For example:

if (!(foo is bar)) 
{
  //do something here
}

The "!" operator in C# is the logical negation operator. It returns true if its operand is false and false if its operand is true. So, "!(foo is bar)" basically means "if foo is not bar".
