Develop a RESTful API in Node.js using Express.js framework, that not only accepts JSON data and adds it to a MongoDB database, but also validates the input data. The data should represent a user, containing fields such as name, email, and password. For the password, the system should ensure it is hashed before it is stored in the database. To retrieve the data, design endpoints to fetch a single user and all users. Ensure all possible errors are adequately handled using middleware. Write unit tests using Mocha and Chai to validate the functionality of your API and afterwards, dockerize your application.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
This is a quite detailed task, let's break it into parts: setting up the project, user model creation, implementing routes and validations, creating middleware for error handling, writing unit tests and dockerizing the application.

1. Setting up the project:

Make sure you have Node.js and npm installed on your system.
Install Express.js using npm CLI (npm install express).
Also, install the packages for MongoDB (npm install mongoose), bcrypt for hashing passwords (npm install bcrypt), cors for providing a Connect/Express middleware (npm install cors), body-parser for parsing the incoming request bodies (npm install body-parser) and express-validator for input validations npm install express-validator.
Also, install mocha and chai for testing purposes (npm install --save-dev mocha chai).

2. User Model:

Define your User Model in Mongoose.

```javascript
const mongoose = require('mongoose');
const bcrypt = require('bcrypt');

const UserSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
  name: {
    type: String,
    required: true
  },
  email: {
    type: String,
    unique: true,
    required: true
  },
  password: {
    type: String,
    required: true
  }
});

UserSchema.pre('save', function (next) {
  const user = this;
  bcrypt.hash(user.password, 10, function (error, encrypted) {
    user.password = encrypted;
    next();
  });
});

module.exports = mongoose.model('User', UserSchema);
```

3. Implement routes and validation:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const router = express.Router();
const { body, validationResult } = require('express-validator');
const User = require('./User');

router.post('/', [
  body('name').isLength({ min: 1 }),
  body('email').isEmail(),
  body('password').isLength({ min: 5 })
], (req, res) => {
   const errors = validationResult(req);
   if (!errors.isEmpty()) {
     return res.status(400).json({ errors: errors.array() });
   }

   User.create({...req.body}).then(user => res.json(user));
});

router.get('/:id', function(req, res) {
  User.findById(req.params.id).then(user => res.json(user));
});

router.get('/', function(req, res) {
  User.find().then(users => res.json(users));
});

module.exports = router;
```

4. Middleware for error handling:

```javascript
function errorHandler (err, req, res, next) {
  if (res.headersSent) {
    return next(err)
  }
  res.status(500).json({ error: err.message });
}

app.use(errorHandler);
```

5. Tests

```javascript
const chai = require("chai");
const chaiHttp = require("chai-http");
const app = require("../app");
const should = chai.should();

chai.use(chaiHttp);

describe("Users", function() {
  it("should list all users on /GET", function(done) {
    chai
      .request(app)
      .get("/")
      .end(function(err, res) {
        res.should.have.status(200);
        res.should.be.json;
        done();
      });
  });
});
```

6. Dockerizing Your Node.js App
Start by creating a Dockerfile in the root of your project.

```
# choose a base image
FROM node:10
# create app directory in the container
WORKDIR /app
# install dependencies
COPY package*.json ./
RUN npm install
# bundle app source
COPY . .
# expose port
EXPOSE 8080
# start app
CMD ["npm", "start"]
```

Then, create a .dockerignore file to ignore node_modules:

```
node_modules
```

Finally, build your image, and run it:

```
docker build -t your-image-name .
docker run -p 8080:8080 your-image-name
```

Please note that the skeleton provided here is basic and may require adjustments as per your project's configuration and requirement. 

The snippets above do not include setting up the MongoDB connection, which you should set up yourself and make sure that it is running and the application can connect to it successfully.

The example also assumes all variables/constants/etc. are defined and doesn't account for environment variables for ports or MongoDB HOST/URL.
<|end|>


