Rewrite the following code to use standard C libraries.
int array[10], x;
for i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    scanf("%d", &x);
    array[i] = x;
}
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Your provided code is already using standard C libraries, but here is a version with all necessary headers, proper syntax, and a main function for a complete runnable program:

```C
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int array[10], x;
    for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
        scanf("%d", &x);
        array[i] = x;
    }
    return 0;
}
```

Please note that the function `scanf()` is a standard library function in C within the `stdio.h` header file. This function reads the input from the standard input, which is generally a keyboard. The `&x` in `scanf` is used to provide the memory location where the scanned input should be stored, which is the memory address of variable `x` in this case.
<|end|>


