<|asst|>
To ensure the SVG graphic adapts to varying display resolutions, you should make it fully responsive. To achieve this, follow these steps: 

1. Remove hard-coded width and height attributes from the SVG tag which may restrict the image to a fixed size, in this case width="32" and height="32".
   
    `<svg viewBox="0 0 32 32" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">.`

2. In CSS, you can use either percentage or viewport units to specify the width and/or the height of the SVG. Percentage will make the SVG relative to its containing element, while viewport units will make it relative to the size of the browser window. 

   For Example, using percentage unit in CSS: 

   ```
   svg {
    width: 100%;
   }
   ```
   
   Using viewport unit:
   
   ```
   svg {
    width: 100vw;
   }
   ```

3. Option to maintain aspect ratio: If you want to maintain the aspect ratio, you can add the `preserveAspectRatio` attribute to the Svg element and set it to `xMidYMid meet`. 

   `<svg viewBox="0 0 32 32" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" preserveAspectRatio="xMidYMid meet">`

4. Respond to device pixel ratio for sharper images: If you want your SVG to look crisp and sharp in Retina-like, high device-pixel-ratio screens, you can double the values of the viewBox attribute but leave your paths and shapes as they are.

5. Also, make sure that other image properties are set to responsive values in your CSS:

   ```
   img {
    max-width: 100%;
    height: auto;
   } 
   ```

6. Test on different screens to ensure it scales correctly. 

By making these adjustments, your SVG should scale and adapt to various display resolutions while maintaining its quality.
<|end|>


