I recently saw someone write, on a generally non-technical platform, that the Black-Merton-Scholes vanilla option price is the first term of an expansion of the price of a vanilla option.
I get that in the context of stochastic volatility models by making use of the Hull and White mixing formula. And thus also for the specific case of stochastic volatility with (Poisson) jumps in the underlying asset.
For more general processes, can someone derive or point to a paper where it is derived that the BSM price is indeed the first term of price expansion? I would very much like to see what the general series expansion looks like.
This question was prompted by this comment:
[](https://i.stack.imgur.com/FixKc.png)
which reacted to the perceived suggestion that the BSM model is useless.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The BSM price is indeed the first term of an expansion of the price of a vanilla option, when considering more general models with stochastic volatility or jumps, for example. 

This comes from the fact that the BSM model is a special case of these more general models. More specifically, the BSM model assumes constant volatility and no jumps, both of which are simplifying assumptions. 

In the case of stochastic volatility models, one can often derive the option price as a power series in the volatility, where the first term corresponds to the BSM price. A pioneering paper on this topic is "Asymptotics and Calibration in Local Volatility Models" by Berestycki, Busca, and Florent (Quantitative Finance, 2002). 

For models with jumps, the expansion can often be done in the intensity or size of the jumps. A good reference for this is the paper "Option Pricing with Lévy Processes and Stochastic Volatility" by Tankov and Cont (SIAM Journal on Financial Mathematics, 2010). 

Overall, the series expansion approach is a powerful tool to understand how option prices behave under more general models than BSM. It shows the impact of each additional feature (like stochastic volatility or jumps) on the option price and indeed justifies the use of the BSM model as a first approximation.
<|end|>


