I set a passphrase when creating a new SSH key on my laptop. But, as I realise now, this is quite painful when you are trying to commit ([Git](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Git_%28software%29) and [SVN](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apache_Subversion)) to a remote location over SSH many times in an hour.

One way I can think of is, delete my SSH keys and create new. Is there a way to remove the passphrase, while still keeping the same keys?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Yes, you can remove the passphrase from an existing SSH private key. You would have to load your key into memory by typing `ssh-add` followed by the path to your key. You would then be prompted to enter your passphrase one last time so the SSH agent can load it. Then you can export this "non-encrypted" version of the key like so:

```bash
openssl rsa -in ~/.ssh/id_rsa -out ~/.ssh/id_rsa_new
```

Next, replace the old key with the new key:

```bash
mv ~/.ssh/id_rsa_new ~/.ssh/id_rsa
```

And finally, don't forget to fix the permissions after overwriting the key:

```bash
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/id_rsa
```

Please note that doing this will remove the protection offered by the passphrase. If someone gets your private key file, they can immediately use it to log into all machines to which the corresponding public key was copied. If it was passphrase-protected, they would also need the passphrase.
<|end|>


