I have this `2 cases` one with `4 partitons` and another with `5 partition` each partition is size of `10 GB`. I just wanted to understand which case would be most optimal way to reading dat and what will the reason behind it?
I belive the smaller partion is the optimal to read it as it will scan the data more efficiently. therefore case 2 is most optimal way. however, i am looking forward to your input.
`**Case-1:** A HDFS file of 10 TB with 4 partitions each with 2.5 TB`
`**Case-2:** A HDFS file of 10 TB with 5 partitions having splits of 3 TB , 3 TB, 2 TB, 1 TB & 1 TB`
Out of the above 2 cases, which one would be more optimal reading data in spark/pyspark and why ?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Case 2 would indeed be more optimal for reading data in Spark/PySpark. 

The reason lies in the way Spark handles data with its parallel processing. In Spark, one partition is equivalent to one task. If a task fails, only the data in its partition will need to be recomputed, not the entire dataset, which significantly improves the fault tolerance of the system. 

When there are fewer partitions, the data will be processed in fewer larger tasks, leading to lower parallelism and potentially to tasks that are too large to fit into memory. 

The more partitions you have, the more concurrent tasks Spark can run, up to the limit of cores available in your cluster. This means that a higher number of smaller partitions will generally ensure better load balancing and utilization of cluster resources when executing tasks. 

In general, it is advised to have around 2-3 tasks (partitions) per CPU in your cluster for the best balance between efficient resource usage and parallelism. 

However, keep in mind that having a huge number of very small partitions can slow down the job due to the overhead of scheduling and executing many tasks.

For case 2, the partitions size is not evenly distributed ( 3 TB , 3 TB, 2 TB, 1 TB & 1 TB). It can run on 5 tasks parallely and will try to use more resources from the cluster. However, the difference may not be as significant based on your cluster configuration and the nature of the data and computation. 

The key is a balance to maximize resource usage and parallelism while minimizing overhead.
<|end|>


