Devise a Java-based HTTP web server, specifically configured to tackle and process a POST request method.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
To design a Java-based HTTP web server that processes POST requests, we can make use of the Java HTTPServer library. This is a simple web server class built into the Java SDK that can handle HTTP requests and deliver responses. Here's a simple implementation of a server that processes POST requests.

```java

import java.io.IOException;
import java.io.OutputStream;
import java.net.InetSocketAddress;
import com.sun.net.httpserver.HttpExchange;
import com.sun.net.httpserver.HttpHandler;
import com.sun.net.httpserver.HttpServer;

public class SimpleServer {

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        HttpServer server = HttpServer.create(new InetSocketAddress(8000), 0);
        server.createContext("/test", new MyHandler());
        server.setExecutor(null); // creates a default executor
        server.start();
    }

    static class MyHandler implements HttpHandler {
        @Override
        public void handle(HttpExchange t) throws IOException {
            if (t.getRequestMethod().equalsIgnoreCase("POST")) {
                // request process
                InputStream is = t.getRequestBody();
                byte [] response = "Hello World".getBytes();
                t.sendResponseHeaders(200, response.length);
                OutputStream os = t.getResponseBody();
                os.write(response);
                os.close();
            }
        }
    }
}
```
In the above code, the HTTPServer is started at port 8000 and a HTTPHandler is added for handling all the requests to "/test" endpoint.

The HttpHandler is configured to specifically handle POST request. If a POST request comes to "/test", the server send "Hello World" back with a 200 (OK) status.

Remember that this code does not handle GET request and other request types.

Note that HttpServer is part of the `com.sun.net.*` packages, not part of the Java standard (javax.* and java.*) and therefore may change or be unavailable depending on your SDK and its version.
Also this code leaves out the input handling and exception handling for simplicity, real world Java servers would include those as well.
<|end|>


