Eliminate all repeating elements from a provided data collection. However, consider two elements equal only if all their attributes are the same, not just a single one.

data_collection = [('X', 7, 'A'), ('X', 9, 'B'), ('Y', 7, 'A'), ('X', 7, 'B'), ('Z', 1, 'A')]
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a Python solution for the problem using sets:

```python
data_collection = [('X', 7, 'A'), ('X', 9, 'B'), ('Y', 7, 'A'), ('X', 7, 'B'), ('Z', 1, 'A')]

unique_elements = set(data_collection)

print(list(unique_elements))
```

A set in Python will remove any duplicates because sets cannot have multiple instances of the same element. However, it is important to note that this will also not preserve the ordering of elements in the original list. If the ordering is important, a different approach will be needed.

In the case you want to preserve the order of elements, you can use a "OrderedDict" from the "collections" module:

```python
from collections import OrderedDict

data_collection = [('X', 7, 'A'), ('X', 9, 'B'), ('Y', 7, 'A'), ('X', 7, 'B'), ('Z', 1, 'A')]

unique_elements = list(OrderedDict.fromkeys(data_collection))

print(unique_elements)
```

In both cases, only fully equal tuples, i.e., tuples where all attributes are identical, are considered duplicates and removed. This is because tuples are compared in a element-wise manner in Python.
<|end|>


