2. Extract and print the content of the <title> tag.
3. Count the total number of HTML tags in the document.
4. Count the total number of list items (<li>) in the document.

html_doc = "<html><head><title>Sample Website</title></head><body><h1>Hello World!</h1><p>This is a sample website.</p><ul><li>Item 1</li><li>Item 2</li><ul></body></html>"
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a Python solution using the BeautifulSoup library, which is a popular library for parsing HTML and XML documents:

```python
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

html_doc = "<html><head><title>Sample Website</title></head><body><h1>Hello World!</h1><p>This is a sample website.</p><ul><li>Item 1</li><li>Item 2</li><ul></body></html>"

soup = BeautifulSoup(html_doc, 'html.parser')

# Task 1
first_h1 = soup.find('h1')
print("Text inside the first <h1> tag: " + first_h1.text)

# Task 2
title = soup.find('title')
print("Content of the <title> tag: " + title.text)

# Task 3
total_tags = len(soup.find_all())
print("Total number of HTML tags in the document: " + str(total_tags))

# Task 4
total_li = len(soup.find_all('li'))
print("Total number of list items in the document: " + str(total_li))
```

After running this program, you should see:

```
Text inside the first <h1> tag: Hello World!
Content of the <title> tag: Sample Website
Total number of HTML tags in the document: 7
Total number of list items in the document: 2
```

This program first uses BeautifulSoup to parse the given HTML string. It then uses the `find` method to get the first `<h1>` and `<title>` tags and prints their text content. It finds all HTML tags and list items using the `find_all` method and prints their counts.
