Craft a SQL command that combines five separate tables, drawing out the requisite fields. 
The initial table "tab_producer" accumulates: producer_name, producer_id.
The second table "tab_genre", is made of: genre_id, genre_name.
Third table called "tab_director", contains: director_id, director_name.
The fourth table "tab_movie", contains: movie_id, movie_name.
The final fifth table is "tab_allocation", which contains: producer_id, genre_id, director_id, movie_id.
The targeted Fields to be pulled out are: producer_name, genre_name, director_name, movie_name.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is the SQL command you would use:

```sql
SELECT p.producer_name, g.genre_name, d.director_name, m.movie_name
FROM tab_allocation a
JOIN tab_producer p ON a.producer_id = p.producer_id
JOIN tab_genre g ON a.genre_id = g.genre_id
JOIN tab_director d ON a.director_id = d.director_id
JOIN tab_movie m ON a.movie_id = m.movie_id;
```

This SQL command uses JOIN statements to combine the five tables using their respective id fields. Then, it uses the SELECT statement to pull out the requested fields: producer_name, genre_name, director_name, and movie_name.
