If Mr. Jones performs an experiment where he rolls a fair six-sided die, with faces numbered 1 through 6, ten different times consecutively, what is the probability that the number three appears on at least one of his rolls?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The task at hand is to calculate the probability of getting at least a single 3 in ten rolls of a six-sided fair die. 

The probability of rolling a 3 with a fair six-sided die is 1/6. Therefore, the probability of not rolling a 3 would be 1 - 1/6 = 5/6.

If the die is rolled ten times, the probability of not getting a 3 in any of the rolls would be (5/6)^10.

The probability of getting at least one 3 would then be 1 minus the probability of not getting a 3 in any of the ten rolls i.e., 1 - (5/6)^10. 

Here is Python code that performs this calculation:

```python
# Defining probability of not getting a 3
prob_not_3 = 5/6

# Calculating the probability of not getting a 3 in ten rolls
prob_not_3_in_ten = prob_not_3 ** 10

# The probability of getting at least one 3 in ten rolls
prob_at_least_one_3 = 1 - prob_not_3_in_ten

print("The probability of getting at least one 3 in ten rolls is approximately {:.2f} or {}".format(prob_at_least_one_3, prob_at_least_one_3))
```

When this code is executed, it calculates a numeric value which is an approximation for the probability. Therefore, the result of the execution is the desired probability.
<|end|>


