<|asst|>
The reason why you are not able to collect any emits in your ViewModel and also in your MainActivity is due to the way you are handling the HTTP requests using ktor. 

The `it.get("...")` will return when the HTTP request completes, hence the flow block will return before you even got the chance to emit the result. 

In this scenario you actually want to suspend the coroutine while the HTTP request executes, allowing it to return your deserialized content. 

To fix it you should make use of `HttpClient` response pipeline. Note that the following examples assumes that you have installed `Json` formatter in you `HttpClient` like this: 

```
val client = HttpClient() {
    install(JsonFeature) {
        serializer = KotlinxSerializer()
    }
}
```

The KtorClient combined with the TodoRepository should look something like this: 

```
val KtorClient = HttpClient() {
    install(JsonFeature) {
        serializer = KotlinxSerializer()
    }
}

object TODORepository {
    suspend fun getTodos(): List<TODO> {
        return KtorClient.get("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/todos")
    }
}
```

Once you have the proper get request you can simply emit this in a flow like this:

```
object TodoRepository {
    fun getTodos(): Flow<List<Todo>> = flow {
       emit(TodoRepository.getTodos()) // << emit is called
    }.flowOn(Dispatchers.IO)
}
```

And also you should use `SharedFlow` or `StateFlow` instead of `MutableSharedFlow` in your ViewModel as these provides better caching properties. You can initialize a MutableSharedFlow with an initial value to make sure that value is always available. 

```
class TODOViewModel: ViewModel() {
    val response = MutableStateFlow<List<TODO>>(listOf())

    init {
        viewModelScope.launch {
            TODORepository.getTODOS().collect {
                // NEVER INVOKED !!!
                response.emit(it)
            }
        }
    }
}
```

And lastly you are blocking the UI thread in your MainActivity using `runBlocking`. 

Most probably you would like to observe the state in your ViewModel which can be done like this:

```
class MainActivity: AppCompatActivity() {
    private val todoViewModel: TodoViewModel by viewModels()

    override fun onCreate(savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState)
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_main)
        lifecycleScope.launchWhenStarted {
            todoViewModel.response.collect { todos -> 
                // do something with todos
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Here I used `lifecycleScope.launchWhenStarted` which is lifecycle-aware and will only execute when the Lifecycle is in `Lifecycle.State.STARTED`. You can adjust this behavior by using different `launch`variants. 

This way it will not block the UI thread and will collect and update your UI accordingly.
<|end|>


