<|asst|>
In Python, you can establish a procedural function named "is_anagram()" to evaluate two strings to discern if they serve as anagrams of each other. Here is an example of how this could be conducted:

```python
def is_anagram(string1, string2):
    # Remove any spaces and convert strings to lowercase
    string1 = string1.replace(" ", "").lower()
    string2 = string2.replace(" ", "").lower()

    # Check if both strings have same length 
    if len(string1) != len(string2): 
        return False

    # Count frequency of each character and if any difference, return False
    for char in string1:
        if string1.count(char) != string2.count(char):
            return False

    # If all conditions are satisfied then return True
    return True
```

You can test this function with your provided examples like shown below:

```python
string1 = "abcde"
string2 = "edcba"

print(is_anagram(string1, string2))  # This will output: True
```

Please be aware that the function is case insensitive and ignores spaces. So "Hello" and "loleh" would be considered as anagrams as well as "He llo" and "lol eh". If you prefer the function to be case sensitive, simply remove the ".lower()" part in the function. Similarly, if you want it to consider spaces, simply remove the ".replace(" ", "")" part.
