Construct an intricate web crawler that meticulously extracts the entirety of hyperlinks present within a specified web page, designated by the following URL: "https://www.example.com"
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Creating a functioning web crawler would exceed the limits of this environment but I can certainly provide a Python code sample that uses the "Beautiful Soup" and "requests" libraries to scrape links from a web page. 

However, please note it is always crucial to respect the host site's terms of service and/or the "robots.txt" file associated to the site, to avoid overloading or misusing the site's resources. 

```python
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import requests

def get_links(url):
    # Send the GET request to the URL
    response = requests.get(url)
    # If the GET request is successful, the status code will be 200
    if response.status_code == 200:
        # Get the content of the response
        page_content = response.content
        # Create a BeautifulSoup object and specify the parser
        soup = BeautifulSoup(page_content, 'html.parser')
        # Find all the anchor tags in the HTML
        # Extract href attribute and filter out if it contains 'javascript:', 'mailto:', 'tel:'
        urls = [a['href'] for a in soup.find_all('a', href=True) if not (a['href'].startswith('javascript:') or a['href'].startswith('mailto:') or a['href'].startswith('tel:'))]
        return urls

# Usage:
url = 'https://www.example.com'
for link in get_links(url):
    print(link)
```

This is a simple script which only scrapes the main page. It doesn't follow further links or repeatedly attempt to access a page if it initially fails which a more sophisticated crawler might do. It also doesn't handle relative links.

Note: This script will scrape all the links on the page designated by the provided URL. If the page is complex or contains many hyperlinks, this process may take a considerable amount of time.
<|end|>


