I have an image and its corresponding camera matrix(intrinsics and extrinsics). I need to chop the image in 4 or n patches. What will be the new camera matrices for each patch of the image? Or is this even possible to find?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Yes, it is possible to create new camera matrices, but when an image is chopped to patches there won't be a different camera matrix for every part, because the intrinsic camera parameters (which include focal length, the point where the optic axis hits the image plane, and any skew between the x and y pixel axes) are the same for the whole image. It's the entire camera that has a specific field of view, principal point etc., not part of an image taken by it.

However, one difference will be the principal points c_x and c_y. When an image is cropped, the principal points of the new image patch will be moved.

The new c_x and c_y in the intrinsic matrix of each patch is equal to the original ones subtracted by the top left x and y coordinates of the patch (in pixel units). 

Don't forget, the principal point is not just the center of the image, it's usually very near it but never exactly in the center due to manufacturing process of the sensor.

On the other side the extrinsics matrix describes the location of the camera in the world when it took that picture. But the camera location is also the same for the entire image and all its patches.

So when you've chopped the image into patches, they all still correspond to the same single camera with the same intrinsic matrix. If you tweak the camera matrix for each patch you're implying that each patch was taken from a different camera, which is not true. They're from the same photograph therefore they're from the same camera with the same matrix. The changes in extrinsic parameters between patches are generally not meaningful because you're essentially introducing artificial camera positions and orientations that did not capture the original image.

It's also important to remember that working with patches of an image using different camera matrices may lead to incorrect results. One possible workaround is to work with the entire image in the image processing pipeline and chop it into patches when feeding into the model, then assemble it back. This way, you do not need to create new camera matrices for each patch because you are essentially still working with the original image and its camera matrix.
<|end|>


