```

Once you've got boto3 and AWS CLI configured, you can create a Python script to launch an EC2 instance with advanced settings:

```python
import boto3

# Create an EC2 client
ec2 = boto3.client("ec2")

# Define advanced configuration
instance_settings = {
    "InstanceType": "t2.micro",  # Desired instance type, modify as needed
    "MinCount": 1,
    "MaxCount": 1,
    "ImageId": "ami-xxxxxxxx",  # Replace with the desired Amazon Machine Image (AMI) ID
    "KeyName": "your-key-pair",  # Replace with your key pair name
    "SecurityGroupIds": ["sg-xxxxxxxx"],  # Replace with your security group ID(s)
    "SubnetId": "subnet-xxxxxxxx",  # Replace with your desired subnet ID
    "UserData": """#cloud-config
    runcmd:
      - echo 'Hello World!' > /home/ec2-user/hello.txt
    """,  # Example of user data, modify as needed
    "IamInstanceProfile": {
        "Arn": "arn:aws:iam::xxxxxxxxxxx:instance-profile/your-instance-profile"
    },  # Replace with your instance profile ARN
}

# Launch the instance
response = ec2.run_instances(**instance_settings)
instance_id = response["Instances"][0]["InstanceId"]
print(f"Launched instance with ID: {instance_id}")

```
