<|asst|>
Here's a basic example of how you might set up a user authentication form in React. This example uses the built-in React state handling and no external libraries or dependencies. This is a simplified version and does not yet hash passwords, verify real users or have a valid system, handle forgot-password cases, or other common practices in production-level code.

```jsx
import React, { Component } from 'react';

class LoginForm extends Component {
  constructor(props) {
    super(props);
    this.state = {
      username: '',
      password: '',
      errorMsg: '',
    };
  }

  handleInputChange = e => {
    this.setState({
      [e.target.name]: e.target.value,
    });
  }

  handleSubmit = e => {
    e.preventDefault();
    const { username, password } = this.state;
    
    // Add your own user authentication logic here
    if (username === 'admin' && password === 'password') {
      alert('Logged in successfully');
      this.setState({ errorMsg: '' });
    } else {
      this.setState({ errorMsg: 'Invalid username or password' });
    }
  }

  render() {
    const { username, password, errorMsg } = this.state;

    return (
      <form onSubmit={this.handleSubmit}>
        <label>
          Username:
          <input type="text" name="username" value={username} onChange={this.handleInputChange} />
        </label>

        <label>
          Password:
          <input type="password" name="password" value={password} onChange={this.handleInputChange} />
        </label>

        <button type="submit">Login</button>

        {errorMsg && <p>{errorMsg}</p>}
      </form>
    );
  }
}

export default LoginForm;
```

In a real-world production environment, you may also want to incorporate the following:

1. A way to handle cases in which information entered by the users does not match the records. This could mean giving users the ability to recover their username or password.
2. Hashing your users' passwords. Storing passwords as plaintext is incredibly unsafe and should be avoided at all costs.
3. Using an authentication library such as `Passport.js` instead of trying to build your own authentication system from scratch.
4. Checking for both client and server-side validation.
5. Utilizing HTTPS for encrypting the user's sensitive data. 

Before you run this, make sure React library is installed in your environment. If not installed, use can use the command `npx create-react-app my-app` to install and create a new app. This example is just a basic understanding, but authentication can be a broad and complex topic depending on the level of security you need.
