I am trying to incorporate editorjs in my react app. I incorporated it with the  element with . I want to implement the text editor with the  element also but it seems it's not working.
Is there anything extra to be done in order to implement the rich-text-editor on  tag.
Using the id of the element on the holder element of editorjs is not helping me with  tag.
[https://laracasts.com/discuss/channels/laravel/editorjs-is-not-working-with-textarea](https://laracasts.com/discuss/channels/laravel/editorjs-is-not-working-with-textarea)
I referred to the link above and unfortunately, it's not helping me.
I am pretty new to implementing this stuff, Does anyone know the issue?
Thanks
<|end|>
<|asst|>
EditorJS is a block-style editor, meaning it creates and edits content block by block (as div elements) rather than as a running piece of text (as in textarea/input elements). This means, incorporating EditorJS with textarea or input elements isn't practically possible. 

This is because the block structure is a fundamental part of the EditorJS design. Each piece of content exists as its own independent block which can be individually styled, moved and manipulated.

The content of EditorJS is represented in a JSON format that holds all the information of different blocks and their types and data.

The reason you can't use <textarea>, is because <textarea> is designed to accept only text. EditorJS outputs a data structure, which is far more than just text. You can't put a JSON object directly into a textarea.

Here’s a suggested alternate approach:

1. Initialize the EditorJS on a <div> element. Here is an example code snippet to do so:

```jsx
import EditorJS from "@editorjs/editorjs";

class MyComponent extends React.Component {
  editor;
  componentDidMount() {
    this.editor = new EditorJS({ holderId: 'editorjs' });
  }
  // rest code
}
```

2. And corresponding 'div' in your render method

```jsx
render() {
  return (
    <div id='editorjs'></div>
  );
}
```

3. When the form is being submitted, you can save the EditorJS' content by calling the `save()` method on the editor instance. Since the `save()` method returns a promise with resulting object, it's ideal to handle it in an async function e.g.:

```javascript
const handleSubmit = async () => {
  const editorData = await this.editor.save();

  // now you have access to the data
  // you can stringify it and put into a hidden field, 
  // or send in a fetch POST request etc.

  console.log(editorData);
}
```
Please note, this provided code is a minimal example, and you're expected to properly handle any errors that might arise.
