As an AI text-based model, I'm unable to directly manipulate SVG or any other graphic file formats. However, animating SVGs largely follows a three-step process: 

1. Create the base shape (which you've done).
2. Define an animation appropriate for that shape.
3. Link the animation to the shape using CSS or JavaScript.

For a shimmering and swirling effect, a good starting point might be to create custom CSS keyframes and attach these to your SVG elements using style tags.

Below is an example CSS animation you can use as a reference. Please note that you understand its functionality and adjust to suit your needs.

```css
@keyframes portalSwirl {
  0% { transform: rotate(0deg); }
  100% { transform: rotate(360deg); }
}

@keyframes portalShimmer {
  0% { fill: #0074BA; opacity: 1; }
  50% { fill: #00A6ED; opacity: 0.5; }
  100% { fill: #0074BA; opacity: 1; }
}
```

Include this CSS with your SVG. Example:

```html
<style>
...CSS animations here...
</style>
<svg>
...SVG paths here...
</svg>
```

Then, include an animation line within each SVG path. The syntax for including animations within an SVG path looks like the following:

```html
<path d="...path data..." style="animation: portalSwirl 10s linear infinite, portalShimmer 2s ease-in-out infinite">
```

Note that two animations are separated with a comma, meaning the SVG will simultaneously rotate and change color. 

The numbers in seconds (10s, 2s) control the speed of animation (duration), and "infinite" means the animation will continually repeat.

Please note that creating visual animations requires technical knowledge about CSS animations, SVG structure and often JavaScript. Consider hiring a web developer if you feel uncomfortable doing this on your own.
<|end|>


