I'd like to gain better knowledge of operating system internals. Process management, memory management, and stuff like that. 
I was thinking of learning by getting to know either linux or BSD kernel.
Which one kernel is better for learning purposes?
What's the best place to start?
Can you recommend any good books?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Both Linux and BSD kernels are excellent for getting into OS internals and have their respective specialties. However, Linux tends to have many more resources available for learning and thus might be easier to start with.

1. Linux: It's considered more beginner-friendly as there are a plethora of resources available online to understand its working. It's also widely used in commercial settings, understanding Linux Kernel can provide you with a good amount of knowledge which is applicable in real-life scenarios.

2. BSD: BSD and its variants are used in several embedded systems and highly secure environments. However, learning resources for BSD might be slightly harder to find than Linux.

Here's a list recommended books/resources:

1. "Understanding the Linux Kernel" by Daniel P. Bovet and Marco Cesati - This book gives a detailed overview of the Linux kernel.

2. "Linux Kernel Development" by Robert Love - The book is all about explaining the concepts, descriptions, and instructions to understand the Linux kernel internals and development. 

3. "Linux Device Drivers" by Jonathan Corbet - Here, you can learn about drivers, a critical part of a kernel.

4. For free online resources, refer to the Linux Documentation project (https://www.tldp.org/) and Linux Kernel Newbies (https://kernelnewbies.org)

For BSD:

1. "The Design and Implementation of the FreeBSD Operating System" by Marshall Kirk McKusick and George V. Neville-Neil - This book is excellent for understanding the FreeBSD kernel. 

2. For online resources, check out the FreeBSD Handbook (https://www.freebsd.org/doc/handbook/)

Lastly, do not just read but also try to get involved in coding. Try to compile the kernels on your own, and understand what each part does. Reading the code of these kernels can also offer an insight. With Linux, you can even try to submit patches to fix bugs or add small features, which is highly educational.
<|end|>


