I installed VS SP1 and played around with Entity Framework.

I created a schema from an existing database and tried some basic operations.

Most of it went well, except the database schema update.

I changed the database in every basic way:

- - - - - 

The first three went well, but the type change and the column deletion did not followed the database changes.

Is there any way to make is work from the designer? Or is it not supported at the moment? I didn't find any related material yet, but still searching.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The most common way to update the Entity Framework's model from the database is by using the `Update Model From Database…` wizard in the Entity Framework Designer. This method allows you to specify exactly which database objects and settings to include in the model.

However, this doesn't work seamlessly. Entity Framework doesn't fully support automatic schema updating especially concerning column type changes or deletion. The primary reason behind it is, in many scenarios, it could risk data loss. 

Consider this action: You have a column of type `nvarchar(50)` and you have data stored in that column. If you change it to `nvarchar(10)`, you could lose data, hence EF restricts such operations. 

In such scenarios, you would have to manually synchronize the EF model and underlying database. This includes deleting the specific entity, saving the model, and then re-adding it using the `Update Model From Database…` wizard. For column type changes, even manual editing of the edmx XML file might be required.

Another alternative is to use "Code First" instead of "Database First". In Code First Migrations, a new migration file is added each time you change your code first model. Those migrations transform your database schema to be compatible with the current model while preserving the existing data. 

Remember, both of these approaches come with their own degrees of complications, and a thorough understanding of your project requirements would let you pick the right one. No matter what approach you take, remember to always backup your data before making such changes.
<|end|>


