Develop a class in C++ to calculate the surface area of a tetrahedron. Additionally, develop methods to calculate and return the volume of the tetrahedron and check if the tetrahedron is regular or irregular.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a simple implementation of a Tetrahedron class in C++.

Note that a regular tetrahedron is a special type of equilateral tetrahedron where all sides are equal.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <cmath>

class Tetrahedron {
    private:
        double side; 
    
    public:
        // Constructor for the class
        Tetrahedron(double sideLength) {
            side = sideLength;
        }
    
        // Method to calculate surface area
        double getSurfaceArea() {
            return sqrt(3) * pow(side, 2);
        }
        
        // Method to calculate volume
        double getVolume() {
            return pow(side, 3) / (6 * sqrt(2));
        }
        
        // Method to determine if it's regular
        bool isRegular(double a, double b, double c, double d){
            if (a == b && a == c && a == d)
                return true;
            else
                return false;
        }
};

int main() {
    Tetrahedron t(5);

    std::cout << "Surface area: " << t.getSurfaceArea() << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Volume: " << t.getVolume() << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Is regular: " << (t.isRegular(5, 5, 5, 5) ? "Yes" : "No") << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

In this code, a class 'Tetrahedron' is created with a private member 'side'. The public methods of the class include a constructor that initializes the 'side', a method 'getSurfaceArea' that calculates the surface area of the tetrahedron, a method 'getVolume' that calculates the volume of the tetrahedron and a method 'isRegular' which checks if the tetrahedron is regular or not.

In the 'main' function, a tetrahedron object 't' is created with side length 5. The surface area, volume and regularity of the tetrahedron are then calculated using the class methods and displayed. 

Note: There are actually a few ways to define a tetrahedron. Depending on the definition, additional data may be required such as the height. This example assumes an equilateral tetrahedron where all sides have equal length.
<|end|>


