Suppose I have data $Y$ regressed against $X$, where $Y$ is the level of health for an individual (from 1 to 10), and $X$ is the whether or no the individual is above 50 years of age. If I wanted to estimate the difference in mean level of health in individuals above or equal to 50, and under 50 — and wanted standard errors, should I use

- Regular OLS standard errors

- HC1 errors

- HC2 errors


?
Thanks
<|end|>
<|asst|>
The choice of which error term to use comes down to the assumptions about the error term:

- Regular OLS (Ordinary Least Squares) Standard Errors are appropriate when the classical linear regression assumptions hold, including that errors are independently and identically distributed (i.i.d).

- HCx (Heteroskedasticity Consistent) Errors are applied when the assumption of homoscedasticity is violated, meaning the variability of the errors differs across levels of the independent variables. The choice between HC1, HC2, and so on, depends on the specific form of heteroskedasticity, with different estimators being more or less biased under different conditions.

In your case, if the assumption of homoscedasticity holds (which would imply that the variability in health levels doesn't differ between persons aged <50 and >=50), then OLS standard errors would be appropriate. However, if the assumption of homoscedasticity doesn't hold (which is very common in real data, especially with variables like health outcomes which can be quite variable), you would typically use one of the heteroskedasticity robust standard errors such as HC1 or HC2.

The robustness of HC1 and HC2 does not always ensure a better model. It is good to compare the result with OLS. You might see marginal differences, in which case the OLS model could suffice. Testing for homoscedasticity or examining a plot of residuals versus fitted values could be a beneficial first step before choosing the model.
<|end|>


