<|asst|>
You can utilize the `htmltools` package to add a logo or any other external image to your networkD3 plots. 

The basic approach is to generate the sankey chart as HTML using `saveNetwork` function, read this HTML back in, and then modify it to add an image. Here’s a simple example how this can be done:

```R
# Generate the Sankey plot and save it as html
sankeyNetwork(Links = links, Nodes = nodes, Source = "IDsource", 
              Target = "IDtarget", Value = "value", NodeID = "name") %>% 
    saveNetwork(file = "sankey.html")

library(htmltools)

# Read the html file back in
sankey_html <- read_html("sankey.html")

img_path <- "path_to_your_logo.jpg" # replace with your local path
style_str <- paste0("position: absolute; top: 20px; left: 20px;")

# Beware of the file path as it'll need to be accessible
img_tag <- tags$img(src = img_path, style = style_str)

# Append the logo to the body
mod_sankey_html <- tagAppendChild(sankey_html, img_tag)

# Save the new html
write_html(mod_sankey_html, "sankey_with_logo.html")
```

In this code `position: absolute; top: 20px; left: 20px;` can be modified to position the image based on specific pixels from the top and left of the page. Replace `"path_to_your_logo.jpg"` with the path to the image file for the logo.

A point to note is that the image must be accessible from the location where you view the HTML. If you're viewing the HTML on your local machine, then a local file path is fine; if you're hosting the HTML on a web server, then the image file needs to be accessible via a URL.
<|end|>


