My HTML is all marked up, ready to make it rain CSS.  The problem is that I have to go back and find out what all my id and class names are so I can get started.  What I need is a tool that parses my HTML and spits out a stylesheet with all the possible elements ready to be styled (maybe even with some defaults).  Does such a tool exist?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
There is no specific tool that does exactly as you mentioned. But there are some tools which might help in this process:

1. **CSS Scan Pro:** This helps you to inspect and copy CSS. Although not exactly what you are looking for, it can be useful when figuring out id and class names.

2. **Allows Extract:** It is a feature in Adobe Photoshop CC that can be used to extract CSS from PSD comps. This may not be directly from HTML, but it is useful for a design-to-code workflow.

3. **Pinegrow:** Pinegrow Web Editor lets you work with HTML files on your computer. It designs and edit the DOM tree and the CSS styles directly from the tool. It shows all the CSS rules that apply to the selected element.

4. **Browser Inspector Tools:** Most modern web browsers like Chrome and Firefox have great inspector tools where you can see and edit CSS live.

5. **CSS Generators:** There are countless CSS generators online which can generate boilerplate code for your CSS elements. They are not specific to your HTML markup but can be helpful to get things started quickly.

6. **Specific Extensions:** There are some extensions available for text editors such as Sublime Text or VS Code which can extract and generate CSS from HTML, work with the structure, and autocomplete for classes or id's.

However, a better approach might be to use a proper naming convention like BEM (Block, Element, Modifier) when writing your HTML. This way your class naming will be consistent, predictable, and easier to work with when it comes to writing your CSS.
<|end|>


