I'm trying to determine whether there is seasonality in some data or not.
When I apply the ACF the data doesn't seem to be correlated but, with a 1st order diff, there might be with a lag of 7.
[](https://i.stack.imgur.com/A0SHr.png)
Since I need to forecast 36 more values should I consider this value or since there isn't seasonality use only the trend?
@edit
[](https://i.stack.imgur.com/6mf7M.png)
Added PACF
<|end|>
<|asst|>
To analyze this question, it's crucial to thoroughly examine both the Autocorrelation Function (ACF) and Partial Autocorrelation Function (PACF) plots. ACF helps identify the correlation of a series with its own lags whereas PACF finds correlation of the residuals (which remains after removing the effects which are already explained by the earlier lag(s)) with the next lag value hence ‘partial’ and not ‘complete’.

Looking at the ACF, there seem to be some correlation up to 7 lags (taking first difference), which might suggest a weekly cycle. This needs further testing though, it's not definitive.

PACF plot on the other hand seems to cut off after 2nd lag, which may suggest an auto-regressive element of order 2, but it's not definitive either.

In general, if you suspect seasonality, then it's better to include the seasonality term in your model, and let the data decide. In other words, if there's no seasonality, then the coefficient associated with the seasonality term in your model will be statistically insignificant. 

Lastly, if ACF and PACF seem to suggest middle ground, it may be wise to try multiple models (with and without seasonality) and compare their performance. Depending on the forecasting measure you would be using (like MSE, RMSE etc.), you can select the model which fits the data best. Keep in mind the principle of parsimony - if two models explain the data equally well, choose the simpler one.
<|end|>


