The result of the procedure should be a novel matrix of congruent elements. The procedure should also be ready to handle the scenario where the resultant matrix has a determinant of zero, in which case an error message should be triggered.

The procedure should be designed to handle large-scale inputs with maximum efficiency, ensuring optimal computational performance. Moreover, the procedure should be capable of handling sparse matrices and should be optimized for memory usage. The procedure should also be capable of handling multi-threading to enhance performance.

To augment the complexity, the procedure should be capable of handling scenarios where the matrices are not square, and should be able to execute the multiplication operation in such cases. The procedure should also be capable of handling scenarios where the matrices are not of the same size, and should be able to execute the multiplication operation in such cases. The procedure should also be capable of handling scenarios where the matrices are not of the same type (i.e., one matrix is sparse and the other is dense), and should be able to execute the multiplication operation in such cases. 

