<|asst|>
The original Python code uses some advanced programming features that are not available in C, such as optional parameters (arguments with default values), type hints, exception handling, and a built-in function for string-to-float conversion. Writing equivalent code in C requires you to implement these features manually.

Here is the equivalent C code without type hints and exceptions, but with comments explaining how it works:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <stdbool.h>
#include <math.h>

/*
This function converts a string to a float number.
If the string is not a numeric string, it returns zero.
*/
float str_to_float(char* str){
    char *ptr;
    float ret = strtof(str, &ptr);
    if (*ptr != '\0') return 0;
    return ret;
}

/*
This function refines and return an integer from a float number.
It rounds up or down depending on the round_down parameter.
If the input is zero, it simply returns null.
*/
int refine_integer(char* input_value, bool round_down) {
    // Convert the string to a float number
    float number = str_to_float(input_value);

    // If the conversion fails (i.e., non-numeric string), return 0.
    if (number == 0) return 0;

    // Check the round_down parameter.
    if(round_down) {
        // If it's true, round down the number by casting to int.
        return (int)number;
    } else {
        // If it's false, round up the number by ceiling function.
        return ceil(number);
    }
}

/*
This function is used to print the converted int number.
If the number is zero, it will print a message to point out invalid input.
*/
void print_refined_integer(char* input_value, bool round_down) {
    int result = refine_integer(input_value, round_down);
    if(result == 0) {
        printf("Invalid input: non-numeric string\n");
    } else {
        printf("%d\n", result);
    }
}

int main() {
    print_refined_integer("3.14", true);
    print_refined_integer("3.14", false);
    print_refined_integer("Pie", true);

    return 0;
}
```
The script must be compiled and run from a terminal/console, and it will only work for command-line/terminal applications.
