Formulate an SQL query to generate a list of client monikers from the underlying database table, that also ranks the users based on the frequency of their orders from another related table "orders". The clients with the most orders should appear first. 

The customer_id in the "customers" table is linked with the customer_id in the "orders" table.

Tables:

Customers
| customer_id | name |
| --------- | ----- |
| 1 | Bill |
| 2 | Jane |
| 3 | John |

Orders
| order_id | customer_id |
| --------- | ----- |
| 101 | 1 |
| 102 | 3 |
| 103 | 1 |
| 104 | 2 |
| 105 | 3 |
<|end|>
<|asst|>
You can use the following SQL query to solve this problem:

```sql
SELECT c.name, COUNT(o.order_id) AS order_count
FROM Customers c
INNER JOIN Orders o ON c.customer_id = o.customer_id
GROUP BY c.name
ORDER BY order_count DESC;
```

This query works by joining the "Customers" and "Orders" tables on customer_id. Then, groups the results by customer name and counts the number of orders each customer has. In the end, the results are ordered in descending order based on the number of orders, so customers with the most orders come first.
<|end|>


