I have some dynamically created inputs which are not server-side controls. I want to relate them to some CalendarExtender and MaskedEditExtender on the clientside. Is there a way to do that?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Yes, it is possible to create dynamic controls and associate them with Ajax control toolkit extenders like CalendarExtender and MaskedEditExtender on the client side. 

The more common approach is to create these controls on the server side and use Ajax to update the client side, but it is also possible to create and associate these controls strictly using client-side JavaScript.

Here's a general approach with JavaScript:

1. Create the input controls using plain HTML or JavaScript.

2. After the controls are created, initialize the Ajax control toolkit extenders. 

AJAX Control Toolkit doesn't provide any built-in function to initialize extenders on dynamically created elements via clientside Javascript. However, you can follow this hack workaround:

- Create extenders on some hidden fields during server side load (ASPX markup).
- Then on client side, copy extenders settings from those hidden fields to yours dynamically created fields.

It's not the cleanest approach, but it's a workaround for achieving your goal. 

It's something like this:

```
// I'm assuming you've created an input dynamically
var input = document.createElement("input");
input.id = "MyDynamicInput";
document.body.appendChild(input);

// Copy settings from hidden field to your dynamic input
var hiddenExtendedInput = $find("HiddenExtendedInput"); // Fetch settings from one hidden input
var extendingBehaviour = hiddenExtendedInput.get_extender(); // Get its extending behaviour
extendingBehaviour.set_target(input); // Set target to your input.
```
Note: This code is just to provide a direction. You need to figure out actual code by yourself.

Moreover, please take care about the element IDs, if you're creating multiple inputs dynamically and applying extenders on them, every element should have a unique ID otherwise it will cause issues.
 
Nevertheless, if your application deals with creating a lot of dynamic inputs, a server-side solution might be a cleaner and more maintainable approach in the long run.
<|end|>


