<|user|>
As I understand it, time value for European options is as follows:
[](https://i.stack.imgur.com/62rG0.png)
What if r=0? Then puts should behave the same as calls, right? Would the time value always be nonnegative or could it be negative?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
If r = 0, it means there is no interest rate or cost of capital. Hence, the cost of money over time will not be accounted for in the option pricing. This will have implications for both call and put options but it doesn't mean that puts will behave the same as calls. A call option gives the holder the right to buy an asset at a certain price on or before a certain date while a put option gives the holder the right to sell an asset at a certain price on or before a certain date.

Even in a zero-interest-rate scenario, the time value of options will indeed be non-negative. The reason is that time value represents the possibility of changes in the price of the underlying asset over time - this possibility exists whether there's an interest rate/cost of capital or not. The longer the time till option's expiry date, the greater the chance for the underlying asset's price to move favorably, and hence, the greater the time value. This is was true even if the risk-free rate (r) is zero. 

However, if the option is at-the-money or out-of-the-money, its intrinsic value is zero and its total value equals its time value. In case the option is in-the-money, its total value also includes its intrinsic value (the difference between current price of the underlying asset and the exercise price). In no case, the time value of an option would be negative as it would imply that the option actually loses value over time, which contradicts the nature of options as a leveraged investment that provides a chance (not certainty) of profit.
<|end|>


