Develop a Python script that not only identifies the frequency of each character in a given string but also sorts them in descending order of frequency. If two characters have the same frequency, sort them alphabetically. The script must also record the time taken to execute these tasks and come with a complexity analysis. The given string includes alphanumeric characters, spaces, and special characters. 

String = "Submarine1 telescope_ microscope_underwater#23"
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here is a Python script for the given problem. 

```python
from collections import Counter
import time

# Python counter keeps the data in the order it is inserted,
# So we can sort first by alphabets and then by frequency
def sort_characters(string):
    start_time = time.time()

    string = sorted(string)
    frequency = Counter(string)

    sorted_characters = sorted(frequency.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True)

    end_time = time.time()
    time_taken = end_time - start_time

    return sorted_characters, time_taken


def main():
    string = "Submarine1 telescope_ microscope_underwater#23"
    sorted_characters, time_taken = sort_characters(string)
    
    for char, freq in sorted_characters:
        print(f"Character: {char}, Frequency: {freq}")
        
    print(f"Time taken for execution: {time_taken} seconds")


if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
```

The time complexity for sorting is O(nlogn) where n is the number of unique characters in the string. The collections.Counter operation has a linear time complexity, i.e., O(n) where n is the length of the string. Therefore, the overall time complexity would be O(nlogn + n).

The space complexity is O(n) because we are storing the frequencies of all distinct characters from the string. This can be at most the size of the string if all characters are unique. 

This code is fairly efficient for small to medium-sized strings. For large strings with many unique characters, the sorting can become a bottleneck. Nonetheless, sorting is necessary in this case because we have a requirement to sort the characters not only by frequency but also alphabetically. 

There are ways to optimize the sorting by using bucket sorting or similar algorithms for integers, but this would only work if we have a fixed range of characters (such as ASCII) and doesn't apply to the given problem which includes many types of characters. Furthermore, unless the size of the string is very large, these kinds of optimizations would not offer a noticeable performance benefit.
<|end|>


