Write an SQL query to list the names, phone numbers and email ID of all customers who have made a purchase above a certain value in the past year. Also, sort the results based on the total purchase value in descending order and group by the type of customer (Premium or regular). 

Make sure to include a safeguard against SQL injection attacks in your query. You should also consider efficiency and optimization in your solution due to the potentially large size of the database. Report any customers who have not provided an email address separately.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here’s a secure and optimized SQL query using parametrized inputs to protect against SQL injection attacks:

```sql
PREPARE statement FROM
'SELECT type, name, phone, email, SUM(purchase_amount) as total_purchase
FROM customers
LEFT JOIN purchases ON customers.id = purchases.customer_id
WHERE purchase_date BETWEEN DATE_SUB(NOW(), INTERVAL 1 YEAR) AND NOW() AND purchase_amount > ?
GROUP BY type, name, phone, email
ORDER BY total_purchase DESC';

SET @value = 500; -- Define the minimal purchase amount here
EXECUTE statement USING @value;
```

In this query, we first PREPARE a statement that contains a placeholder for the certain value. Then, we SET a variable containing the certain value (here $500) that a customer should have spent in the past year. Then, we EXECUTE the statement, which essentially substitutes the placeholder with the certain value. This structure ensures that no SQL injection is possible.

Also, in order to handle large amounts of data, the customers and purchases tables should be indexed (especially on columns involved in WHERE, JOIN and GROUP BY predicates).

Finally, to separately report customers without email addresses, we would run another query:

```sql
PREPARE statement FROM
'SELECT type, name, phone, email, SUM(purchase_amount) as total_purchase
FROM customers
LEFT JOIN purchases ON customers.id = purchases.customer_id
WHERE purchase_date BETWEEN DATE_SUB(NOW(), INTERVAL 1 YEAR) AND NOW() AND purchase_amount > ? AND email IS NULL';

SET @value = 500; -- Define the minimal purchase amount here
EXECUTE statement USING @value;
```

This query is similar to the first one, but with an additional condition in the WHERE clause to filter customers whose email is NULL.
<|end|>


