It looks like the OCR scanner has confused several characters and added typos. I believe this is a correct interpretation:

```python
from collections import Counter

def check_permutation(seq1, seq2):
    """Validate if seq1 is a permutation of seq2"""
    return Counter(seq1) == Counter(seq2)

def find_longest_permutation(seq1, seq2):
    """Discover the longest common permutation among two sequences"""
    
    def generate_permutations(seqs):
        """Recursive function to generate permutations"""
        if len(seqs) == 1: 
            return [seqs]
        else:
            permutations = []
            for i in range(len(seqs)):
                rest = seqs[:i] + seqs[i+1:]
                for p in generate_permutations(rest):
                    permutations.append([seqs[i]] + p)
            return permutations

    seq1, seq2 = list(seq1), list(seq2)
    common = list(set(seq1) & set(seq2))

    # Iterate over lengths from len(common) to 1
    for length in range(len(common), 0, -1):
        for perm in generate_permutations(common[:length]):
            if check_permutation(perm, seq1) and check_permutation(perm, seq2):
                # Return the longest permutation in its original type (string or list)
                if isinstance(seq1, str):
                    return ''.join(perm)
                else:
                    return perm

    # If there is no common permutation, return an empty sequence in the original type
    if isinstance(seq1, str):
        return ''
    else:
        return []
``` 

Note: The computation time of this function is quite high due to the permutation calculation as permutations have a time complexity of O(n!), where n is the length of the input. You may have to improve this function if you are using it for larger sequences.
<|end|>


