Craft a minimization algorithm in C++ that specifically targets the reduction of expenditures in a financial plan optimization challenge. 
The upper bound of the cost is set as 500, and the elements of the budget encompass: [{expenditure: 100, particulars: ManuscriptPrinting}, {expenditure: 250, particulars: ManuscriptEditing}].
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Here's a simple C++ program outline for this problem. We'll use a greedy algorithm to solve it, which means we minimize on a per-step basis. The following program isn't complete (e.g., there's no main function), but it should provide an idea of how you could approach the problem.

```cpp
#define MAX_COST 500
#define NUM_PARTICULARS 2

#include<iostream>
#include<vector>

using namespace std;

struct FinancialPlan {
    int expenditure;
    string particulars;
};

int MinimizeExpenditure(vector<FinancialPlan>& budget) {
    int totalCost = 0;
    
    // sort the budget in increasing order of expenditure
    sort(budget.begin(), budget.end(), [](const FinancialPlan& x, const FinancialPlan& y) {
        return x.expenditure < y.expenditure;
    });

    for (const auto& item : budget) {
        // if adding expenditure does not exceed cost limit, add to totalCost
        if (totalCost + item.expenditure <= MAX_COST) {
            totalCost += item.expenditure;
        } else {
            // if expenditure exceeds cost limit, reduce the cost
            return totalCost;
        }
    }

    return totalCost;
}

int main() {
    vector<FinancialPlan> budget = { {100, "ManuscriptPrinting"}, {250, "ManuscriptEditing"} };

    int cost = MinimizeExpenditure(budget);
    cout << "The minimized cost is: " << cost << endl;

    return 0;
}
```

In this program, we first sort the budget in increasing order of expenditure. Then for each item in the sorted budget, we check if adding it to our total cost will exceed our limit (500). If it doesn't, we add it to our total cost; if it does, we return our current total cost. Note, "return" in this algorithm means to stop without finalizing the entire budget. Thus only the absolutely necessary costs are considered.
<|end|>


